<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Satisfied With Yugoslav Effort  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Clinton administration officials say they are  
satisfied that the Yugoslav military is making a sincere effort to 
meet Tuesday's deadline for emptying a swath of southern Kosovo of 
all soldiers and police. The territory includes a section of Kosovo 
being patrolled by American troops. It remained unclear how NATO 
would respond if it discovered Serb stragglers. ``They are making a 
strong effort to get them out,'' the Pentagon's chief spokesman, 
said Monday. NATO had said it would resume bombing Yugoslavia if 
the Serbs deliberately dragged their feet in leaving Kosovo, a 
province of Serbia. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Leave for Europe  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, leaving tonight for Europe,  
is joining with allies to launch a costly rebuilding plan for 
war-torn Kosovo and other trouble-plagued nations of southeast 
Europe. ``The coming months will be a period of return and 
reconstruction,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said 
Monday. European nations will bear the largest share of the 
financial burden of rebuilding, Albright said, because the United 
States absorbed the heaviest cost of the 78-day bombing campaign 
against Yugoslavia. She said that as of Monday, 13,000 to 15,000 
Serb forces have pulled out of Kosovo and 14,000 peacekeeping 
troops have begun to deploy. 

</P>
<P>
	South Korea Sinks North Korean Ship  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea's Defense Ministry says  
South Korean warships sank a North Korean torpedo boat after a 
10-minute exchange of gunfire in contested waters of the Yellow 
Sea. ``Our patrol boats fired 35mm guns and hit one'' of three 
torpedo boats, a Defense Ministry spokesman said. ``There is no 
word on casualties yet.'' Col. Hwang Dong-kyu, spokesman for the 
Joint Chiefs of Staff, said the three northern torpedo boats shot 
first. The gunfire happened only minutes before talks began in an 
effort to end the standoff, Seoul's Defense Ministry said. 

</P>
<P>
	Medical Helicopter Crashes in Ky.  
</P>
<P>
	JACKSON, Ky. (AP) -- A University of Kentucky medical helicopter  
crashed in eastern Kentucky late Monday, and a clinic spokeswoman 
said all four people aboard were killed. The victims included two 
pilots, a flight nurse and a paramedic, said Mary Margaret 
Colliver, a spokeswoman for the UK Hospital who cited information 
from state police. There were no patients aboard, she said. A state 
police dispatcher confirmed deaths aboard the helicopter but said 
he did not have details. Jackson is about 70 miles southeast of 
Lexington. 

</P>
<P>
	Panel Urges Nuclear Security Changes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An influential intelligence advisory panel  
told President Clinton Monday that his proposed security 
improvements for the Energy Department and nuclear labs fall short 
of what is needed to protect against nuclear thefts. The panel, 
asked by the president three months ago to closely examine security 
problems at the Energy Department, strongly recommended that 
nuclear programs be placed under a new agency either within the 
department or altogether independent. 

</P>
<P>
	Fund-Raiser Arraigned on Conspiracy Charge  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Democratic Party fund-raiser John Huang was  
arraigned Monday on a conspiracy charge as part of a plea bargain 
that was reached after he helped the government's campaign finance 
investigation. He is expected to plead guilty in federal court next 
Monday. Prosecutors are seeking a sentence of a year's probation, 
500 hours of community service, a $10,000 fine and a requirement 
that he continue cooperating with the government. Huang was charged 
with conspiracy to defraud the Federal Election Commission by 
helping raise $7,500 in donations and then reimbursing the 
individuals who provided the funds. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Rise Moderately  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose moderately in midday trading  
Tuesday, with the Nikkei gaining 28.25 points to hit 17,217.02 in 
early trading. 

</P>
<P>
	Brewers 5, Cubs 1  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Geoff Jenkins and Dave Nilsson homered, and  
Jeff Cirillo had two RBIs to lead the Milwaukee Brewers to a 5-1 
victory over the Chicago Cubs on Monday night. Sammy Sosa hit his 
NL-leading 22nd home run and extended his hitting streak to 17 
games as Chicago dropped its season-high fifth straight. Steve 
Woodard got the win, allowing one run and seven hits in 6 2-3 
innings. 

</P>
<P>
	Yankees 8, Rangers 2  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chili Davis made the most of his return from an  
interleague vacation, homering and driving in four runs in the New 
York Yankees' 8-2 win over the Texas Rangers on Monday night. 
Hideki Irabu allowed two runs and five hits in seven innings, 
allowing only a two-run homer to Juan Gonzalez. The Yankees have 
won 16 of the last 20 games against the Rangers, including a 
three-game sweep in last year's playoffs. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
