<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mergers Seen Key to Aerospace Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LE BOURGET, France (AP) -- European aerospace firms must  
consolidate to cut costs and compete more effectively with their 
American rivals, top officials from French and German companies 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	France's Aerospatiale Matra, itself the product of a merger, is  
seeking further linkups in Europe and in the United States. 
Meanwhile, DaimlerChrysler Aerospace believes the region has too 
many players and hopes to take a lead role in consolidating them. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies want to restructure Airbus Industrie, the  
four-nation passenger jet consortium and fierce rival of Boeing Co. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not stupid enough to keep a type of organization that  
will slow us down in the war we wage with Boeing,'' said Jean-Luc 
LaGardere, chairman of Aerospatiale's supervisory board, at a news 
conference at the Paris Air Show. 
</P>
<P>
	The show, being held at Le Bourget airfield north of the French  
capital, is the world's largest. 
</P>
<P>
	In a welcome boost to its business, Airbus said Monday it has  
received an order for 30 A-320 aircraft from Debis AirFinance, a 
Netherlands-based leasing company. Airbus will deliver the first 
aircraft in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger that created Aerospatiale Matra, France's No. 1  
aerospace conglomerate, was formally completed Friday, just hours 
after DaimlerChrysler Aerospace announced a plan to unite with CASA 
of Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	By merging with CASA, DaimlerChrysler will become the dominant  
shareholder in Airbus with a 42 percent stake. Aerospatiale and 
British Aerospace comprise 38 percent and 20 percent of the 
consortium, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Flagging demand for big civilian jets has exposed the need to  
reorganize Airbus, whose planes are assembled in France from 
components produced by each of the four national companies, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``All parties believe we really should improve the organization  
of Airbus ... to make it more efficient,'' Aerospatiale chairman 
Yves Michot told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The DaimlerChrysler-CASA deal took the European industry by  
surprise. Aerospatiale itself was hoping that the Spanish 
government would select it as a partner for CASA, but Michot tried 
to put a brave face on the merger, saying it won't ``destabilize'' 
the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	British Aerospace dismissed any negative impact on Airbus of the  
DaimlerChrysler-CASA merger. 
</P>
<P>
	``In many ways, it's easier to make decisions with three people  
sitting around a table than with four,'' said spokesman Simon 
Raynes. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler said there is no chance that it will dominate  
Airbus. The consortium was formed under statutes that require a 
consensus among all of its members, DaimlerChrysler spokesman 
Rainer Ohler said. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler supports centralizing Airbus' disparate  
operations within a single, more efficient corporate entity, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spurned by CASA, Aerospatiale expects that finding a new partner  
will be easier in Europe than in the United States, where laws 
controlling access to technologies with military applications are 
an obstacle, Michot said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe one day we can actually merge with an American company,  
but we shouldn't do this too hastily,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrylser sees better prospects across the Atlantic.  
Formed by a German-American merger of Chrysler Corp. and 
Daimler-Benz AG, the company has found that ``doors are quite 
open'' in the United States, Ohler said. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's biggest aviation opportunities lie in the United  
States, and an American acquisition or merger is one of the options 
DaimlerChrysler is evaluating, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
