<HEADLINE> Business Inventories Up 0.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Inventories at American businesses rose 0.2  
percent in April as sales edged down 0.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Too big a buildup in inventories can force manufacturers to cut  
production as businesses struggle to reduce the backlog of unsold 
goods. 
</P>
<P>
	However, even with the modest April rise, current inventory  
levels are lean in relation to sales as confident American 
consumers continue spending freely. 
</P>
<P>
	April's small decline in business sales, to $809.3 billion,  
followed a big 1.1 percent rise in March, the Commerce Department 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	That meant there were enough goods on shelves and backlots in  
April to last just 1.36 months at current levels of demand -- a good 
sign that U.S. manufacturers will have work to do in coming months, 
economists say. 
</P>
<P>
	The April inventory increase, to a seasonally adjusted $1.1  
trillion, added to a 0.5 percent increase in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Wholesalers' inventories rose 0.2 percent and retailers'  
inventories grew 0.7 percent in April. Manufacturers' stockpiles, 
meanwhile, fell 0.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales by retailers rose 0.4 percent while demand from  
wholesalers was unchanged. Manufacturers' sales dropped 0.4 
percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
