<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Livent's Executives Stepping Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- The two top executives of Livent Inc. plan to  
step down effective June 25, two weeks before the insolvent theater 
company heads into a bankruptcy sale hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Livent said Monday that Roy Furman will step down as chief  
executive and David Maisel will resign as president. 
</P>
<P>
	Rob Webster, now executive vice president, will succeed Furman  
as chief executive, Livent said. 
</P>
<P>
	Furman will continue as chairman of the company's board of  
directors and Webster will become a director. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes follow Livent's June 1 announcement that it had  
reached a $115-million deal to sell almost all of its assets to SFX 
Entertainment Inc. of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. bankruptcy court has set July 7 as the tentative date for  
a hearing to approve the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Livent filed for bankruptcy protection last November in Canada  
and the United States after the August 1998 discovery of what the 
U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission described as a ``pervasive 
eight-year fraudulent accounting scheme by the former senior 
management of Livent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations are denied by former Livent executives Garth  
Drabinsky and Myron Gottlieb of Toronto and have not been proven in 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	In a countersuit, Drabinsky has alleged there was an unlawful  
takeover conspiracy involving Furman, Maisel, Webster, Hollywood 
power broker Michael Ovitz and directors Scott Sperling of Thomas 
Lee, a U.S. investment company that owned part of Livent. 
</P>
<P>
	Webster has been responsible for overseeing the internal  
investigation into alleged accounting irregularities and the 
restatement of earnings. He has also overseen the bankruptcy 
process, including marketing of Livent's assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Webster joined Livent last July. Previously he was a partner in  
KPMG Peat Marwick's national U.S. mergers and acquisition practice, 
where he specialized in media and entertainment industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Livent's ``Fosse'' won the award for best Broadway musical at  
the recent Tony Awards. It also is the producer of ``Ragtime.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
