<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9:45 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Korean Ships Exchange Gunfire  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South and North Korean warships  
exchanged gunfire Tuesday in contested waters of the Yellow Sea 
only minutes before talks began in an effort to end the standoff, 
Seoul's Defense Ministry said. Col. Hwang Dong-kyu, spokesman for 
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said three North Korean ships shot first 
and their fire was returned by at least some of the eight South 
Korean ships patrolling the area. One North Korean ship was hit, 
with casulties unknown. One South Korean ship was hit by northern 
fire, but no casualties were reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian, U.S. Officials To Meet  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The stalemate between NATO troops and the  
Russian soldiers blocking their entrance into the Pristina airport 
in Kosovo has not adversely affected the peacekeeping mission as a 
whole, Clinton administration officials said. Secretary of State 
Madeline Albright said the Russians understood and accepted NATO's 
insistence on a unified command structure in Kosovo. Albright and 
Defense Secretary William Cohen made plans today to meet Russian 
officials to thrash out Moscow's disputed peacekeeping role in 
Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Serbs Withdraw With Fury  
</P>
<P>
	PEC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav forces withdrew from Kosovo's  
border region with Albania today, but not before a spree of 
shooting, burning, and alleged raping. Some citizens in the 
hard-hit city of Djakovica say Serb paramilitary troops went on a 
rampage there Saturday, after the peace deal and two days before 
their withdrawal. Masked fighters burned buildings and raped 
several women, said Binakaj Azgon, who said his daughter was among 
the women taken away. A tally of Djakovica's dead has yet to be 
compiled; a cemetery worker said he buried as many as 200 people 
slain in mass killings of up to 70 at a time. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Slams NRA, House on Guns  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Pressing for help in a fight for stricter gun  
laws, Vice President Al Gore told the nation's mayors today that he 
had underestimated the ability of the National Rifle Association to 
get its work done in Washington. ``Will we let the NRA call the 
shots in Washington or will we cross party lines to make our 
children safer?'' Gore said. The Republican-controlled House is 
expected to debate gun control proposals this week, with Democrats 
generally pressing for adoption of provisions the Senate approved 
last month, and the NRA fighting to water them down or eliminate 
them. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush: No Litmus Test on Abortion  
</P>
<P>
	NEW CASTLE, N.H. (AP) -- Supreme Court nominees will not have to  
pass any anti-abortion litmus test if he is elected president, 
George W. Bush said today. He also pledged to uphold the dignity of 
the presidency. Bush visited New Hampshire on a campaign swing for 
the GOP nomination. He said he was determined not to raise 
corporate and income taxes and eager to work with the 
Republican-led Congress. 

</P>
<P>
	ebay Stock Plunges After Outage  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Business was buzzing on Internet auction  
site eBay today, but that didn't prevent investors from pushing the 
company's stock down 18 percent as fallout continued from last 
week's 22-hour outage. Shares of eBay dropped $29.87 1/2 to $136 in 
trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market, the first trading day since 
eBay said it would refund fees for all active auctions from 
Thursday and Friday, costing it between $3 million to $5 million in 
second-quarter revenue. 

</P>
<P>
	Corpse Rides Subway for Five Hours  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A man got on a subway train at rush hour this  
morning, died, and his body rode the train for hours before 
passengers notified anyone about it, police said. The man, believed 
to be in his 40s, had no visible signs of a struggle or attack and 
no identification, police said. Police do not know where the man 
boarded the train, but believe he was dead for four to five hours. 
They speculate that no one noticed him because the train was so 
crowded and people in too much of a hurry. ``Do you know how many 
people sleep on the train during morning rush?'' subway rider Mario 
Licari said. ``Unless the guy slumps into me, I just leave him 
alone.'' 

</P>
