<HEADLINE> Novotna Will Play Wimbledon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Jana Novotna on Monday said she's recovered  
enough from a painful ankle sprain to defend her Wimbledon singles 
title next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to just be prepared ... to struggle and to fight,''  
Novotna said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old Czech star won't defend her Eastbourne  
championship this week to avoid re-injuring the right ankle she 
sprained when she collided with her partner, Natasha Zvereva, in 
the French Open doubles quarterfinals. She said she will play 
doubles at Eastbourne to get grasscourt preparation. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal, ultimately, after my sprain back in Paris, was to be  
able to play at Wimbledon,'' Novotna said in a telephone conference 
call Monday. ``Now my aim is to get better every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Novotna was taken off the court in Paris in a wheelchair after  
she and Zvereva both went to cover the same ball and collided. 
Novotna twisted her ankle when she stepped on Zvereva's foot. She 
said an MRI found a partial tear in one of her ligaments, but that 
the damage wasn't great enough to keep her from Wimbledon. 
</P>
<P>
	Novotna didn't play for eight days and underwent 10 to 12 days  
of ``intense therapy'' after the June 2 injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Novotna was seeded fifth for the June 21 tournament in rankings  
that came out Monday. She called the women's tournament a ``very 
open Wimbledon,'' but gave particular praise to French Open 
champion Steffi Graf, who upset top-ranked Martina Hingis in the 
finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we all pretty much know who has the best shot to win  
Wimbledon this year,'' Novotna said. ``Look at the French Open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said the injury, and her recent breakup with former doubles  
partner Hingis, hasn't hurt her opinion of doubles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, occasionally it happens that you don't get along anymore  
with your partner,'' Novotna said. But ``all the other benefits 
that you have from playing doubles are just incredible. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just helps you to pick up your game. It just gives you an  
extra practice,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Novotna and Zvereva are also playing doubles at Wimbledon.  
</P>
<P>
	Novotna also will defend her title at the A&AMP;P Classic in Mahwah,  
which begins July 12. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
