<DOCNO> APW19990614.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 16:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Heads to Europe on Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With NATO forces pouring into Kosovo,  
President Clinton will fly to Europe on Tuesday to join allies in 
signing a plan to rebuild war-torn southeast Europe and address 
``the larger imperative of establishing stability throughout the 
Balkans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Monday that the  
European nations will assume the lion's share of the financial 
burden of rebuilding, since the United States played the dominant 
role in the 78-day military campaign against the forces of Slobodan 
Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Departing late Tuesday, the president will fly overnight to  
Geneva to address the International Labor Organization on 
Wednesday. Clinton will speak in support of an accord to eradicate 
the worst forms of child labor. The measure is expected to be 
adopted by all 174 ILO members later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, the president will stop overnight in Paris for talks  
with French President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel 
Jospin. 
</P>
<P>
	From Paris, Clinton will travel to Cologne, Germany, for the  
annual summit of the world's seven wealthiest nations -- the United 
States, Germany, England, France, Italy, Canada and Japan -- and 
Russia. They will meet Friday through Sunday, discussing 
reconstruction of the Balkans, debt relief for the poorest nations 
and new global finance structures. 
</P>
<P>
	For the summit's first two days, Russia will be represented by  
Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin. President Boris Yeltsin will come 
in for the final day of talks Sunday and a private meeting with 
Clinton. National security adviser Sandy Berger said he was not 
sure why Yeltsin was not attending the first two days, speculating, 
``It could be a question of physical stamina.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said it was critical to bring the Balkans into the  
mainstream of Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``We and our Europeans allies have recognized, after our  
experience in Kosovo and earlier this decade in Bosnia, that 
isolated programs to assist individual countries in this region 
have been insufficient,'' Albright said. ``And we need to 
coordinate our resources and encourage real integration within the 
Balkans, throughout Europe and across the Atlantic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said the president ``will consult with his counterparts both  
on the immediate challenges there and on the larger imperative of 
establishing stability throughout the Balkans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Clinton has said that the West will not help Yugoslavia  
rebuild as long as Milosevic is in power. 
</P>
<P>
	After the summit ends, Clinton will meet Monday with leaders of  
the European Union in Bonn, where discussions on the Balkans will 
continue. Afterward, he will fly to Slovenia for an overnight stay. 
Slovenia, Bosnia and Croatia broke away from Yugoslavia after the 
fall of communism. Slovenia now is a leading candidate to join 
NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	Berger said Slovenia has made considerable progress politically  
and economically in terms of democracy and openness. Clinton's 
schedule calls for him to return home from Slovenia. However, White 
House aides are exploring a possible stop in Macedonia to visit 
refugees or in Aviano, Italy, to salute American forces that 
carried out both bombing runs and relief efforts in the Balkans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
