<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Down on Good Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures retreated early today  
on the Chicago Board of Trade as favorable weekend growing weather 
boosted the chances for bumper fall production. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors continued to bail out of the market amid expectations  
that weekend rains and forecasts for milder temperatures this week 
will prove ideal to early crop development. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers this year planted record soybean acreage and large  
tracts of corn, boosting chances of record production. While export 
demand is expected to increase slightly because of a partial 
recovery to the Asian economy, market participants are worried 
about large surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 1 1/4 cents to $2.55 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn fell 2 1/2 cents to $2.14 3/4 a bushel; July oats fell 2 1/2 cents to 
$1.21 1/2 a bushel; July soybeans fell 5 cents to $4.65 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle futures were higher on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while hog futures fell. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .48 cent to 65.50 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .65 cent to 78.60 cents a pound; July lean hogs 
fell .40 cent to 53.55 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 1.22 
cents to 45.95 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
