<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Decathlete Missing, Feared Drowned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- A college decathlete was missing and  
feared drowned after a raft capsized in the Spokane River. 
</P>
<P>
	The missing athlete was identified as Dusty Lane, a former  
Cashmere resident and top decathlete at the Community Colleges of 
Spokane. Lane, a sophomore, recently accepted a full athletics 
scholarship to the University of Alabama for next year. 
</P>
<P>
	He recently broke the Community Colleges of Spokane's decathlon  
record set by Dan O'Brien, who attended the school and is the 
defending Olympic champion and world record holder. 
</P>
<P>
	Lane, 22, was rafting with three friends Sunday in Riverside  
State Park northwest of Spokane when the raft capsized in the 
Spokane River's turbulent waters, Spokane County sheriff's Sgt. 
David Fray said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the rafters made it to shore near the Bowl and Pitcher,  
a rough turn in the river favored by kayakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Two rescue boats and a helicopter searched for three hours  
Sunday before the search was called off due to darkness. 
</P>
<P>
	No searching was done Monday, in part because of the possibility  
that Lane's body might be stuck on the river bottom, sheriff's 
spokesman Deputy David Reagan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputies will use personal watercraft to search the river  
Tuesday, Reagan said. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the rafters had been wearing life jackets, and the group  
had been drinking before the accident, Fray said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
