<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	S. Korea Sinks N. Korean Ship  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korean warships sank a North  
Korean torpedo boat Tuesday in contested waters of the Yellow Sea 
after a 10-minute exchange of gunfire, South Korea's Defense 
Ministry said. ``Our patrol boats fired 35mm guns and hit one'' of 
three torpedo boats, Koo Bon-hak, a Defense Ministry spokesman 
said. ``The North Korean ship later sank. There is no word on 
casualties yet.'' Col. Hwang Dong-kyu, spokesman for the Joint 
Chiefs of Staff, said the three North Korean torpedo boats shot 
first and their fire was returned by at least some of the eight 
South Korean ships patrolling the area. The gunfire happened only 
minutes before talks began in an effort to end the standoff, 
Seoul's Defense Ministry said. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia's Kosovo Role To Be Explored  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and  
Defense Secretary William Cohen made plans to meet Russian 
officials to thrash out Moscow's disputed peacekeeping role. 
Albright told a White House news conference a range of issues would 
be discussed at the meeting in Helsinki, Finland, including 
Russia's continued encampment at the airport in the Kosovo capital 
of Pristina. Despite the airport stalemate, ``there has not been 
long-term damage from this'' to U.S.-Russian relations, Albright 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Panel Urges Nuke Security Changes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An influential intelligence advisory panel  
told President Clinton today that his proposed security 
improvements for the Energy Department and nuclear labs fall short 
of what is needed to protect against nuclear thefts. The panel, 
asked by the president three months ago to closely examine security 
problems at the Energy Department, strongly recommended that 
nuclear programs be placed under a new agency either within the 
department or altogether independent. 

</P>
<P>
	Huang Arraigned on Conspiracy Charge  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Democratic Party fund-raiser John Huang was  
arraigned today on a conspiracy charge as part of a plea bargain 
that was reached after he helped the government's campaign finance 
investigation. He is expected to plead guilty in federal court next 
Monday. Prosecutors are seeking a sentence of a year's probation, 
500 hours of community service, a $10,000 fine and a requirement 
that he continue cooperating with the government. Huang was charged 
with conspiracy to defraud the Federal Election Commission by 
helping raise $7,500 in donations and then reimbursing the 
individuals who provided the funds. 

</P>
<P>
	ebay Stock Plunges After Outage  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Business was buzzing on Internet auction  
site eBay today, but that didn't prevent investors from pushing the 
company's stock down 18 percent as fallout continued from last 
week's 22-hour outage. Shares of eBay dropped $29.87 1/2 to $136 in 
trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market, the first trading day since 
eBay said it would refund fees for all active auctions from 
Thursday and Friday, costing it between $3 million to $5 million in 
second-quarter revenue. 

</P>
<P>
	Book: Clinton Excuses Irked Lawyer  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One of President Clinton's lawyers hit the  
roof when he heard the president might argue that he was truthful 
when he denied having a sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky 
because oral sex did not fit the definition, a new book by Bob 
Woodward says. ``You can't do this,'' the book quotes lawyer Robert 
Bennett as telling a Clinton adviser. Woodward, a Washington Post 
reporter, will have his book ``Shadow: Five Presidents and the 
Legacy of Watergate,'' released tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Gannett Issues Ethical Guidelines  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Public distrust of the media and reader  
concerns about fair play and accuracy prompted The Gannett Co. Inc. 
today to announce ethical guidelines for all 73 of its daily 
newspapers. The news-gathering ethics state that newspapers should 
seek and report the truth in a truthful way, serve the public 
interest, exercise fair play, maintain independence and act with 
integrity. The decision to write them was prompted in part by a 
rising number of lawsuits challenging news gathering methods. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise Moderately  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose moderately in early trading  
Tuesday, with the Nikkei gaining 62.37 points to hit 17,251.19 in 
early trading. On Wall Street on Monday, the Dow industrials closed 
up 72.82 to end at 10,563.33. 

</P>
<P>
	Lakers Hope To Lock Up Jackson Deal  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Lakers reportedly are offering Phil  
Jackson a four-year, $24 million contract to become their coach. 
Lakers executive vice present Jerry West and general manager Mitch 
Kupchak spoke with Jackson by telephone today after Jackson 
returned from a fishing trip in Alaska. ``The conversation went 
very well,'' team spokesman John Black said. An announcement is 
expected this week. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  

  	   	
</P>
