<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Standard Planned for E-Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Some of the nation's largest computer companies,  
credit card companies and retailers are expected to announce today 
they have agreed on an Internet commerce standard that will make 
online shopping easier and quicker. 
</P>
<P>
	The standard evolves around the concept of an ``electronic  
wallet'' that allows consumers to input their personal data once, 
instead of re-entering the information for every transaction. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Corp., Sun Microsystems Inc., Compaq Computer Corp.,  
America Online Inc. and IBM Corp. are set to endorse a new 
technical format called electronic-commerce modeling language, or 
ECML, The New York Times and The Wall Street Journal reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The common format is also backed by Visa USA Inc., MasterCard  
International Inc. and American Express Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The software firms will use the common language to store a  
consumer's name, address and credit card number in a secure Web 
browser or on a server on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Retailers that agree to use the standard will be able to read  
the stored information and share it with others, eventually 
providing one-click checkout. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a Jupiter Communications survey cited by the Times,  
27 percent of potential online buyers reported earlier this year 
that they abandoned their orders because of the many steps it took 
to complete a purchase. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
