<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Abortion Waiting Period OK'd in Mich </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Women will have to wait 24 hours before  
obtaining an abortion under a compromise signed Monday by Gov. John 
Engler. 
</P>
<P>
	The Legislature passed a law in 1993 requiring a waiting period  
for abortion, but a lawsuit attempting to overturn the law had 
prevented it from taking effect. 
</P>
<P>
	The state and a coalition of more than 20 abortion clinics  
agreed to a settlement that requires clinics to give women written 
material about abortion at least 24 hours before the procedure is 
performed. 
</P>
<P>
	The materials discuss the risks and complications of abortion  
and show detailed drawings of the development of a fetus. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been six long years, and this is getting actual  
information to women. This information doesn't sway people one way 
or the other,'' Department of Community Health spokeswoman Geralyn 
Lasher said. ``This isn't information that Right to Life is putting 
together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the settlement, a doctor who performs an abortion without  
a waiting period can be charged with a misdemeanor unless the 
abortion meets the federal definition of a medical emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement allows the reading materials to be sent by mail,  
fax, or electronic mail. Abortion clinics wanted that change to 
prevent women from having to travel twice to an abortion clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	Margie Kelly, a spokeswoman for the Center for Reproductive Law  
and Policy in New York, said the change ``minimized the harm to 
women's health and protected as much as possible a woman's right to 
have an abortion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Engler had already signed the law, which will now go into effect  
in 90 days. A federal judge was expected to approve the settlement 
Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
