<HEADLINE> Palladium Futures Fall Sharply  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Palladium futures fell sharply Monday on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange amid reports of heavy sales. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, grain and soybeans advanced, while cocoa  
futures retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium prices tumbled as market participants reacted to  
suggested that Tiger Management, a large hedge fund, is dumping its 
positions in the industrial metal. Such a move could signal heavy 
physical selling is on the way, although the company denied it had 
sold any of its positions. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium prices have seesawed for months as speculators bet on  
when Russia will resume large-scale shipments of the metal to 
Western manufacturers, particularly Japan. The metal is used 
heavily in automobiles and electronics, but large shipments have 
been absent since December amid economic turmoil in Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium for September delivery fell $8 to $336.80 an ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures finished mostly higher on the Chicago  
Board of Trade, 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures led the gains, moving higher on reports of heavy  
commercial buying, which may indicate export demand is on the rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices also were supported by forecasts for hot, dry weather to  
develop later this week in the Plains. That could scorch crops in 
areas where harvesting has been delayed by heavy recent rains. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans shrugged off early weakness tied to favorable  
growing weather on the rally in wheat prices. 
</P>
<P>
	July wheat rose 5 3/4 cents to $2.63 3/4 a bushel; July corn rose 1  
cent to $2.18 1/4 a bushel; July oats fell 1 cent to $1.23 a bushel; 
July soybeans rose 1 1/4 cents to $4.71 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures tumbled on the Board of Trade of the City of New  
York amid expectations candy manufacturers have secured enough 
supplies to last until the next West African harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures had risen sharply in previous sessions as supplies  
out of Ghana and Ivory Coast, the two largest cocoa growers, 
dwindled. That helped support a market that has been under pressure 
by a world awash in supplies and weaker demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa is used mainly in the manufacture of chocolate.  
</P>
<P>
	July cocoa fell $34 to $1,063 a ton.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
