<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise Moderately / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was lower against the yen in early  
trading Tuesday on profit-taking, despite warnings by Japanese 
finance officials. Tokyo stocks rose moderately. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.56 yen in early trading, down 0.10 yen  
from late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 
120.62 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 62.37  
points, or 0.36 percent, to 17,251.19 in the first 30 minutes of 
trading. On Monday, the index lost 9.73 points, or 0.06 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong words from Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa and  
other officials that they would take action against sudden 
dollar-yen moves briefly sent the U.S. currency back up to its New 
York levels. But it soon edged back down on profit-taking, traders 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most market participants remain reluctant to take new positions  
in the wake of the Bank of Japan's aggressive dollar-buying binge 
in Monday's Asian session, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisuke Sakakibara, Japan's vice finance minister for  
international affairs, confirmed Monday that the Bank of Japan 
intervened in the currency market to prevent an excessively fast 
strengthening of the yen, which is feared could wreck economic 
recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen is a threat to the exporters that power Japan's  
economy because it makes their goods more expensive overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakakibara declined to say how large the intervention was, but  
traders estimated the central bank spent as much as dlrs 10 billion 
and flooded the market with yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, early buying was led by foreign investors,  
said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager of the stock division at Tokyo 
Securities. He said that domestic institutional investors remained 
cautious about the direction of the economy and the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower-priced shares in materials manufacturers, such as paper  
and steelmakers, were among the gainers early Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York overnight, the Dow Jones industrial average gained  
72.82 points to close at 10,563.33. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 1.59 points, or 0.12 percent, to 1,382.86. The 
TOPIX gained 0.59 points, negligible in percentage terms, the 
previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies Monday, the euro was traded at 125.56 yen,  
down from 126.49 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond dropped to 1.590 percent from 1.635 percent Monday, driving 
its price up to 98.36 from 97.97. 
</P>
<P>
 *(may-dj) 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
