<HEADLINE> Coles To Skip IOC Meeting in Seoul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Australian IOC member Phil Coles has  
decided not to attend international Olympic meetings in Seoul this 
week, officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles was forced to resign Monday from the board of the Sydney  
2000 organizing committee, but escaped expulsion from the 
International Olympic Committee for alleged ethical misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles was expected to arrive in Seoul on Tuesday to attend the  
109th IOC session beginning Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But IOC and Australian Olympic officials said Coles decided to  
stay in Sydney to avoid a media frenzy in Seoul that would distract 
from the meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC executive board Monday reprimanded Coles for ``serious  
negligence'' in writing notes about his colleagues, some not very 
flattering. 
</P>
<P>
	The board said the notes written by Coles and his companion,  
Patricia Rosenbrock, did not in themselves ``constitute an 
offense,'' but that Coles was negligent in allowing them to become 
public. 
</P>
<P>
	The board barred Coles from serving on IOC commissions for two  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Last March, Coles received a severe warning for his role in the  
Salt Lake City vote-buying scandal. 
  	   	
</P>
