<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU May Delay Ban on Some U.S. Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union will likely delay  
for six months a proposed ban on U.S. beef which it threatened to 
impose because of evidence beef certified as hormone free may 
include growth hormones outlawed in the EU. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigel Gardner, a spokesman for the EU executive Commission, said  
Monday an EU veterinary committee meeting Tuesday, when the ban is 
due to go into place, will likely agree to postpone the ban until 
Dec. 15. Tests on certified hormone-free beef imports would 
continue however to ensure they are safe, Gardner said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said ``a lot of progress'' had been made in ongoing talks  
between the EU and the United States to try and resolve the 
transatlantic dispute, one of many trade tiffs between the two 
sides. 
</P>
<P>
	EU imports of U.S. beef certified as hormone-free amount to an  
estimated 7,000 metric tons a year and are worth an estimated $20 
million-$30 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	A ban on hormone-free beef would effectively mean a total EU ban  
on U.S. beef imports because the EU already bans imports of 
hormone-treated beef from the U.S. and all other trade partners. 
That ban, imposed in 1989, is based on fears that hormone-treated 
beef can cause cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is threatening to slap $202 million in tariffs  
on European imports because the EU ignored a World Trade 
Organization order to drop the ban on hormone-treated American beef 
imports by May 13. Canada has threatened sanctions on trade worth 
$51 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU argues it wants to maintain the ban until the end of the  
year, when it expects to complete scientific tests to determine 
whether the hormones are safe. The United States says there is no 
evidence of health risks from the beef. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten days ago, the WTO set up an arbitration panel to assess the  
losses incurred by the United States and Canada because of the EU 
ban on hormone-treated beef. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel must report back by mid-July. At that point, the  
United States and Canada will be entitled to slap punitive 100 
percent duties against EU products ranging from chocolate to 
mineral water to offset losses incurred by the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	The tariffs would double the price of the targeted products and  
make them prohibitively expensive for American consumers. It would 
also spell possible economic ruin for European manufacturers 
involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 90 percent of the beef produced in the United States and  
Canada uses hormones approved by the regulatory U.S. Food and Drug 
Administration to make cattle grow faster and bigger. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
