<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak Trains Return to Oklahoma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARDMORE, Okla. (AP) -- Twenty years after the last passenger  
train left Oklahoma, Amtrak rolled back into the state on Monday 
with daily service between Oklahoma City and Fort Worth, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad to see it come back. We've missed it,'' said  
90-year-old Pauline Anderson Foster, one of hundreds of people who 
turned out along the tracks in this town just north of the Texas 
state line to catch a glimpse of the gleaming silver train, called 
the Heartland Flyer. 
</P>
<P>
	State leaders had lobbied for years for the return of train  
service, which was discontinued because of federal budget cuts in 
1979. The result is a collaborative effort between the state and 
Amtrak, with Oklahoma leasing the track, trains and crew and Amtrak 
operating the train. 
</P>
<P>
	The Heartland Flyer will allow travelers from Oklahoma City to  
connect in Fort Worth with trains that serve Chicago, San Antonio, 
Los Angeles, New Orleans and Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 600 people were on hand for train's arrival at the old  
Frisco depot in Ardmore, where Boy Scouts stood with American 
flags, a band played ``Oklahoma!'' and vendors hawked hot dogs and 
hamburgers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a first-rate train standing on a track in a  
first-rate city,'' Gov. Frank Keating declared. 
</P>
<P>
	Burlington Northern Santa Fe owns the tracks and uses them to  
deliver coal, grain and other freight. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma is spending $23 million, some of which will go toward  
rail and signal improvements to that the train speed can be 
increased to 90 mph, shortening the 4 1/2-hour trip along the 180-mile 
route. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma's venture with Amtrak isn't unique. Eleven other states  
-- California, Illinois, Michigan, Missouri, New York, North 
Carolina, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Vermont, Washington and Wisconsin -- 
have created similar passenger train routes along existing railroad 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Amtrak has not made a profit since Congress created it in 1971  
to take over passenger operations of private railroads. Last year, 
however, it topped $1 billion in revenue for the first time, 
propelled by the best ridership in a decade and its best on-time 
performance in 13 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Only five states are without Amtrak service -- Alaska, Hawaii,  
Maine, Wyoming and South Dakota. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
