<DOCNO> APW19990614.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 12:00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Demotes Delegate After Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Olympic leaders have demoted one of  
their most popular colleagues after giving him one last chance -- 
for a second time -- to save his seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Phil Coles, a former Olympic kayaker from Australia known as the  
``Bondi Battler,'' was allowed to remain on the International 
Olympic Committee on Monday while being forced off the organizing 
committee for next year's Summer Games in his hometown of Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC executive board also stripped Coles of most of his  
official duties on the international panel and barred him from 
serving on commissions for two years for writing notes about his 
colleagues, some not very flattering. 
</P>
<P>
	In reprimanding Coles for ``serious negligence,'' the board  
hinted that one more infraction would bring his expulsion, familiar 
language in Coles' case. 
</P>
<P>
	Last March, an IOC investigation into the Salt Lake bribery  
scandal found Coles received excessive travel and other perks from 
Utah bidders. It slapped him with a ``most serious of warnings'' 
and said ``such repeated lack of judgment would expose him to 
expulsion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The board said the notes written by Coles and his companion,  
Patricia Rosenbrock, did not in themselves ``constitute an 
offense,'' but that Coles was negligent in allowing them to become 
public. 
</P>
<P>
	They came to light after reportedly winding up with Salt Lake's  
successful 2002 Winter Games bid. Coles and Rosenbrock denied 
giving them to Salt Lake, but the executive board said ``merely to 
read such notes makes it reasonable to believe that the person 
writing them intended them for Salt Lake City.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``These are extremely severe (sanctions), just short of  
expulsion,'' IOC director general Francois Carrard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrard said there ``has never been talk of corruption in  
connection with Mr. Coles,'' and there was no suggestion the Salt 
Lake committee paid him for the notes, which detail the likes and 
dislikes of dozens of IOC members and suggest how some might vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Before leaving Australia for the IOC session, Coles said his  
resignation was forced by Sydney Olympic politics and hoped that 
the ``exhausting and nightmarish experience'' was finally over. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC gave Coles an ultimatum -- quit the Sydney organizing  
committee or be forced out -- and officials said Coles' seat on the 
IOC was never threatened. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Sydney Morning Herald reported Tuesday that a special  
investigation by executive board members Anita DeFrantz, Marc 
Hodler and Keba M'Baye found the dossiers were ``not in keeping 
with the integrity of the IOC'' and warranted expulsion. 
</P>
<P>
	The paper, which did not identify its sources, said that  
position split the full 11-member board and that two powerful 
members -- vice president Dick Pound of Canada and Kim Un-yong of 
South Korea -- refused to consider an expulsion recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound, who headed the original IOC investigation of corruption,  
has been a friend of Coles for three decades, while Kim also 
received a ``most serious'' warning in the Salt Lake inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Although his case has since been closed, Kim has taken pains to  
assure that the IOC general assembly that opens Thursday with him 
as host runs smoothly and focuses on the election of the host city 
for the 2006 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber denied that the  
three-member panel had originally recommended Coles be expelled. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was absolutely never mentioned that he should be expelled  
from the IOC,'' he said. ``I can categorically deny that he was 
ever recommended for expulsion from the IOC.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carrard said the IOC decision was taken by the executive board  
Sunday. He said Coles notified the IOC of his resignation in a 
phone call Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Morning Herald, again without identifying its sources, said  
Coles called IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch to try to arrange 
a meeting to ``sort something out,'' but that Samaranch promptly 
handed the phone to Carrard, who told Coles the deal was final. 
</P>
<P>
	The 67-year-old Coles has served on the IOC since 1982. He will  
lose his posts on the marketing and radio and television 
commissions, but he will continue to attend IOC meetings, vote in 
the election of Olympic host cities and attend the Sydney Games as 
an official IOC delegate. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles had temporarily stepped aside from Sydney organizing  
committee in February after being implicated in the Salt Lake 
vote-buying case. He was later stripped of his role in organizing 
the Olympic torch relay in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizing committee chief Michael Knight and other Australian  
Olympic officials had demanded that Coles leave the committee 
altogether, claiming the scandal was detracting from the games and 
scaring sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrard said Coles needed to have a ``perfect working  
relationship'' with the Sydney committee and his resignation 
``contributed to an easing of tension.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Australian executive board member Kevan Gosper said, ``I  
sincerely hope this closes a very unfortunate chapter. I think Phil 
Coles did the right thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pound said Coles had ``become a distraction'' for the Sydney  
organizing committee. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sydney, Coles said Knight was behind the move.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's been quite an exhausting and nightmarish experience and  
there has been an orchestrated move to discredit me and have me 
removed,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
