<DOCNO> APW19990614.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 10:10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Virus Continues To Spread </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Computer support lines were overwhelmed today  
with calls reporting new outbreaks of a software virus that spreads 
not only by e-mail, but through shared files on a network. 
</P>
<P>
	Dashing hopes that Worm.Explore.Zip might be contained more  
quickly than the recent Melissa outbreak, a leading antivirus team 
warned that the new file-destroying bug may be more virulent than 
first thought. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the primary means of infection seemed to be through a  
friendly e-mail that tricks the recipient into opening an attached 
file, uncaging Worm.Explore.Zip. 
</P>
<P>
	But in addition to ruining files stored on an individual  
computer, the virus apparently ``worms'' its way into other 
computers linked to the same network server. 
</P>
<P>
	``Further analysis has shown that, once installed, the program  
may also behave as a worm, and it may be able to propagate itself, 
without any human interaction, to other networked machines,'' the 
Computer Emergency Response Team at Carnegie Mellon University in 
Pittsburgh said in a statement on its Website. 
</P>
<P>
	Although nervous calls to computer support lines dropped off  
sharply over the weekend, a support technician for the software 
maker Network Associates said this morning's call volume was even 
heavier than on Thursday and Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Bureau of Investigation was trying to track down the  
author of the virus, but the agency declined to provide any updates 
on the probe over the weekend. It took only days earlier this 
spring for authorities to trace the digital footprints of Melissa 
and the Chernobyl virus that struck in late April. 
</P>
<P>
	The virus, first detected in Israel about a week ago, began  
spreading rapidly on Thursday and Friday, infecting computer 
systems at several big corporations including AT&AMP;T, Boeing, General 
Electric and even Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Worm.Explore.Zip targets computers using Microsoft Windows  
operating systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The virus arrives in a person's e-mail box as a timely reply  
from an acquaintance, inviting the recipient to open an attached 
file that will unleash a two-pronged attack: It spreads by sending 
a copy of itself to the address of any arriving e-mail and destroys 
files stored on a person's machine, including those created by the 
popular programs Microsoft Word and Excel. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
