<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing: $1.38 Trillion on New Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LE BOURGET, France (AP) -- Boeing expects airlines to invest  
$1.38 trillion on new commercial airplanes during the next 20 years 
with the largest amount -- more than $570 billion -- going for 
intermediate, twin-aisle airplanes, such as the 767 and 777. 
</P>
<P>
	Single-aisle airplanes are a close second, with regional jets,  
747 and larger airplanes accounting for the smallest dollar 
investments, according to the 1999 Boeing Current Market Outlook, 
released today at the Paris Air Show. 
</P>
<P>
	A trend toward more non-stop flights between more cities will  
drive airlines to invest 87 percent of their airplane dollars in 
regional and single-aisle airplanes, such as 717s, 737s and 757s, 
and long-range twin-aisle jets smaller than the 747, said Randy 
Baseler, vice president of marketing for the Boeing Commercial 
Airplanes Group. 
</P>
<P>
	The outlook, considered the leading industry forecast of  
worldwide air travel growth and new-airplane demand, predicts: 
</P>
<P>
	--The world's commercial jetliner fleet will double to 28,425  
airplanes by 2018. 
</P>
<P>
	--Of the 20,150 airplanes to be delivered over the next two  
decades, nearly three-fourths will be regional and single-aisle 
airplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Only 930 of the total deliveries will be in the 747 and larger  
category, and less than 40 percent of these will be 500-plus seat 
airplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseler said the projections are driven by annual worldwide  
travel growth of 4.7 percent, and the anticipated replacement of 
more than 4,300 airplanes in today's fleet of 12,580 airplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the forecast, Latin America is the fastest-growing  
air-travel market, with traffic projected to increase by 6.9 
percent per year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Asian economic crisis reduced that region's near-term  
traffic rates, but annual growth of 6.3 percent will more than 
triple the Asia-Pacific region's traffic by 2018, the forecast 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Growth in the largest and most established market, North  
America, is about 3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseler pointed to the Pacific and Europe-Asia markets as  
offering numerous opportunities for new routes best served by 
intermediate-size, twin-aisle airplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compared to the North Atlantic network, U.S. hub cities and  
major European gateways are linked to relatively few destinations 
in Asia,'' Baseler said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As more liberal bilateral and 'open skies' agreements are  
signed, and 777s and similar airplanes offer increased range, we 
see tremendous opportunities for international market fragmentation 
-- more frequent flights using airplanes smaller than 747s,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report calls for 4,400 intermediate, twin-aisle airplanes to  
be delivered during the next 20 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
