<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-U.N. Chief Highlights Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Former U.N. Secretary-General Boutros  
Boutros-Ghali tried to highlight Monday some successful instances 
of cooperation with the United States, downplaying in person the 
criticism of Washington that he unleashed in his new memoirs. 
</P>
<P>
	The two areas of cooperation he offered reporters, including  
U.N. operations in Mozambique and El Salvador, are not found in the 
book, ``Unvanquished: A U.S.-U.N. Saga.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boutros-Ghali told a news conference sponsored by the Overseas  
Press Club that his editor excised those chapters because they made 
the book too long. 
</P>
<P>
	And the other instances of successful U.S.-U.N. relations that  
he mentioned, including five international conferences and 
peacekeeping missions in Cambodia and Haiti, make up only a small 
part of the 352-page memoir. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall tone of the book, and what is highlighted on the  
bookflap, is that the United States used the United Nations as an 
extension of its own foreign policy and made it a scapegoat for its 
own indecisive policies in Somalia, Bosnia, and Rwanda. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington campaigned to make Boutros-Ghali the first U.N. chief  
to be denied a second term, despite backing from virtually all 
other U.N. member states. 
</P>
<P>
	At the unveiling ceremony U.N. headquarters, Boutros-Ghali's  
successor, Kofi Annan, praised the Egyptian intellectual for having 
steadied the United Nations during his 1992-96 term, when the world 
around it was suddenly changing with the end of the Cold War. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the picture of a man with the courage to stick by his  
decisions, and with the fortitude to stand by his convictions,'' 
Annan said before a large gathering in the lobby of the U.N. 
Secretariat building. 
</P>
<P>
	Boutros-Ghali, currently living in Paris as secretary-general of  
the International Organization of the Francophonie, an association 
of 52 countries that promotes the French language, appeared 
genuinely happy to be back, warmly greeting old friends and 
colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	At the press club briefing, though, Boutros-Ghali acknowledged  
that he felt he was made a scapegoat for Washington immediately 
after leaving office in 1996. He said he had since realized that 
such risks come with civil service. 
</P>
<P>
	But Boutros-Ghali noted that he was at least allowed to live a  
free life. 
</P>
<P>
	``So at least this is the advantage to be living in a real  
democracy, that you can just write a book like this book,'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
