<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Consider Retroactive Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide  
whether people suspected of sexually assaulting children can be 
prosecuted under a Texas law enacted after they allegedly committed 
the crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said it will hear arguments by a man convicted of  
assaulting his stepdaughter. He argues that applying the new law 
retroactively to his case violates the Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott L. Carmell was convicted in a Denton County court in  
January 1997 of multiple counts of indecency with a child, 
aggravated sexual assault and sexual assault against his 
stepdaughter. He was sentenced to life in prison on the aggravated 
sexual assault convictions and 20 years on the other counts. 
</P>
<P>
	The sexual assault allegedly occurred in June 1992, when his  
stepdaughter was 14. Under Texas law at the time, a conviction for 
assaulting someone age 14 or older could not be supported unless 
the alleged victim told a third person about the offense within six 
months. She told her mother of the alleged assault in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The stepdaughter testified that Carmell had ``married'' her in a  
mock ceremony two days after the first incident. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, the law was changed so that no time limit was required  
for a complaint by any alleged victim under age 18. The judge 
relied on the 1993 law during Carmell's trial. 
</P>
<P>
	A Texas appeals court upheld Carmell's conviction, rejecting his  
argument that use of the 1993 law violated the Constitution's 
prohibition against retroactive laws. The state court said the new 
law was a rule of procedure that did not increase punishment or 
change the elements of the offense. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal granted review today, Carmell argued on his own  
behalf that the use of the 1993 law ``changed the rules of evidence 
against the accused to require less proof to convict him and ... 
deprived him of an acquittal that he would have otherwise been 
entitled to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said the 1993 law did not change the elements of the  
offense, but involved the type of evidence required for a 
conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Carmell vs. Texas, 98-7540.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
