<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 14:50:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blood Vessel Caused Dierker Seizure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The condition afflicting Houston Astros manager Larry Dierker  
stems from abnormal connections of arteries with veins in the 
brain. 
</P>
<P>
	Known as arteriovenous malformation, it affects about 2 percent  
of Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Occasionally, these tangled masses of blood vessels can cause  
seizures or bleeding into the brain, either a sudden hemorrhage or 
a slow leak, said Dr. Rafael Tamargo, co-director of Johns Hopkins 
University's division of cerebrovascular neurosurgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Treatment has to be tailored to the precise kind of  
arteriovenous malformation, or AVM, that a patient has -- 
particularly its size and location in the brain. 
</P>
<P>
	With surgery, doctors can remove the AVM. They use brain scans  
to pinpoint exactly where it is. All the blood vessels involved in 
the mass must be removed, ``or it will continue to pose a threat,'' 
Tamargo said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said patients who are good candidates for surgery have a very  
high cure rate, about 97 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Large AVMs may require a procedure before surgery called  
embolization. Using a catheter, doctors snake inside the blood 
vessels feeding the mass and inject a glue to close part of the 
AVM, so that surgery to remove the mass is easier. 
</P>
<P>
	Some doctors also are using ``stereotactic radiosurgery,'' also  
known as a ``gamma knife'' surgery, to focus radiation directly 
onto the AVM and thus destroy it. This radiosurgery is reserved for 
very small AVMs, or those that are in a part of the brain not 
conducive to surgery, Tamargo said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
