<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate To Move on Medical Privacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate is set to move ahead on protecting  
the privacy of medical records, but after months of talks, major 
disagreement remains over patients' ability to sue for improper 
disclosure of their personal information. 
</P>
<P>
	There is broad agreement over the main point of the legislation,  
which would establish the first federal right to privacy over 
medical records. While many states have privacy laws, freely 
distributing someone's medical records is not against any federal 
law. 
</P>
<P>
	A vote in the Senate Health, Education, Labor and Pensions  
Committee is set for Tuesday, but even after months of talks, 
significant differences remain, and the chances for a bipartisan 
agreement seemed slim Monday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar dispute divides Republicans and Democrats over patient  
rights in dealing with HMOs and other managed care plans, with many 
Democrats wanting to let patients sue their insurance companies if 
care is denied. Most Republicans oppose allowing such lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	The privacy debate is being driven by an August deadline. If  
Congress does not act by then, a law they passed in 1996 requires 
the Clinton administration to write its own regulations governing 
privacy. Critics of the administration's approach would prefer that 
Congress resolve the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt., the committee's chairman, has been  
trying to get broad support for a bill, hoping to avoid the 
partisan fighting that has dominated the HMO debate. His committee 
approved an HMO bill with no Democratic support. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffords has tried to balance Democrats, who want to give  
patients broad privacy rights, and Republicans, who want to be sure 
that businesses are not hampered by an overly strict law. 
</P>
<P>
	He has already twice postponed the committee vote on the privacy  
issue, and there were rumors Monday that it might be postponed 
again if a deal could not be reached on two outstanding issues: the 
right to sue and the privacy rights of minors. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee spokesman Joe Karpinski said he was still optimistic,  
saying, ``Some people are just pessimists and others have a sunny 
disposition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But there are major hurdles to overcome.  
</P>
<P>
	Democrats will not support the bill as written, said Jim Manley,  
spokesman for Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., the committee's top 
Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	On the right to sue, Jeffords originally included language more  
acceptable to Democrats. But then conservative Republicans balked, 
led by Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala. So Jeffords tightened the 
provision to cap damages for pain and suffering at $50,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would require plaintiffs to prove in court that  
their records were released willfully and intentionally, a high 
standard. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats are also angry at a provision that would give parents  
the right to see their children's medical records, even if the 
child sought medical attention independently. 
</P>
<P>
	Some states require doctors to give these records to parents.  
Democrats want to let doctors in other states withhold them if they 
see fit. 
</P>
<P>
	There are differences on other issues, but those were not  
serious enough for either side to oppose the bill, Senate aides 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	On other issues of contention, Jeffords' legislation would:  
</P>
<P>
	--Allow states two years to pass stricter privacy laws. After  
that, states could not pre-empt federal law. 
</P>
<P>
	--Enable law enforcement officers to seize medical records  
without the patient's permission if they have a warrant or other 
court action ordering it. 
</P>
<P>
	--Give medical researchers access to records without getting  
permission first. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 03:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
