<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Machines To Help With Gene Sequence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New machines will enable the Department of  
Energy to triple its speed in decoding human genes and should 
enable the agency to reach its goal of sequencing 300 million base 
pairs of DNA by March. 
</P>
<P>
	Elbert Branscomb, director of the department's Joint Genome  
Institute, said that 24 new DNA sequencer machines to be installed 
at its Walnut Creek, Calif., lab will enable the agency to increase 
the number of base pairs processed monthly from about 5 million to 
about 15 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The new machines, valued at about $5 million, were made by  
Amersham Pharmacia Biotech of Piscataway, N.J., and are being 
leased by the department. Twelve machines are already operating and 
another dozen are expected soon. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department is part of an international public team --  
including the National Institutes of Health and some European labs 
-- that is attempting to sequence, or put into proper order, all of 
the more than 3 billion pairs of DNA molecules that make up the 
human genome. 
</P>
<P>
	Within that genome are all of the 50,000 genes that control  
human physical characteristics. By identifying each of the genes, 
researchers hope to find new ways to treat or prevent many diseases 
and disorders. All of the DNA is contained within 23 pairs of 
chromosomes. 
</P>
<P>
	The department is targeting human chromosome pairs 5, 16 and 19.  
These chromosomes contain about 300 million base pairs of DNA, 
about 10 percent of the entire genome. The three chromosome pairs 
are known to include genes linked to diabetes, cardiovascular 
disease, cancer and asthma. 
</P>
<P>
	Branscomb said the Energy Department already has sequenced about  
30 million base pairs and that the new machines will enable the 
agency to reach its goal. 
</P>
<P>
	The immediate plan, he said, is to establish a ``draft'' of the  
human DNA sequences by next spring. Branscomb said researchers then 
will spend another two to three years refining the data so that the 
location, size and DNA sequence of each gene is known precisely. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
