<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Banks To End Sales to Telemarketers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Big banks are coming under pressure to give up  
a lucrative part of their business, selling customers' personal 
data to telemarketers, as state officials and House lawmakers take 
tough actions aimed at protecting financial privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of America, one of the nation's largest, said Friday it  
would no longer share any customer information with outside vendors 
-- a move welcomed by federal regulators but criticized by consumer 
groups as insufficient. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the time that banks need to make a decision'' on  
whether their privacy practices are appropriate, John Byrne, senior 
counsel for the American Bankers Association, said Monday. ``We 
would certainly encourage banks to examine their practices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several banking industry groups plan to meet next month to come  
up with a coordinated approach to financial privacy proposals now 
before Congress, said Steve Bartlett, president of the Financial 
Services Roundtable. Bartlett, a Republican, is a former U.S. 
representative from Texas and former mayor of Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of America's move came two days after Minnesota's attorney  
general sued U.S. Bancorp, the largest bank based in the state, 
alleging that it illegally sold customer data to a telemarketing 
firm and pocketed $4 million in commissions -- while promising 
customers in writing that their account information would be kept 
confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the California state attorney's office announced  
last week that it would investigate the privacy practices of banks 
in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of America, which now includes NationsBank Corp., is based  
in Charlotte, N.C., but maintains branch operations in its former 
home state of California. 
</P>
<P>
	And in a surprise move in Congress, the House Commerce Committee  
adopted a measure last Thursday that would allow consumers to stop 
banks, securities firms and other financial service companies from 
sharing their personal data with affiliated or outside companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The privacy measure was attached to sweeping legislation to  
remove Depression-era barriers between banks, securities firms and 
insurance companies. The full House is expected to vote on the 
package in the coming weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of America's move ``shows how much the banks are under  
pressure,'' said Edmund Mierzwinski, consumer program director for 
U.S. Public Interest Research Group. ``The tide is starting to 
turn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amid mergers of big banks and marriages of other financial  
services companies, public concern about financial privacy has 
grown. Consumer activists such as Ralph Nader have warned that 
privacy risks for Americans have increased as banks, brokerages and 
insurers compile profiles of customers' buying habits, hobbies and 
health data. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Monday, U.S. Comptroller of the Currency John D. Hawke Jr.,  
who oversees nationally chartered banks, denounced what he called 
abusive sales by some institutions of customers' personal data to 
telemarketing firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law doesn't prohibit banks from selling customers'  
personal data, but prohibits the sharing of information obtained 
from a third party, such as a credit bureau. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks often provide the data -- such as addresses, phone numbers,  
birth dates, Social Security numbers, and checking and credit card 
account information -- to telemarketing firms and other companies in 
exchange for commissions on sales to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue in the U.S. Bancorp case was the bank's alleged  
practice of sharing both bank customers' information and data from 
credit bureaus with telemarketers. In addition, one telemarketing 
firm allegedly ``slammed'' some U.S. Bancorp customers, charging 
them for unauthorized purchases by deducting money from their 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to Bank of America's decision, Julie Williams, chief  
counsel in Hawke's office and his predecessor as comptroller, said, 
``We commend the bank for announcing these changes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Mierzwinski and Mary Griffin, counsel for Consumers Union,  
maintained that Bank of America's action was insufficient because 
the bank pledged not to share customer data only with those 
companies that sell products and services to the bank's customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The new prohibition doesn't cover other outside companies, such  
as those that assemble information databases. 
</P>
<P>
	``It still doesn't give consumers control,'' Ms. Griffin said.  
``It's still not stopping the hemorrhaging of information that gets 
out there.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
