<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Griffey Still Leads AL Voting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- While Ken Griffey Jr. remained the overall  
leader among AL players in voting for next month's All-Star game in 
Boston, Derek Jeter maintained his slight lead over Nomar 
Garciaparra at shortstop. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle star leads outfielders with 847,412 votes, followed  
by Manny Ramirez (437,075) and Kenny Lofton (383,941) of the 
Cleveland Indians. Another Cleveland player, David Justice, was 
fourth (288,86), followed by Bernie Williams of the New York 
Yankees (247,316). 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey was the AL's leading vote-getter in 1991 and 1993 and  
led all players in 1994, 1996, 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other Indians maintained leads at their positions: first  
baseman Jim Thome (220,553) and second baseman Roberto Alomar 
(702,016). 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore's Cal Ripken, who had the first six-hit game of his  
career Sunday night at Atlanta, leads at third base (309,345) and 
is on track for his 17th consecutive All-Star start. He is hitting 
.367 (40-for-109) since returning to the lineup May 13, raising his 
season average to .328 going into Monday's night games. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeter, the top hitter on the World Series champion New York  
Yankees, leads his Boston rival 247,020 to 232,056 at shortstop. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan Rodriguez of Texas (523,457) leads at catcher, and Jose  
Canseco of Tampa Bay (447,262), who began the day tied with Griffey 
for the major league lead in home runs at 23, topped designated 
hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	The All-Star game is scheduled for July 13 at Boston's Fenway  
Park. AL starters will be announced July 5, and NL starters the 
following day. 
</P>
<P>
	An update on NL totals will be released Tuesday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
