<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 22:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Wants Prison Hitching Posts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Gov. Don Siegelman has asked a federal  
judge to allow Alabama to again become the only state that 
handcuffs inmates to hitching posts when they refuse to work. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Myron Thompson ruled last year that the way  
the state was using the posts -- leaving inmates in the sun for 
hours without water or restroom breaks -- was unconstitutionally 
cruel. But he allowed the state to try to devise a constitutional 
method. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Haley, Siegelman's prison commissioner, said he believes  
the new policy proposed by the state Department of Corrections is 
constitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	It includes videotape monitoring of the posts to make sure  
inmates get hourly water and restroom breaks, and it allows an 
inmate to be unhitched the moment he agrees to go to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson was to hear testimony today from two guards who  
volunteered to spend nearly four hours shackled to a hitching post. 
</P>
<P>
	Inmate attorney Rhonda Brownstein argued during a court hearing  
Monday that except for the videotaping, the Siegelman policy 
differs little from the one used during Gov. Fob James' 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Restraining people this way is a form of corporal punishment  
and violates the Constitution,'' Brownstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	The posts are chest-high metal bars with metal rings on them  
that are placed outside in the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	Prison officials contend the post is an incentive to work and  
that inmates shackled to it are no more uncomfortable than inmates 
working on the prison farms or picking up trash. 
</P>
<P>
	``The weather conditions, the sunlight conditions, should be  
virtually the same as the work squad,'' said Ralph Hooks Jr., 
warden at Limestone Correctional Center near Capshaw. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
