<DOCNO> APW19990614.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 04:10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.D. Man Wins 'Think-Off' Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK MILLS, Minn. (AP) -- Mark Friestad said it, the audience  
believed it, and that settled it. 
</P>
<P>
	The 26-year-old high school social studies teacher from Valley  
City, N.D., won the Great American Think-Off on Saturday with a 
convincing spiel that science is more dangerous than religion. 
</P>
<P>
	``He seemed to overwhelmingly convince the audience where blind  
faith in science can prove dangerous for people's ability to reason 
for themselves,'' said Jolie Sasseville, who coordinated the 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	The seventh annual event featured debate between four finalists  
selected from about 500 argumentative essays submitted from around 
the world. The Think-Off audience then selected a winner, who 
receives $500 and a contract from an educational book publisher. 
</P>
<P>
	Friestad cited the early 1900s eugenics movement, which  
hypothesized the human gene pool could be improved if weak links 
were removed. 
</P>
<P>
	``That led to public policy like sterilizing handicapped  
people,'' he said. ``We accepted that because scientists told us it 
was so. And anytime you have to rely on someone else to do your 
thinking for you, that's dangerous.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 10:27:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Qwest Bids Billions for Telecom Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Qwest's bold bid Sunday to acquire U S West Inc.  
and Frontier Corp. lost some of its luster today as investors 
pummeled Qwest's stock, reducing the value of the initial $55 
billion deal to $43 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest's unsolicited proposals aim to break up the two companies'  
agreements to be acquired by Global Crossing Inc., and could start 
a bidding war between Qwest and Global Crossing. The two companies 
are fighting to be the first to build a global network of 
high-speed fiber optic cables that will bring consumers and 
businesses a host of video, audio and Internet services. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver-based Qwest, the nation's fourth-largest long-distance  
telephone company, also offers Internet and data communications 
services to businesses and consumers. The deal would give Qwest a 
piece of the local phone markets in 14 western states with the 
addition of the Denver-based Baby Bell U S West. It would 
strengthen Qwest's long-distance business with the addition of 
Rochester, N.Y.-based Frontier, the No. 5 long-distance company, 
which also has local phone, cellular, paging and Internet 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Even combined, however, the companies would still be less than  
half the size of AT&AMP;T Corp., the country's largest long-distance 
phone and cable company. 
</P>
<P>
	But Qwest's investors reacted negatively to the deal, sending  
the company's stock down 20 percent, or by $9.06 1/4, to $35.81 1/4 a 
share in midday trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	The drop in Qwest's stock price will significantly dull the  
appeal of the company's plans to print more shares to pay for U S 
West and Frontier. Qwest offered 1.738 shares of its stock, worth 
$62.24 in today's trading, for U S West. For Frontier, Qwest 
offered $20 a share in cash and 1.181 shares of stock, worth 
$42.29, for a total value of $62.29. Both bids will be sweetened 
slightly if both companies agree to the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest's offer, which originally represented a hefty premium to  
Global Crossing's bid, is now worth less. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing, a Bermuda-based company with plans to link the  
world's continents with high-speed fiber optic cables, is offering 
$63 in cash and stock for Frontier and about $63 in stock for U S 
West. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph P. Nacchio, Qwest chairman and chief executive officer,  
sent letters to the heads of U S West and Frontier Sunday, saying, 
``Given the clear superiority of our offer to the proposed Global 
Crossing merger, we would like to meet with you and your advisors 
as soon as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U S West and Frontier both said they would review the offers and  
declined to comment further. Officials from Global Crossing 
declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet is revolutionizing the telecommunications industry  
and is driving a string of merger bids. Companies are hoping that 
the next generation of high-speed Internet technologies will link 
more homes and businesses, providing a wealth of new opportunities 
to sell goods and provide information and entertainment. These 
hopes have prompted telecom and cable companies to make big bets on 
mergers so they can gain the size and market share that will be 
keys to new profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``These new companies like Qwest and Global Crossing are  
building state-of-the-art fiber optic networks which are the key to 
the future of a communications company, but they don't have the 
customers or revenues yet,'' said Jeffrey Kagan, an independent 
telecom analyst. ``On the other hand, companies like U S West and 
Frontier have the older networks but they have the customers and 
revenue. So it's natural for the two of them to get together,'' 
Kagan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, AT&AMP;T Corp. won a bidding war with cable TV company  
Comcast for MediaOne Group Inc., another cable company. AT&AMP;T, the 
nation's largest long distance company, is gambling that television 
cables will also be the way to carry Internet, voice and data 
traffic in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	Other telecom companies such as Qwest and U S West are banking  
on an alternative high-speed Internet technology that uses 
traditional telephone lines. 
</P>
<P>
	If Qwest is successful in its takeover quest, the combined  
company would have revenues of $22 billion in 2000 and serve 31 
million customers. Currently, Qwest has just $2.24 billion in 
revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest estimates the united company could save as much as $11.1  
billion in operating costs and capital investments, and generate up 
to $3.1 billion in sales as it expands local telephone service as 
well as data and Internet services. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a heady undertaking, and not without risks. Global  
Crossing, or another telephone company, could raise the stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We entered this planning to win,'' Nacchio said in an  
interview. ``That will remain unchanged, irrespective of anyone 
else's entering it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Qwest's offer is accepted by U S West, the company's chairman  
and chief executive officer, Solomon D. Trujillo, would be invited 
to become the vice chairman of Qwest. Trujillo and three other U S 
West directors would also be asked to join Qwest's board. 
</P>
<P>
	For Frontier, Qwest is offering two seats on its board,  
including one for Joseph P. Clayton, Frontier's chief executive 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West's stock rose $3.31 1/4, or by 5 percent, to $58/18 3/4 by  
midday on the New York Stock Exchange, where Frontier's shares 
jumped $2.93 3/4, or 5 percent, to $58.37 1/2. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
