<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FX Targets Male Viewers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It was five years ago this month when cable's FX  
-- or fX, as it was known then -- signed on. With the slogan 
``Television Made Fresh Daily,'' it specialized in live talk piped 
from its apartment-like studio and it welcomed interaction from its 
viewers. Women viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Now ``Breakfast Time'' and ``Personal fX'' are long gone. So are  
repeats of ``Hart to Hart'' and ``Eight Is Enough.'' So, for that 
matter, are the gals. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, FX -- all capitals now -- is angling for the young men in  
its 39 million cable homes. 
</P>
<P>
	And it's after something else, something the Fox-owned network  
has yet to nail: a bold, widely recognized identity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think FX is wavering in the viewer's mind: What exactly is  
FX?'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is Peter Liguori talking. He's the president of FX, which  
this summer is introducing a slate of new series aimed at settling 
that question. 
</P>
<P>
	``My job is to brand the network,'' says Liguori, ``and the best  
way to brand it is by creating original programming that supports 
some kind of a position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His most notable entry is ``The X Show,'' a weeknight  
talk-and-information hour that is by, for and about guys. It began 
June 2. 
</P>
<P>
	What kind of position does ``The X Show'' support?  
</P>
<P>
	``The mindset commonly held by a younger male audience, 18 to  
34,'' declares Liguori, who, having exited that market segment just 
three birthdays ago, still knows it when he sees it. ``They're 
savvy, cynical, and they want their entertainment in an unabashed 
format.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unabashed is what ``The X Show'' means to be.  
</P>
<P>
	``Half of life is knowing the rules -- and the other half  
involves ointment,'' quipped Mark DeCarlo on the show's opening 
night. DeCarlo, who used to emcee the syndicated game show 
``Studs,'' is one of four regular-guy hosts who keep ``The X Show'' 
focused on the Big Four regular-guy topics: money, games, sex and 
savoir-faire. No time for ointment. 
</P>
<P>
	Pretty straightforward, huh? Even so, the gospel of ``The X  
Show'' -- and FX overall -- could initially be garbled by this week's 
premiere of ``The Man Show'' on Comedy Central (Wednesday at 10:30 
p.m. EDT). 
</P>
<P>
	But there need be no confusion between the two new series. ``X''  
is a talk show devoted to the tricks of the trade of being a guy; 
``Man'' is a guy comedy. ``X'' evokes a rec room, ``Man'' a locker 
room (and sometimes bathroom). ``X'' astutely mirrors guyhood, 
whatever that means, while ``Man'' is a fun-house mirror of 
guy-grotesquerie. Funny, yes, and about as representative of males 
as ``South Park'' (which ``The Man Show'' shrewdly follows) is 
emblematic of childhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Another difference between the two shows: ``Man'' features  
members of the fairer sex bouncing on trampolines -- and, hey, who 
doesn't like trampolines! But that's not the kind of bounce Liguori 
wanted for FX. 
</P>
<P>
	When he took over as president last August, he inherited its  
initial wave of series whose spirit, if not always their execution, 
reflected the network's new sense of itself. 
</P>
<P>
	``Penn &AMP; Teller's Sin City Spectacular'' (Friday at 10 p.m. EDT)  
Liguori sums up as ``the anti-variety show, and Penn and Teller are 
the anti-magicians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, he calls ``Bobcat'' (Saturday night at 1:30 a.m.)  
``the anti-game show,'' and ``Instant Comedy With the Groundlings'' 
(Sunday night at 1:30 a.m. EDT) ``the anti-comedy show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``All three shows have what we like to call -- and I'm going to  
challenge your gag reflex with this turn of phrase -- `antitude,''' 
Liguori says. ``Antitude means: If there's a convention out there, 
we're gonna take it, we're gonna turn it on its ear, we're gonna 
dissect it, and then take it from another angle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In February, Liguori launched the highly antitudinous, and often  
very funny ``Fast-Food Films'' (Sunday at 12 midnight EDT), whose 
half-hour episodes take three well-known feature films and edit 
each into an entirely different cinematic send-up. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 20, FX introduces the animated ``Dick and Paula  
Celebrity Special,'' a wry weekly look at husband-and-wife 
talk-show hosts who interview famous people, living and dead. It 
comes from the producer of Comedy Central's droll ``Dr. Katz: 
Professional Therapist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And on July 23, FX debuts weekly ``World Toughman  
Championships.'' Enough said about that. 
</P>
<P>
	But most of all it's ``The X Show'' putting the network's  
testosterone crusade to the test. Success, predicts Liguori, will 
come from that show's unabashed honesty: 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's picking stocks, if it's tipping a stripper, if it's  
talking politics, if it's talking about dating -- just be honest and 
the audience will relate to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And no one will mind if they leave the seat up.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	FOOD NETWORK SIGNS MARTHA: Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia has  
signed a three-year production partnership with cable's Food 
Network to include the development of an original network series 
scheduled to premiere in 2000. In addition, food and entertainment 
segments from TV's syndicated ``Martha Stewart Living'' will begin 
airing as a yet-untitled series on the 24-hour network in 
September. Food Network, dedicated to good food and good times, is 
available in more than 40 million cable homes. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ``at'' ap.org.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
