<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Bond Opening Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Securities regulators would be required to  
make price information on corporate bonds as widely available as 
data about stocks and government bonds under a bill the House 
passed Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Such information would make the market more competitive and  
enable investors to shop around for the best prices, said sponsors 
of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration supports the measure, which passed  
the House 332-1 and advanced to the Senate for further 
consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, bond dealers are not obligated to reveal their  
selling prices, which means they can sell the same bond to 
different people for different prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Tom Bliley, R-Va., chairman of the House Commerce  
Committee, cited the case of two investors who bought identical 
bonds at a 6 percent difference -- an amount that he said can amount 
to almost a full year's worth of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason for this is that there exists no mechanism to  
provide investors with bond prices, like the ticker that investors 
see every day for stock prices,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill directs the Securities and Exchange Commission to use  
the authority it has had since 1975 to adopt rules to make the 
pricing system more open, thus increasing competition and improving 
prices for all investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate bonds are considered integral to stock market  
performance since it is difficult to make decisions about a 
company's stock without accurate data on its debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike stocks, the vast majority of bonds are not traded in a  
central market. They are bought and sold over the telephone by a 
relatively small group of dealers that includes major brokerages. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1400.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
