<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ebay Stock Plunges After Outage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Business was buzzing on Internet auction  
site eBay on Monday, but that didn't prevent investors for pushing 
the company's stock down 18 percent as fallout continued from last 
week's 22-hour outage. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of EBay dropped $29.87 1/2 to $136 in trading on the Nasdaq  
Stock Market, the first trading day since eBay said it would refund 
fees for all active auctions from Thursday and Friday, costing it 
between $3 million to $5 million in second-quarter revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of the popular auction house, which has attracted more  
than 3 million users in 50 countries, are now down more than 43 
percent from the $234 high reached in April. 
</P>
<P>
	EBay engineers joined technicians from Sun Microsystems Inc. and  
Oracle Corp. to figure out what went wrong and how to make sure the 
site doesn't crash again. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've marshaled virtually every resource in the company to  
make sure we provide a stable system for our users,'' said eBay 
vice president Steve Westly. 
</P>
<P>
	Westly and about 200 other eBay employees and managers spent  
Monday trying to personally call 10,000 eBay users to ``listen to 
their perspective,'' said Westly. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had massive data corruption caused by Sun software,''  
said Westly. ``That's all we know for certain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The site went down late Thursday evening and was not functioning  
again until Friday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	E-commerce analyst Jill Frankle at International Data Corp. in  
Framingham, Mass., compared eBay's current problems to 
technological struggles AOL, and later ETrade faced, as they were 
overloaded with users. 
</P>
<P>
	``These glitches are characteristic of the growth a lot of the  
Internet companies are experiencing,'' she said. ``These business 
models are based on technology. This shows us what can happen when 
something doesn't work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Bernstein, a research analyst at Gartner Group in  
Stamford, Conn., said that in the grand scheme of things, eBay's 
recent technical and investor problems are relatively minor. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a fiasco like this that will force a company to really  
fix the problem,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those fixes may come too late for some eBay users.  
</P>
<P>
	Paul Gregg, a computer engineer in Inglewood, Fla., said Monday  
that it's time to check out Yahoo! and Amazon, competing online 
auctions. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregg said he was trying to auction a computer for about $5,000  
this weekend, but eBay cut the last 40 minutes off his auction, 
which is usually the most active time. He had to sell it for 
$4,000, and pay eBay a $65 listing fee. 
</P>
<P>
	``When things go wrong there, they go really wrong,'' said  
Gregg. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed Sibley, of Lewisberg, Penn., who breeds and races  
quarterhorses and sells everything from movie cameras to hand tools 
on eBay, said he believes the company has a sound future, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see the word failure written anywhere near eBay,'' he  
said. ``There are plenty of people making a living off this, for 
crying out loud, and they're not going to go away.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
