<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Off DL, Ripken Ripping the Ball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cal Ripken woke up Monday morning wondering  
whether the finest performance of his outstanding baseball career 
was merely a figment of his imagination. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken set a Baltimore Orioles record by getting six hits in a  
game Sunday night, hitting two homers and a double in a 6-for-6 
effort against the Atlanta Braves. He then boarded a chartered 
flight and arrived home around 3 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	After a few hours sleep, Ripken opened his eyes and immediately  
had a horrid thought. 
</P>
<P>
	``You wake up and wonder if it actually did happen or you just  
dreamed it happened. It's nice to know it did happen,'' Ripken said 
Monday afternoon. ``It's a pretty darn good feeling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The record-breaking night was the consummation of a remarkable  
stretch in which he has added 149 points to his batting average 
while moving significantly closer to reaching 400 homers and 3,000 
hits over his 19-year career. He had 391 homers and 2,923 hits 
before the Orioles played Kansas City on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, best known for playing in 2,632 consecutive games, was  
batting .179 on April 20 before being placed on the disabled list 
for the first time in his career with a strained lower back. At the 
time he was also wrestling with feelings related to the death of 
his father, Cal Sr., who succumbed to lung cancer on March 25. 
</P>
<P>
	``In hindsight, there was a lot of benefit of being on the  
disabled list. It was a good break for me mentally and a necessary 
break physically,'' Ripken said. ``So when I came back, I was armed 
with a little bit better focus, a clearer head. And physically, I 
felt great. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you learn the most from some of your not-so-nice  
experiences,'' he said. ``The obstacles that were in the way, I've 
been able to step over them and step around them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since returning from the disabled list on May 13, Ripken hit  
safely in 22 of 26 games, batting .367 over that span to raise his 
batting average from .179 to .328. 
</P>
<P>
	The difference goes far beyond the new stance he broke out last  
month. Ripken valiantly attempted to play with pain in his lower 
back and anguish in his heart, but it was a futile effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fire just wasn't there,'' Orioles manager Ray Miller said.  
``Now he's having fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Batting coach Terry Crowley, who played under Ripken Sr. and has  
known the younger Ripken for years, realized early in spring 
training that Cal just didn't have his usual zest for the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know his actions, his personality and I know right away when  
Cal is feeling good. When he's feeling good, he's got a lot of 
energy and is fun to be around,'' Crowley said. ``When he's a 
little quiet, you know something's bothering him. I saw spurts of 
energy from him, but it wasn't a normal spring for Cal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, admittedly, Sunday wasn't a normal night for Ripken. His 13  
total bases tied his career high, the five runs scored set a team 
mark and it was the first time he had as many as five hits in a 
game since May 5, 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like the ball was looking bigger than normal and coming  
in a little slower, even though the speed gun said differently,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	His recent surge might turn out to be worth millions to him.  
Ripken's contract states that the Orioles must decide by the 
All-Star break whether to exercise his $6.3 million option for next 
season, or pay him $2.5 million with a chance to re-sign him at a 
lesser salary. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, Ripken looks like a steal at $6.3 million a year,  
even if he does turn 39 in August. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he did last night was sort of a culmination,'' Orioles  
first baseman Will Clark said. ``By no means was it a fluke. He's 
been swinging the bat well for weeks.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
