<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indiana Energy, Sigcorp Plan Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The parents of Indiana Gas Co. and Southern  
Indiana Gas and Electric Co. plan to merge in an exchange of stock 
valued at $1.4 billion to create a company with more than 650,000 
customers in Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	If the shareholders of Indiana Energy Inc. and Sigcorp Inc.  
approve the merger announced today, a new holding company will be 
created called Vectren Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``The energy industry is converging and successful participants  
will be able to offer a broad array of products and services to 
customers,'' said Niel C. Ellerbrook, president and chief executive 
of Indiana Energy, based in Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellerbrook will be chairman and CEO of the combined company and  
Andrew Goebel, president of chief operating officer of 
Evansville-based Sigcorp, will hold the same positions with 
Vectren. 
</P>
<P>
	``This combination,'' Goebel said, ``will allow us to cross-sell  
a greater array of products and services to our existing and future 
customer base and to make the necessary investment in technology to 
continue delivering first-class customer service in an increasingly 
competitive environment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The companies' current chairmen, Indiana Energy's L.A. Ferger  
and Sigcorp's Ronald Reherman, will retire upon completion of the 
merger but join Ellerbrook and Goebel on Vectren's board of 
directors. Each company will appoint six other directors to the 
16-member board. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders of each of the companies will contol about 50  
percent of Vectren's stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies said they expect the merger to save them $200  
million over 10 years by eliminating duplicate corporate and 
administrative functions and through greater efficiency. 
</P>
<P>
	They expect to eliminate 120 of their combined 1,850 jobs, or  
less than 7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Indiana Energy shareholders will exchange  
one share in the current company for one share of Vectren. Sigcorp 
shareholders will receive 1.33 shares in the new company for each 
share of Sigcorp they hold. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company will also have $500 million in debt and  
subsidiary preferred stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company will be based in Evansville, which also will  
remain home to Southern Indiana Gas and Electric headquarters. 
Indiana Gas operations will remain based in Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies already are partners in Energy Systems LLC, a  
two-year-old company providing energy-related contracting services. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellerbrook said that the 2003, Vectren's goal is to for  
non-regulated operations to contribute 25 percent of earnings and 
for earnings per share to grow on average by 10 percent per year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
