<DOCNO> APW19990614.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 02:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Angels Rookie Hurt in MLB Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Mike Colangelo, making his major league  
debut, was hurt in a collision in the outfield Sunday in the 
seventh inning of the Anaheim Angels' game against Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo was taken to UC Irvine Medical Center with a high back  
injury and an injured left wrist, Angels spokesman Tim Mead said. A 
preliminary examination revealed no serious neck injury. Colangelo 
was put in a neck brace and underwent a CT scan, which was 
negative. He will be re-examined Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo, playing left, and center fielder Reggie Williams were  
both running full speed for a fly in the gap hit by Steve Finley. 
Williams caught the ball and immediately crashed into Colangelo, 
who lay on the field for about 15 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Angels trainers tended to Colangelo, who was placed on an  
immobilizing board for precautionary and taken off the field on a 
medical cart. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo, 22, was just called up from Anaheim's Triple-A  
Edmonton farm team and singled in the first inning. He walked and 
grounded out his next two times up. 
</P>
<P>
	He was hitting .362, with 13 runs scored and nine RBIs in 26  
games at Edmonton. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams remained in the game.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
