<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T: Cable To Allow More Offerings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Cable companies are poised to provide all the  
communications offerings consumers desire and should be given free 
rein to do so, AT&AMP;T Corp.'s chief executive said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	C. Michael Armstrong, who opened the National Cable Television  
Association's annual meeting here, said he is betting his company's 
success on its ability to provide a host of services, including 
super-fast Internet access, phone lines and interactive television. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're moving toward a single information opportunity,''  
Armstrong said. ``Technology, applications and devices are 
converging. Customers are simply going to get more and pay less.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T has made more than $100 billion in cable purchases over the  
past year, including its acquisitions of Tele-Communications Inc. 
and MediaOne Group. That vaulted it into the position of the 
nation's leading cable company, followed by Time Warner and 
Comcast. 
</P>
<P>
	As the convention highlighted technologies that will open the  
Internet to new commerce, information and entertainment services, 
Armstrong argued that federal regulators should not interfere with 
companies that provide access. 
</P>
<P>
	Competitors, including local telephone companies and Internet  
services like America Online have argued that cable companies 
should be required to sell them access to cable customers at 
wholesale prices, just as local phone companies must now sell 
access to their customers to long-distance companies. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
