<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Soccer Team Boasts of Chemistry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINSVILLE, N.J. (AP) -- They shout encouragement to each  
other, even when they're on opposing sides during a scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	There's never been a report of jealousy or backbiting.  
</P>
<P>
	The veterans look at the newcomers the way professors observe  
prodigies. Thirty-somethings room with youngsters barely into their 
20s. Longtime members of the team pal around with rookies. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the U.S. women's soccer team. It's also, according to  
the members of one of the favorites for the World Cup that begins 
Saturday, a great big happy family. 
</P>
<P>
	``Exactly,'' Carla Overbeck said Monday after the Americans'  
first practice session of the final week before they open the 
tournament at Giants Stadium against Denmark. ``This is a unique 
group of people and we know whenever there are new players, it 
boosts the talent of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``The younger players have to step up and accept a role, and  
realize that everyone is as important as the next one. It's a true 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like a family, because we've watched each other grow up,  
and we're all close. This is the situation that is going to make 
this team get better and possibly win the World Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans did just that in 1991 in China, then finished  
third in the 1995 championships. They used the '95 disappointment 
as a catalyst to the 1996 Atlanta Olympics gold medal. 
</P>
<P>
	Through it all, there has been no discord among the women's team  
members. Contrast that with the men's national team, which 
self-destructed during last year's World Cup in France. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's huge,'' coach Tony DiCicco said of the camaraderie.  
``In many ways it's a factor in our success. The challenge of this 
World Cup is very high and the opportunities are equally high. This 
team is so close that hopefully it will factor in. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wish to develop that. We let them know when they join the  
team, they need to make a contribution to the chemistry. We say, 
`You must contribute, or you'll be part of a problem.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	So they contribute. Danielle Fotopoulos set career scoring  
records while at the University of Florida. Then she moved up to 
the national squad, where she is one of many bigtime players -- and, 
for now, filling a supporting role. 
</P>
<P>
	``The veterans who molded the team let the people coming in know  
they have got to fit into the chemistry they've worked so hard to 
create,'' Fotopoulos said. ``Plus, they make everything fun for us. 
Practice is fun. We hang out together and have fun. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can be very intimidating coming into any new team,  
especially one with the success rate the U.S. has had. You don't 
know where you will fit in or the personalities on the team. If 
these were not cool people who cared, it could be a nightmare. 
Instead, it's so special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the means used to create team unity is to switch  
roommates throughout training and during trips for games. Most of 
the veterans have roomed with most of the kids on the team. 
</P>
<P>
	During practice, DiCicco mixes youth and experience, whether it  
be for 4-on-4 minigames, or for full scrimmages. 
</P>
<P>
	The players also consult sports psychologist Coleen Hacker, whom  
Kristine Lilly -- the most experienced U.S. player, with 179 
international appearances -- says is ``a source to vent, if we need 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no negative mentality around the team,'' Lilly added.  
``We're taught different ways to get out of it when we are down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not that this team often gets down, on the scoreboard or away  
from the arena. But if it does, the chemistry developed in a decade 
of partnership seems to carry the Americans through. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess there is a bond there in the female game,'' Lilly  
said. ``We enjoy each other. We've all been in positions where we 
were the new player coming in. It can be difficult to reach out to 
players. But we all do a great job of opening doors.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
