<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trial Begins in Centennial Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Trial began Monday for two businessmen accused of  
helping to cook the books of the personal computer card 
manufacturer Centennial Technologies Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert E. Lockwood, chief executive of Presage Corp., a  
Centennial vendor, and Robert Kuzara, a former Centennial director, 
are charged with conspiracy and securities fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair helped Wilmington, Mass.-based Centennial devise a  
phony transaction to boost its stock price, prosecutor John Falvey 
said during opening arguments in U.S. District Court here. 
</P>
<P>
	A third defendant, Centennial founder Emanuel Pinez, did not go  
on trial as scheduled. Instead, his case was severed from the other 
two. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Joseph Tauro gave no explanation for the change.  
</P>
<P>
	Falvey said Lockwood and Kuzara helped hatch a scheme in which  
Centennial supposedly sold $2 million worth of inventory and 
accounts receivable to a new company called Information Capture 
Corporation. 
</P>
<P>
	In reality, Falvey said, the inventory was not worth much, the  
accounts receivable were questionable and the transaction was used 
to create $1 million in fictional revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors have said Pinez gained more than $4.2 million from  
trading in the company's inflated stock and stood to make more from 
option contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Lockwood and Kuzara held large amounts of stock in  
Centennial, Falvey said. It was not immediately clear if the two 
allegedly gained from the scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	Centennial's former chief financial officer, James M. Murphy,  
has pleaded guilty to securities fraud charges and will testify 
against Lockwood and Kuzara, Falvey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another former Centennial executive-turned-vendor, Bond D.  
Fletcher, also pleaded guilty to the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Lockwood and Kuzara say their clients knew nothing  
about maneuvers to inflate Centennial's assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Centennial engaged in ``hundreds of thousands of bogus  
transactions'' that have nothing to do with Kuzara, said his 
lawyer, Richard Egbert. 
</P>
<P>
	``The evidence will show he wasn't a knowing participant in the  
scheme to defraud,'' said Albert Cullen, Lockwood's attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinez and the others were indicted for allegedly inflating  
Centennial assets by $40 million in 1997. Centennial Technologies 
was a top performer on the New York Stock Exchange in 1996, when 
its stock price increased by 450 percent to trade as high as $55 a 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	But Centennial's stock was delisted from the exchange in  
February 1997 and its price has hovered between 37 cents and $1.75 
for the past year in over-the-counter trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The company appears to be recovering from the scandal.  
Centennial reported its fourth consecutive profitable quarter in 
March and annual sales of $28 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The company hopes to get the stock relisted, this time on the  
Nasdaq Stock Market, said Donald Peck, Centennial's secretary, 
treasurer and general counsel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 10:10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British Bus Company Buys Coach USA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- British bus transport company Stagecoach Holdings  
PLC has agreed to buy one of the United States' leading bus charter 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	Stagecoach's $1.2 billion purchase of Houston-based Coach USA  
Inc. will be subject to informal approval by the staff of the U.S. 
Surface Transportation Board. The offer also includes the 
assumption of $638 million in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am delighted that we are entering the North American market  
at a relatively early stage in its consolidation with the prospect 
of exciting growth opportunities,'' said Brian Souter, chairman of 
Stagecoach, on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stagecoach currently runs bus, train and airport businesses in  
the United Kingdom, New Zealand, Sweden, Finland, Portugal, 
Australia, Hong Kong and China. The Perth, Scotland, company 
employs 37,000 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach USA is the leading U.S. supplier of charter bus, airport  
shuttle and taxi services in North America, operating in more than 
120 cities in 33 states, provinces and territories. Coach employs 
about 12,500 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Stagecoach has 1998 revenues of about $2.5 billion, while Coach  
USA's reported $804 million in revenues last year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
