<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Glider Pilot Killed in Nev. Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINDEN, Nev. (AP) -- One of the nation's top glider pilots was  
killed when his plane plunged about 100 feet to the ground during 
practice for an upcoming race. 
</P>
<P>
	Clem Bowman died instantly when his Genesis sail plane crashed  
Sunday at Minden-Tahoe Airport shortly after take off, airport 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman, of Clermont, Fla., had been competing for more than 10  
years and was the 1997 U.S. glider plane champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman's plane had been towed about 100 feet into the air when  
the horizontal stabilizer, a piece on the tail that control's the 
plane's pitch, fell off, causing the plane to dive, said Rick 
Walters, chairman of the Minden-Tahoe Airport Advisory Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration and the Douglas County  
Sheriff's Department are investigating the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	``The initial guess is that he did not assemble the aircraft  
correctly,'' Walters said, adding that gliders are taken apart 
after every flight for storage. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 45 pilots and their crews were at the airport, 10 miles  
south of Carson City, to take part in a practice run ahead of the 
1999 Standard Class Nationals competition. The race is scheduled 
for Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a very quiet event now,'' Walters said. He said it  
was the first time in 10 years a pilot had died in competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Walters said Bowman was a doctor in his early 50s. He is  
survived by a wife and two children. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
