<DOCNO> APW19990614.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 13:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Automakers, UAW Begin Contract Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- National contract talks began Monday  
between the United Auto Workers and Ford Motor Co., which enjoys 
the best union relations among Detroit's automakers and may again 
set the standard for an economic package for the start of a new 
century. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the key issues for the industry this year is a change in  
manufacturing that could rely more heavily on components made by 
lower-paid workers who are not members of the UAW. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not only is it a new contract for a new century, but it's a  
contract that a lot of people in the U.S. and in the world will be 
watching -- not only what we accomplish, but how we do it,'' Jac 
Nasser, Ford's president, told the bargaining teams. ``The how is 
almost as important as where we come out in the end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Health and safety, job security, wages and benefits remain  
perennial major considerations. 
</P>
<P>
	UAW president Stephen P. Yokich and Ford vice chairman Peter J.  
Pestillo, the architects of Ford-UAW relations and longtime 
friends, formally kicked off the talks by shaking hands across the 
50-seat ``main table'' where major issues will be decided in the 
coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	The handshakes and opening remarks at Ford's world headquarters  
were a triennial ritual that will be repeated Tuesday at 
DaimlerChrysler AG and Wednesday at General Motors Corp. Their 
contracts expire Sept. 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike strike-prone rival GM, Ford has enjoyed peaceful labor  
relations with the UAW for two decades. Ford has not endured a 
nationwide UAW strike in 23 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Come Labor Day, the UAW will choose the lead company with which  
it will work out an economic package that the other automakers will 
be expected to adopt. Ford set the pace for the contracts as lead 
company in 1993 and 1996 and is hoping to do so again. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford chief negotiator Robert H. Marcin said the reason was  
simple: It allows the company to negotiate what's best for Ford 
rather than being stuck with what may be best for its domestic 
competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasser told negotiators that ``manufacturing processes'' were a  
major issue for Ford. All three companies have long sought more 
flexibility in the way they can use UAW workers on the assembly 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	But GM executives' public talk of drastically changing the way  
the No. 1 automaker manufactures small cars by adopting ``modular'' 
assembly techniques has angered the UAW. Modular assembly would 
rely more on suppliers to build a car's major parts assemblies, or 
``modules,'' and less on higher-cost UAW workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford executives have been careful in recent weeks to avoid the  
``M word,'' and Nasser was no exception. But he said the issue of 
manufacturing processes ``really drives how good we are and what 
our customers think about us and our products and the value that we 
can put into the market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The remarks by Nasser and chairman William C. Ford Jr. were made  
behind closed doors, but they were inadvertently broadcast into the 
Ford pressroom where reporters were awaiting the handshake 
ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	At a later news conference, Yokich insisted Nasser had not  
mentioned manufacturing processes. But he maintained his stance 
against modular assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's not good for GM, why would I say it's good for Ford?''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Health and safety issues will be one of the first issues tackled  
at Ford in the wake of the February explosion at its Rouge plant 
near Detroit, said a company executive who spoke on condition of 
anonymity. The blast killed six workers. The executive said the 
company was eager to negotiate any contract provisions that could 
prevent another such disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	Yokich said he discussed the Rouge explosion with negotiators  
Monday and that it would be an issue throughout the talks. He noted 
that there have been 42 work-related deaths in the domestic auto 
industry during the current three-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's 42 too many as far as we're concerned,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ford negotiators also will be tackling the future of the 23,500  
UAW workers at the company's Visteon parts unit. Ford is expected 
to spin off Visteon in the next year or two, though it says no 
final decision has been made. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiations cover between 101,000 and 110,000 Ford workers,  
depending on who's counting. The company issued the smaller number 
Monday; the union used the larger one. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford, the 42-year-old great-grandson of founder Henry Ford who  
took over the chairman's seat in January, said he entered these 
talks with a deep sense of history. The company will mark its 100th 
anniversary in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a sense that we, in many ways, created the industrial  
revolution,'' Ford said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said his work on the 1982 Ford bargaining team taught him  
much about the importance of trust in his company's relationship 
with the UAW. 
</P>
<P>
	The UAW negotiators presented their Ford counterparts with a  
large banner that read ``Bargaining for Families,'' the theme the 
UAW officials chose for these talks. UAW lead negotiator Ron 
Gettelfinger said the banner would be ``a reminder throughout the 
negotiations of what we're here for.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 13:10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aetna Told To Shed Some Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The federal government has told Aetna  
Inc. to shed some of its operations before it approves the 
company's pending $1 billion acquisition of the health care unit of 
Prudential Insurance Co. of America. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department told Aetna Friday to divest itself from  
some of its combined health plan operations, a company official 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna spokeswoman Joyce Oberdorf would not give any details of  
the demand, but said talks with the Justice Department are expected 
to be wrapped up soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their view was pretty much in line with our expectations,''  
Oberdorf said. ``There weren't any surprises.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal reported Monday that Aetna is leaning  
toward accepting the government's conditions, which include 
shedding operations in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Some groups, such as the American Medical Association, have  
argued the acquisition will be bad for consumers and will give 
Aetna too much power over physicians. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas Medical Association also opposed the deal, claiming it  
would give Aetna about a 60 percent share of the commercial HMO 
market in Houston and as much as a 50 percent share of the market 
in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	The combination of the Hartford-based company's Aetna U.S.  
Healthcare unit and Prudential HealthCare would provide benefits to 
about 22 million people nationwide. Aetna currently provides health 
care coverage to about 16 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	Oberdorf said Aetna is trying to close its deal with Prudential  
by the end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	After the deal was announced late last year, Aetna chairman and  
chief executive Richard Huber said he expected it to clear the 
Justice Department antitrust review without having to give up any 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent months, Huber has been more receptive to giving up  
some businesses to get approval. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 07:40:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DoubleClick To Buy Abacus Direct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- DoubleClick Inc. and Abacus Direct Corp. today  
announced a $1 billion merger to create a combined online 
advertising and database marketing company. 
</P>
<P>
	DoubleClick, a seller of banner advertising on the Internet,  
will use Abacus' database of consumer catalog buying behavior to 
better target ads to specific consumers, the companies said today 
in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Abacus tracks more than 2 billion consumer catalog transactions  
from 1,100 merchandise catalogs. 
</P>
<P>
	Right now, DoubleClick can display ads based on the type of Web  
site an Internet user is visiting. By using Abacus' database, 
DoubleClick will be able to display an advertisement suited to that 
consumer's catalog buying habits as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based DoubleClick will issue 1.05 shares of common  
stock for each share of Abacus, based in Broomfield, Colo. The new 
company, which will retain the DoubleClick name, will be 
headquartered in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, which is subject to regulatory approval and approval  
by shareholders of both companies, is expected to be completed in 
the third quarter of this year. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 12:20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Helsinki Bids for Shared Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Finland's highest mountain for alpine  
skiing is a mere 2,370 feet, and it's nowhere near the capital. 
Still, Helsinki is bidding for the 2006 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Renowned for its winter sports, Finland has never before had a  
chance to host a Winter Games because it lacks alpine facilities. 
That changed in 1990, when the International Olympic Committee 
decided to allow the games to be shared. 
</P>
<P>
	Lahti, known as a Nordic skiing center, was ready a few years  
ago but failed to find a partner. In 1997, IOC president Juan 
Antonio Samaranch urged the Finns to try again. 
</P>
<P>
	And they did, with one of the most popular partners possible.  
</P>
<P>
	They approached the successful 1994 Olympic host, Lillehammer,  
which agreed to be paired with Helsinki for 2006. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot think of an economically better concept than Norway  
and Finland together,'' said Jari Piirainen, the Helsinki 2006 
project manager. ``Norway has the know-how in the alpine events, 
and we've got it in cross- country skiing and ice hockey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not building castles in the air. We know there'll be a  
lot of spectators in both countries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lillehammer would stage alpine skiing, snowboarding and the  
sledding events. Lahti, an hour's drive north of Helsinki, would 
have the Nordic skiing, biathlon and freestyle skiing events. 
Curling, ice hockey, figure skating and speedskating would be held 
in Helsinki. 
</P>
<P>
	The distance between Helsinki and Lillehammer is 500 miles, but  
travelers will have to transfer to a train or bus at Oslo's new 
airport, since Lillehammer doesn't have an airport to cater to 
Olympic crowds. 
</P>
<P>
	But Piirainen said a special fleet of planes and swift handling  
of luggage from charter flights will make it a short trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``The distance between Helsinki and Lillehammer was our  
logistical challenge, and we have solved it in the way we 
promised,'' Piirainen says. ``Between three hours and three hours 
and fifteen minutes ... to Lillehammer is not that much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The strength of the Helsinki 2006 bid is that most venues exist.  
Only an arena for speedskating has to be built, with organizers 
bypassing a chance to use the Viking Ship hall in Hamar, Norway, in 
favor of a new multipurpose building for ice sports here. 
</P>
<P>
	The Finns are used to organizing major sports events.  
</P>
<P>
	Ten years ago, Lahti hosted the World Nordic Skiing  
Championships before 450,000 spectators. In 1997, the Ice Hockey 
World Championships drew over 520,000, mainly to the new Hartwall 
Arena in Helsinki. 
</P>
<P>
	Helsinki will be responsible for handling the finances,  
including all revenue and expenses, and the wages of the people 
working with the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials, athletes and accredited media will be provided with a  
smart card that acts as a passport, visa and a free-of-charge 
transportation ticket. Fans will be able to benefit from special 
low-rate fares promised by the games' official carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	The Helsinki 2006 project manager admits that the tightened  
rules for IOC members, imposed in the wake of the Salt Lake bribery 
scandal, hurt the chances of its bid, especially the ban on travel. 
</P>
<P>
	The host city also will be picked in a new way, with a special  
panel reducing the field of six to two finalists and the IOC 
delegates then deciding the winner. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Helsinki concept demanded a new way of thinking by the  
people making decisions, and it would have benefited us if they 
could have seen our arrangement with their own eyes,'' Piirainen 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Finnish IOC member Pirjo Haeggman worked for the Helsinki 2006  
committee until mid-January, when she resigned from both the IOC 
and the local panel. Haeggman was the first of 10 IOC members to 
quit or be expelled for abusing their positions. 
</P>
<P>
	``She became a hot subject and did not want to be a burden to  
us. But she then made her own brave decision (to resign),'' 
Piirainen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Finns have mostly welcomed the idea of the Olympics, and polls  
have indicated that some two-thirds of the nation approves of 
hosting the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Some doubt that a country of 5 million can afford the cost, but  
Piirainen points out that most of the money in the $460 million 
budget will come from international TV contracts and sponsorship 
deals, with $360 million already secured. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our sole aim is to win, and to do it now. We don't see this as  
a preliminary round for a future campaign,'' he says. ``We have to 
reach the final, and it doesn't matter against whom. Our main 
opponent is perhaps Sion. Rumors have them as the favorite, but 
we'd like to beat them in the final.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 18:31:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Serbs Flee Kosovo in Huge Convoys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ducking at the sound of gunfire,  
patrolling cautiously to avoid the ire of Serbs, thousands of NATO 
peacekeepers spread out Monday across Kosovo. Some uncovered grim 
evidence of atrocities as they tightened their control of the 
province. 
</P>
<P>
	Serb forces complying with the pullout ordered by NATO to end  
the 78-day air war mixed in with civilians fleeing in columns up to 
500 vehicles long. Some ethnic Albanian homes were set ablaze by 
Serb troops leaving Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Aiming to bring a measure of stability to the province shattered  
by war and a long history of ethnic hatred, NATO and U.S. forces 
sought to downplay the impasse over about 200 Russian soldiers 
occupying the Pristina airfield where the allies planned to 
establish headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO lead commander Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson insisted the  
airfield wasn't crucial to occupying forces though the White House 
said Defense Secretary William Cohen and Secretary of State 
Madeleine Albright will meet their Russian counterparts in 
Helsinki, Finland, within days. 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovo's Serbs fear that the majority ethnic Albanians will take  
bloody revenge on them for years of oppression and for reported 
atrocities. The West, meanwhile, fears that a Russian zone will 
lead to the partition of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Refugees who began streaming out of Kosovo after the NATO  
bombing campaign began March 24 told of Serb slaughter and the 
massacre of innocent victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The accounts could not be independently confirmed at the time  
and one of the peacekeepers' grueling tasks will be to investigate 
what happened. On Monday, they gingerly probed the town cemetery in 
Kacanik, where the stench of decayed flesh hung heavy over 81 
apparently newly dug graves. 
</P>
<P>
	British Capt. Andy Reeds said war crimes investigators would be  
called in to examine the site, 30 miles south of Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	Peacekeepers continued to pour into the battered Serbian  
province from neighboring Macedonia and Albania, and officials said 
about 15,000 allied troops had entered Kosovo by Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The deployment of KFOR is on schedule,'' said NATO Secretary  
General Javier Solana. ``The withdrawal of the Serbian forces is 
also on time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A convoy of 1,200 U.S. Marines began crossing just south of  
Kacanik at first light, and U.S. forces took over the area, 
including the site of the graves, from the British troops. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were all a little edgy going in,'' said Cpl. Will Rapier,  
20, of Paintsville, Ky., with the 3rd Battalion, 8th Marines. ``We 
just hope to get this thing over so we can all go home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the tensions, Monday's troop movements went off without  
a repeat of Sunday's pair of fatal confrontations, when soldiers 
shot a Serb in Pristina and German forces killed one man and 
wounded another after the men fired at them from a car in the city 
of Prizren. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Serb citizens poured out of Prizren, Kosovo's  
second-largest city, taunted by ethnic Albanians who erupted into a 
wild victory celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	German soldiers disarmed several members of the Kosovo  
Liberation Army, the ethnic Albanian guerrilla group, as they tried 
to seize wounded Serb soldiers at the main Prizren hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The KLA is supposed to demilitarize under the Kosovo peace  
agreement, but the group boldly set up an office in Pristina on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The private news agency Beta reported Monday that three Serbs  
were killed by men wearing KLA armbands in a suburb of Pristina. 
The Serb-run Media Center said it had a report of five people 
killed in the same suburb but did not have details. 
</P>
<P>
	The center blamed the KLA for the shooting death of a Serb  
employee of Pristina's television station in front of his home 
Monday night in the Taslidze section of the city. The Serb report 
gave no other details of the attack 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview distributed Monday by the rebels' Kosova Press  
agency, senior guerrilla leader Hashim Thaci said the Russians were 
unwelcome in Kosovo and demanded they leave. He warned that the KLA 
``will not guarantee their security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Their uninvited entrance may stir more conflict in Kosova that  
we do not want to happen,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thaci also claimed that the KLA is not required to demilitarize.  
However, the peace accord calls from the group to disarm. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian troops entered the city of Pec, the seat of the Serbian  
Orthodox Church in Kosovo and the scene of some of the grimmest 
accounts of slaughter in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav troops withdrew from the city on Monday after a spree  
of home-burnings and alleged rapes, whooping on the way out. 
</P>
<P>
	Two German journalists were shot dead by unidentified gunman  
Sunday 15 miles south of Pristina. The German newsweekly Stern 
identified them as photographer Volker Kraemer, 56, and reporter 
Gabriel Gruener, 35. The magazine said the team's interpreter was 
missing. 
</P>
<P>
	In Pristina, an impasse over its strategic airport continued.  
</P>
<P>
	Russia's role in the envisaged 50,000-member peacekeeping force,  
which includes 7,000 Americans, was not clearly defined in the 
peace plan. A contingent of 200 Russian troops arrived unexpectedly 
from Bosnia on Saturday, ahead of NATO troops, and took control of 
the airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson said Monday that he did not regard the presence of the  
Russians as important from a military standpoint. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not in a tussle with them,'' he said. ``They are on the  
airfield. ... It is not important to me at this stage. What is 
important to me is getting this job done on the ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and Russian leader Boris Yeltsin spoke for a  
second straight day about continuing differences over Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials and those from allied countries have largely  
sought to play down indications of a rivalry with the Russians, who 
demand to control their own sector in northern Kosovo where ethnic 
Serbs -- their longtime allies -- are concentrated. 
</P>
<P>
	The deployment of peacekeepers did not stop Serb forces from  
shelling an Albanian village early Monday at the village of Dobrun, 
an area where the KLA maintains sanctuaries, according to Andrea 
Angeli, spokesman of the Organization for Security and Cooperation 
in Europe. There were no reports of casualties. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic toured the ruins of a  
destroyed bridge across the Danube River in Beska, 30 miles 
northwest of the Yugoslav capital, Belgrade, and officially 
inaugurated the country's reconstruction effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that peace is here again, we face the task of rebuilding  
the country,'' he was quoted as saying by the state-run Tanjug news 
agency. 
</P>
<P>
	About 300 refugees tried to return Monday, crossing the Yugoslav  
border from Albania before being turned back by German peacekeepers 
and rebels. Thirty or 40 refugees broke away and scampered off over 
the hills into Kosovo, said an OSCE spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials want Kosovo Albanians to remain in refugee camps  
until peacekeepers have restored order and cleared minefields. 
</P>
<P>
	About 860,000 Kosovo Albanians fled the province of 2.1 million  
people during the conflict. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0101 </DOCNO>
