<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Managers Describe Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Tom Kelly remembers seeing dark circles under Sparky Anderson's  
eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told some people, `Sparky looks terrible,''' the Minnesota  
Twins manager recalled Monday. ``He had black rings under his eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since that day, when I wake up in the morning and see black  
rings, that's when I say `timeout' and sit back and reevaluate, 
because that's not healthy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of game decisions. Late-night meals. Early-morning  
trips. And the pressure to win every day. 
</P>
<P>
	No telling whether any of it contributed to Larry Dierker's  
collapse Sunday. Still, managers throughout the major leagues could 
only wonder. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first reaction was `Yeah, was it something stress- or  
job-related?''' Detroit's Larry Parrish said. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Tampa Bay's Larry Rothschild: ``Whatever, it was probably  
exacerbated by the stress of the job. I don't doubt that it was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Managers are not required by major league baseball to take  
annual physicals. Many teams give them, sometimes for insurance 
purposes. Unlike players or umpires, there is no union for 
protection. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no association, we have each other,'' Texas' Johnny  
Oates said. ``This is almost like a fraternity. We need each other. 
We are the only ones who understand what we do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Torre was forced to leave the New York Yankees this year for  
treatment of prostate cancer. Bench coach Don Zimmer filled in, 
hobbling in constant pain from a knee problem. 
</P>
<P>
	John Boles missed a total of 13 games for Florida because of  
back surgery and a sprained neck. In 1996, Tom Lasorda stepped down 
in Los Angeles after having a mild heart attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The signs show up in other ways, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Tony La Russa chews his fingernails to the nub, Jim Leyland  
chain-smoked in the dugout tunnel. Billy Martin was known to drink, 
Buck Showalter slept in his office. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not much time to reflect on how you feel physically or  
mentally because there are important decisions to be made 
day-by-day. A lot of time you're the last person you worry about,'' 
Kansas City's Tony Muser said. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Baltimore's Ray Miller: ``Every once in a while you think,  
`If I dropped dead, no one would know until the afternoon?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker collapsed in the dugout at the Astrodome in the eighth  
inning of Houston's game against San Diego. The 52-year-old manager 
will undergo brain surgery Tuesday to remove a mass of malformed 
blood vessels that caused his seizure. 
</P>
<P>
	Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said doctors told him  
Dierker's prognosis is ``excellent.'' Dierker told Hunsicker he'd 
been having severe headaches in the days prior to his collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe that stress is going to affect a manager to  
the point where he's going to lose consciousness. From what I've 
been reading, he had a problem before,'' Montreal's Felipe Alou 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had some tough times in 1996 during the offseason, not  
during the season,'' he said. ``It had nothing to do with the game. 
Problems begin any month of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	White Sox manager Jerry Manuel said he took a physical in spring  
training. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that's a good barometer,'' he said. ``Who's  
stressed in spring training? There's nothing going on, it's 
relaxed, the workouts are short, the games don't count, you're 
playing golf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most teams insure the contracts of their managers, forcing them  
to take physicals at the time of the signing -- but not necessarily 
repeated until a new deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The exams often include a general checkup, an EKG, a blood test  
and a prostate-specific antigen (PSA) test for prostate cancer. 
Managers over 50 frequently take treadmill tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly, 48, broke a small blood vessel in his eye in November and  
lost part of his vision. Since then, he has a medical evaluation 
every three months. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody right away wants to relate it to stress,'' San  
Francisco's Dusty Baker said. ``What was the stress that did it to 
Larry?'' 
</P>
<P>
	At 68, Cincinnati's Jack McKeon has spent most of his life  
dealing with the daily pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like the stress, to be honest with you. I don't really view  
it as stress. Probably because I've been in it so long, I don't 
live or die with every game,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most managers try to find a way to relax away from baseball.  
</P>
<P>
	Baker likes to fish, Kelly spends time at the race track. Manuel  
swims, Rothschild runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lifestyle is not conducive to end stress,'' Rothschild  
said. ``You end up going to bed late and by the time you wake up 
you're reading the newspaper and you're back into the rut again.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
