<HEADLINE> Boeing Anounces 737 Jetliner Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Co. on Monday announced orders and options  
for 45 737 jetliners, deals worth more than $2 billion if all 
options are exercised. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcements were the first of what is expected to be a  
flurry of deals to be made public at the Paris Air Show. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing said Midway Airlines ordered 15 new-generation 737-700s  
and took options for 10 more. The value of the deal was not 
announced, but Boeing lists the price of the 126-seat twinjet 
between $41.5 million-$59 million. At that price the firm orders 
would be worth at least $622.5 million, and all 25 planes would be 
worth $1 billion or more. 
</P>
<P>
	Midway, whose hub is in Raleigh-Durham, N.C., is an East Coast  
regional carrier. It also will lease two additional 737-700s from 
GE Capital Aviation Services, with the first of those to be 
delivered in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Jet Airways of India ordered 10 737-800s, worth approximately  
$550 million, with deliveries to begin in 2001 and continue through 
2003. The 162-passenger planes will be used on domestic Indian 
routes. 
</P>
<P>
	CIT Group Inc. announced an agreement to buy 10 737  
next-generation planes, with the right to convert to earlier models 
of the 737, and options to acquire more planes over a four-year 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the deal was not announced, but would be worth  
about $500 million according to Boeing's price list. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based financial services company will take delivery  
of the new planes over a three-year period starting in the second 
quarter of 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	In other announcements from the air show, Rolls-Royce said it  
has received orders totaling $275 million to provide jet engines 
for Airbus Industrie A320 and A330 airliners for CIT and two other 
aircraft leasing companies. 
</P>
<P>
	CIT has ordered 15 A320s to be powered Rolls-Royce by V2500  
engines, the British company said. Deliveries are to start in the 
fourth quarter of 2000. CIT also ordered Rolls-Royce Trent 700 
engines to power three A330s. 
</P>
<P>
	Boullion Aviation Services Inc. of Seattle has ordered 15 A320s,  
with deliveries planned from February 2002 to November 2006, 
Rolls-Royce said, and Debis AirFinance of the Netherlands has 
ordered at least 20 V2500-powered A320s. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
