<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EEOC Can Order Gov't To Pay Damages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal agency that protects workers  
against job discrimination can order other federal agencies to pay 
damages to employees they discriminate against, the Supreme Court 
ruled today. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-4 decision said federal law allows the Equal Employment  
Opportunity Commission to require federal agencies to pay 
compensatory damages, intended to reimburse for harm a worker 
suffered, such as emotional distress. 
</P>
<P>
	``We conclude that the EEOC possesses the legal authority to  
enforce (anti-discrimination law) through an award of compensatory 
damages,'' Justice Stephen G. Breyer wrote for the court. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal employees are required to take their discrimination  
complaints to the EEOC before going to federal court in an effort 
to encourage ``quicker, less formal'' resolution of such disputes, 
Breyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring the EEOC from awarding compensatory damages would  
``force into court matters that the EEOC might otherwise have 
resolved,'' the justice added. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal appeals courts had disagreed over whether the EEOC can  
force federal agencies to pay workers compensatory damages. 
</P>
<P>
	The case involves discrimination claims filed under a major  
anti-bias law known as Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. 
In 1991, Congress voted to allow workers who are victims of job 
bias to collect compensatory damages in addition to back pay and 
other remedies previously allowed under the law. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal workers who file discrimination claims under Title VII  
must complain first to their agency, then go through an EEOC 
administrative proceeding. If they are dissatisfied with the EEOC's 
findings, they can go to federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	In today's case, an accountant for the Department of Veterans  
Affairs argued that the EEOC did not have the authority to award 
him compensatory damages. A federal appeals court agreed and gave 
him a chance to seek such damages in federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Gibson began his VA career in Albuquerque, N.M., in 1988  
and transferred to Hines, Ill., in 1990. He applied for a promotion 
in 1992 but a less-experienced woman was chosen instead. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibson filed a sex-discrimination claim, but the VA found no  
illegal conduct. He appealed to the EEOC, which found that the VA 
had discriminated against him and ordered the VA to give him a 
promotion and back pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The VA was late in complying with the commission's order, and  
Gibson sued in federal court. His lawsuit sought the back pay and 
promotion that he belatedly received, and also requested 
compensatory damages for emotional distress. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge threw out Gibson's lawsuit, saying the back pay  
and promotion issues were moot and that he should have raised the 
damages claim first in the EEOC proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed and said Gibson  
was entitled to a trial on his claim for damages. The EEOC is not 
authorized to make such awards, so Gibson's failure to raise the 
issue before the commission was irrelevant, the appeals court said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court said the appeals court was wrong. The justices  
ordered the appeals court to consider other issues raised by Gibson 
in an effort to collect damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Breyer's opinion was joined by Justices John Paul Stevens,  
Sandra Day O'Connor, David H. Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Dissenting were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices  
Anthony M. Kennedy, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing for the four, Kennedy said the 1991 amendment ``does not  
so much as mention the EEOC, much less empower it to award or 
authorize money damages.'' He also said the federal government had 
not waived its sovereign immunity against awards. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is West vs. Gibson, 98-238.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
