<HEADLINE> Valentine To Talk With NL President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- New York Mets manager Bobby Valentine expects  
to talk to NL president Len Coleman on Tuesday about his two-game 
suspension for returning to the dugout in disguise after being 
ejected. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine said before the start of a series Monday against the  
Cincinnati Reds that he had not yet spoken to Coleman, who imposed 
the suspension and fined him $5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspension is on hold while Valentine appeals.  
</P>
<P>
	Valentine declined to talk about donning the disguise Monday,  
other than to say: ``At the time it served the purpose because I 
thought levity was needed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine was ejected by plate umpire Randy Marsh in the 12th  
inning of a game last Wednesday for arguing a catcher's 
interference call on Mike Piazza. 
</P>
<P>
	The manager later returned in disguise, wearing eye black on his  
upper lip, sunglasses and a hat. A television camera quickly 
spotted him, although Valentine insisted he stayed a step away from 
the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	A National League rule stipulates that an ejected manager must  
remain in the clubhouse until the game ends or leave the stadium. 
He also may sit in the stands away from the bullpen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
