<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Baptists To Recruit in Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Southern Baptists open their annual  
convention Tuesday, and the agenda includes yet another attempt by 
their leaders to distance the nation's largest Protestant 
denomination from its segregationist past. 
</P>
<P>
	The convention's president, the Rev. Paige Patterson, is  
expected to propose that the denomination diversify and broaden its 
appeal in inner cities by forming multiethnic congregations from 
Boston to Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what I can do to change things 100 years ago,''  
said the Rev. Phil Roberts of the convention's North American 
Mission Board. ``I do know what I can do now: Take the Gospel and 
reach out and minister to all the city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That would mark a dramatic shift for a denomination whose 16  
million members live mostly in the suburbs, small towns and rural 
areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The denomination was formed in 1845 by rural whites who insisted  
on their right to own slaves. During the civil rights era, blacks 
were not welcome in most Southern Baptist churches. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years ago, the denomination apologized to blacks for 150  
years of tolerating racism. It now has an estimated 2,800 churches 
with mostly black members -- a tiny sliver of the thousands of black 
Baptist churches. 
</P>
<P>
	The new outreach plan is less about reconciliation than growth,  
said the Rev. David Key, director of Baptist Studies at Emory 
University's Candler School of Theology. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Southern Baptists have not been successful in an urban  
setting,'' he said. ``They want to be more than a white Southern 
rural denomination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, Southern Baptists are looking forward to more fervor  
than fighting at this year's gathering in the Georgia Dome. They 
are hoping for an end to the battles between conservatives and 
moderates of recent years, and they said they don't expect more 
grand announcements, like the 1997 Disney boycott or the decision 
to target Jews for proselytizing. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you are going to see in this convention is a return to  
normalcy,'' said the Rev. Timothy George, dean of Beeson Divinity 
School at Sanford University in Birmingham, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	Patterson, who helped engineer a conservative resurgence in the  
convention, is expected to be re-elected without opposition, and 
many moderates are sitting this convention out. Attendance is not 
expected to exceed 14,000. It was once as high as 45,519 people, in 
Dallas in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Patterson has long been critical of President Clinton, who is a  
Southern Baptist, and has called on the president's home church to 
discipline him for his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	During a radio show Monday, Patterson made similar comments,  
saying the president should be disciplined for calling for the 
observance of Gay and Lesbian Pride Month. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for Clinton have addressed criticism from Patterson by  
saying the president disagrees with his church's stands on several 
issues. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 14:40:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stanley Cup Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- How difficult is it switching positions in  
the middle of the Stanley Cup finals? It appears to be a snap for 
Darryl Sydor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas Stars' defenseman expects to see some action at  
forward on the top line with Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen in Game 
4 on Tuesday night because of a groin injury to Brett Hull. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have seen some spot duty (at forward),'' Sydor said. ``I've  
been with these guys before, and I know what my role is. It gives 
me more freedom with the puck, be a little more creative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sydor said his role will be ``to bring energy and physical  
(play) to the line. I'll try to make some room for Mike and Jere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sydor wasn't sure how much action he would see on the top line,  
but ``right now I'm thinking about being a forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sydor was asked if he found anything different at Monday's  
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, they passed to me,'' said Sydor of his new linemates.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MARINE MIDLAND MELTDOWN:* Players in the Stanley Cup finals  
have said the ice couldn't be any worse than it was at Reunion 
Arena in Dallas. They hadn't played in Buffalo yet. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres' Curtis Brown said it was actually worse at Marine  
Midland Arena for Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	How bad was it?  
</P>
<P>
	``The only way to control the puck was to put in your pocket, it  
was bouncing so much,'' Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STRAIGHT TALKER:* Buffalo's Dixon Ward just loves talking to  
the press. His teammates love it, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we don't feel like talking, he takes some of the pressure  
off the rest of us,'' Rob Ray said. 
</P>
<P>
	What do the Sabres think about Ward's relationship with  
reporters? 
</P>
<P>
	``Well,'' Ray said with a straight face, ``no one will talk to  
him at home, and we won't talk to him here, so he has to have 
someone to talk to.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *INFORMATION, PLEASE:* While the Buffalo Sabres went through  
their morning skate at the Marine Midland Arena on Monday, there 
was a ``spy'' watching them -- Ken Hitchcock. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas Stars coach had a cup of coffee in his hand and was  
standing in the entrance way to the ice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any line changes?'' Hitchcock asked a reporter.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a secret,'' the reporter responded.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TWO FOR ONE:* If the Dallas Stars win the Stanley Cup, it will  
mean two Cups in a short time for Rick Wilson's family. 
</P>
<P>
	Son Landon Wilson, a right wing with Providence of the AHL, just  
won the Calder Cup when the Bruins wrapped their series in five 
games against the Rochester Americans. Rick Wilson, of course, is 
the Stars' assistant coach. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *COMING OF AGE:* Is age a factor as the Stanley Cup finals get  
deeper into the series? That question was posed to Buffalo Sabres 
coach Lindy Ruff, whose team's average age is about three years 
younger than the Dallas Stars and theoretically would have the 
``younger'' legs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was thinking that theory earlier, but not any more,'' said  
Ruff, whose Sabres trail the Stars 2-1 in the best-of-7 series. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RUFFED UP:* Lindy Ruff was asked if there was a sense of  
impending doom in Buffalo regarding his team, considering that the 
Sabres were not only down 2-1 in the Stanley Cup finals but also 
unable to generate much offense against the Dallas Stars. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't been out on the town,'' Ruff said, then quipped  
after a pause, ``It seems like you guys have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ruff didn't stop there.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know, I was playing with my two 4-year-olds on their  
bikes. They're OK with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WRIST SHOT:* Ever since Dallas center Mike Modano had his left  
wrist injured in Game 2 of the finals, the Buffalo Sabres have said 
they would make it a target. They went after it in Game 3, to no 
avail. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of padding on it, they can whack all they  
want,'' Modano said Monday, displaying a heavily padded wrist. ``It 
didn't bother me.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WATCHING HIMSELF:* Brett Hull didn't skate in Monday's Dallas  
Stars practice because of his groin injury, but did watch his 
teammates from the bench in a warmup jacket. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the funniest practice I had all year,'' Hull said.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LOVE-HATE RELATIONSHIP:* Dallas goalie Ed Belfour loves the way  
his teammates block shots in front. He also hates it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's frustrating at times,'' Belfour said. ``I'll be yelling  
for them to get out and let me see the puck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars' shot-blocking ability helped them limit the Sabres to  
12 shots in Game 3, tying a Stanley Cup finals record. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
