<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Huang Arraigned on Conspiracy Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Democratic Party fund-raiser John Huang has  
been arraigned on a conspiracy charge as part of a plea bargain 
reached after he helped the government's campaign finance 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	He is expected to plead guilty in federal court next Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors are seeking a sentence of a year's probation, 500  
hours of community service, a $10,000 fine and a requirement that 
he continue cooperating with the government. Huang's plea agreement 
specifies that he has already participated in 21 interviews with 
prosecutors and agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang, who appeared in court Monday, was charged with conspiracy  
to defraud the Federal Election Commission by helping raise $7,500 
in donations and then reimbursing the individuals who provided the 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang was the top U.S.-based representative for the Lippo Group,  
an Indonesia-based financial conglomerate, before President Clinton 
appointed him in 1994 to a position at the Commerce Department. 
Huang later became a finance vice chairman of the Democratic 
National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The DNC returned $3 million in donations it received leading up  
to the 1996 election -- most of it raised by Huang and Clinton's 
friend Yah Lin ``Charlie'' Trie -- because of concerns the money 
came from improper or foreign sources. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
