<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Testifies in Reggie Lewis Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A man with past drug convictions testified Monday  
he saw Boston Celtics captain Reggie Lewis snort a ``white, powdery 
substance'' in a restaurant bathroom a year before he died. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald J. Marks, 49, told the jury in the malpractice trial  
stemming from Lewis' death that he witnessed the drug use in the 
bathroom of a Saugus pizza restaurant during a Celtics benefit 
auction in July 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Marks said he saw Lewis standing with an unidentified man, who  
was holding the substance up to the player's nostril. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was sniffing that white, powdery substance'' said Marks, a  
Celtics fan attended the auction. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis died of a cardiac arrhythmia while practicing jump shots  
in July 1993. His widow, Donna Harris-Lewis, sued Dr. Gilbert Mudge 
and two consultants, claiming they misdiagnosed and mistreated the 
NBA All-Star's heart condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge said publicly that Lewis suffered from a neurological  
fainting condition, even after a team of top doctors diagnosed him 
with a potentially fatal cardiac problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Possible cocaine use by Lewis has been a central issue at the  
trial since Mudge testified last week that Lewis confessed to past 
drug use two weeks before he died. 
</P>
<P>
	One part of Mudge's defense argument is that the belated  
admission made an accurate diagnosis impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys on Monday also read the sworn deposition  
testimony of Wayne Lebeaux, a former Celtics ball boy and equipment 
manager, who said he smoked marijuana with Lewis at a Maine 
basketball camp in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for Harris-Lewis attacked Marks' credibility and cited  
his criminal history, which includes drug offenses and an alleged 
attack on his wife, who says in court documents that he tried to 
run her over with a car and sprayed Lysol in her face. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Robert Harley also suggested that Marks' Celtics season  
tickets were revoked by the team after Marks tried to give packets 
of white powder to the wives or girlfriends of two players. Marks 
denied the claim. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Lebeaux, plaintiff's attorneys suggested he was bitter  
after being fired by the Celtics in 1997 after more than 15 years 
with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial, now in its seventh week, could be in the hands of the  
jury by Thursday as the defense wraps up its case. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 23:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> School Building Costs Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As school districts struggle to fix or build  
new schools for growing student enrollments, lawmakers are touting 
plans to help ease the burden on taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic Sen. Bob Graham of Florida wants to use private  
investors to build public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Clinton administration says its school  
construction proposals were validated by government figures showing 
that states and local districts are spending and borrowing billions 
of dollars more for public school construction. 
</P>
<P>
	School districts nationwide spent $18.7 billion on school  
construction in 1996, the latest year for which data was available, 
according to Census Bureau data released Monday. The districts 
spent $15.9 billion in 1995 and $14.4 billion in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a tremendous need as evidenced by these figures,''  
said Julie Green, the Education Department spokeswoman. ``And it's 
a problem in many different communities -- city, suburban or 
rural.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One third of America's schools, about 25,000 schools, are in  
need of at least one major repair, according to the General 
Accounting Office, Congress' investigative agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Green said a Clinton administration plan would address the need  
to fix existing school buildings. The plan would make construction 
and repair of more than 6,000 schools cheaper for states and 
districts by providing federal tax credits to pay the interest on 
bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham's plan, meanwhile, would cut red tape, said the senator's  
spokesman, Chris Hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``It decreases the time in which schools can be built,'' Hand  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who oversees tax policy for the  
House, has a similar plan to create more money for school 
construction. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationwide enrollment of pre-kindergarten through 12th grade  
students reached 44.8 million in 1996, up from 44.1 million 
students in 1995 and 43.5 million in 1994, according to the Census 
data, available on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The Census data also indicate that:  
</P>
<P>
	--Texas, New York, and Florida spent the most among the states.  
Texas spent $2 billion, followed by New York and Florida at $1.6 
billion each. 
</P>
<P>
	--School systems in five states borrowed more than $1 billion  
each for building construction, reconstruction and refinancing: 
Texas, $2.7 billion; Pennsylvania, $2.5 billion; New York, $1.9 
billion; Illinois, $1.5 billion, and Florida, $1.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Individual state governments contributing the largest  
percentage of education revenues were Hawaii, which, unlike other 
states, has a single, state-run school system, 90 percent; New 
Mexico, 73 percent, and Delaware, Michigan and Washington, 68 
percent each. 
</P>
<P>
	--States spending the highest average amount per pupil were New  
Jersey, $9,208; the District of Columbia, $8,510; and New York, 
$8,374. The average nationwide was $5,656. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey of local government finances includes revenues,  
expenditures and debt for public elementary and secondary school 
systems with more than 15,000 students. The figures, which have not 
been adjusted for price and wage changes occurring throughout the 
years, are also not subject to sampling error. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The Web site is www.census.gov/govs/www/school.html/  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
