<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Book: Clinton Excuses Irked Lawyer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One of President Clinton's lawyers hit the  
roof when he heard the president might argue that he was truthful 
when he denied having a sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky 
because oral sex did not fit the definition, a new book says. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't do this,'' the book quotes lawyer Robert Bennett as  
telling a Clinton adviser. ``It's insanity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton made that argument anyway, in testimony to  
independent prosecutor Kenneth Starr's grand jury. And Clinton's 
assertion that oral sex was not a sexual act helped him escape 
removal from office in the impeachment trial. 
</P>
<P>
	A phone conversation between Bennett and Clinton adviser Mickey  
Kantor is recounted in ``Shadow: Five Presidents and the Legacy of 
Watergate,'' by Washington Post reporter Bob Woodward. The 
Associated Press obtained a copy in advance of Tuesday's release of 
the book. 
</P>
<P>
	Another passage shows Starr standing firm in his determination  
to send a report to the House full of explicit detail on Clinton's 
relationship with the former intern, despite attempts by some on 
his staff to have him focus on the president's alleged legal 
wrongdoing and go easy on the sex. 
</P>
<P>
	The report's lengthy narrative ``shows how pathetic Clinton is,  
that he needs therapy, not removal,'' the book quotes Starr lawyer 
Brett Kavanaugh as saying. ``Our job is not to get Clinton out (of 
office). It's just to give information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Starr is said to have dug in, telling staff members: ``I  
love the narrative!'' 
</P>
<P>
	In reconstructing events behind the drawn-out Lewinsky affair,  
Woodward quotes private conversations among leading players that he 
says came from at least one source -- in most cases unidentified. In 
an excerpt published earlier by the Post, Bennett was quoted as 
having warned Clinton bluntly that he should be honest about any 
extramarital affairs. Bennett did not return phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett himself had laid the groundwork for parsing the legal  
meaning of sex when, in representing Clinton in the Paula Jones 
sexual harassment case, he had objected to a broad definition of 
sexual relations. The judge drew a more limited definition. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bennett told Kantor he had just been throwing the usual  
legal hurdles into a case on behalf of a client and did not think 
any strategy making a distinction between types of sexual acts 
would work. 
</P>
<P>
	``These distinctions are absurd,'' he is quoted as saying.  
``This crap won't fly with anyone. ... It's awful, awful advice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton went on to testify to the Starr grand jury that he had  
an inappropriate relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, but said, ``I did 
not have sexual relations, as I understood this term to be 
defined,'' with her. 
</P>
<P>
	When pressed, he said he did not consider the type of relations  
the two had to fall within the definition drawn in the Jones case. 
</P>
<P>
	A footnote: Among the acknowledgments, Woodward thanks his  
agent, Robert B. Barnett, who happens to be the law partner of 
David Kendall, Clinton's lawyer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 04:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Tutored on Plastic Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- The group of physicians from around the  
world watched intently as Dr. William Magee Jr. detached the lower 
jaw of the 15-year-old girl, pulling it forward before filling in 
the gaps with bone from her skull. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can get the mandible forward, then she can breathe  
properly,'' Magee told his fellow plastic surgeons, who then 
peppered him with questions on technique. 
</P>
<P>
	The 50 doctors and 15 anesthesiologists had come to Norfolk from  
22 countries as far as Vietnam, Colombia and Kenya for a two-week 
tutorial that would teach them how to treat children in need of 
facial reconstructive surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12th year of the program, run by the nonprofit humanitarian  
group Operation Smile, ends today with a trip to a local amusement 
park. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they get from this is a sense that they have a  
responsibility to take care of people in their own country and the 
world,'' said Magee, who founded Operation Smile with his wife, 
Kathleen, in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Operation Smile also sends doctors abroad to perform free  
surgeries on children with cleft lips and other facial deformities. 
In developing countries, one child in 500 suffers from a facial 
deformity -- almost double the rate in the United States, the group 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. program allows doctors to attended lectures, present  
their own talks and practice surgical techniques on rats and 
cadavers. Begun in 1987 with about 10 doctors, this year's group of 
65 was the largest thus far. 
</P>
<P>
	``You share your ideas of what is working in your country and is  
not working well,'' said Dr. Ernesto Barbosa, a plastic surgeon 
from Colombia. ``You are learning about what people do around the 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The doctors also observed Magee perform five operations which  
were too complicated to be undertaken overseas. Among his patients 
were a 20-year-old Kenyan woman with a jaw deformity and a 
5-year-old Moroccan boy with a facial cleft. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Hoang Quoc Ky of Vietnam found himself especially interested  
in the craniofacial surgery. His country's hospitals don't have the 
equipment needed to offer it yet, but hopes to by 2005, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see everything here, go back home and look at the budget,''  
Ky said. ``We get equipment step by step.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just as important as imparting practical knowledge, Magee said,  
is to help doctors ``realize they are part of this international 
organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Ostensibly, it's all based around medicine,'' Magee said.  
``But what they get is a lot more.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
