<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China's Exports Rise in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's exports showed improvement in May for the  
first time this year, rising to $15.53 billion, or 4.2 percent 
higher than the same month a year earlier, official media reported 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The rising exports -- reflecting some recovery in regional demand  
-- created a strong trade surplus that lends stability to the 
Chinese currency, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports rose in May to $13.66 billion, up 21.5 percent from the  
year-earlier total. That left a surplus for the month of $1.87 
billion, nearly double the $960 million surplus registered in 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebound in exports followed declines in the first four  
months of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first five months of 1999, exports fell 5.3 percent from  
the year-earlier total to $67.55 billion, according to figures 
released by Chinese customs and reported by the Xinhua News Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports rose 15.3 percent in the January-May period to $60.48  
billion, resulting in a trade surplus of $7.07 billion, the report 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had worried that the narrowing trade gap might pressure  
Beijing into devaluing the yuan to make Chinese products more 
competitive on world markets. Senior Chinese officials have 
repeatedly promised to keep the currency's exchange rate steady in 
1999. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
