<P>
	Greenspan Cautious on Productivity  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan warned  
Congress today that the productivity that has played a considerable 
role in keeping inflation low cannot last forever. Private analysts 
interpreted his remarks as a hint of future Fed increases to slow 
the economy. They said Greenspan was likely to make that warning 
more explicitly when he appears before Congress again on Thursday. 
David Jones, chief economist at Aubrey G. Lanston &AMP; Co. in New 
York, and other economists noted signs of economic rebound in Japan 
and other countries, and said Greenspan is likely to signal that 
U.S. interest rates will need to be increased to slow the U.S. 
economy. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Chief Warns on Hasty Regulation  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- IBM Chairman Louis Gerstner Jr. warned  
Congress against hastily enacting legislation to govern the 
fast-changing technology industry, saying that policies rushed into 
place today could become obsolete quickly. Gerstner, speaking at 
the Joint Economic Committee's High Tech Summit, said the rise of 
networks that connect people around the world already has begun to 
transform education, business and government. But he estimated that 
this process is only about one-sixth of the way complete, and that 
more information is needed to develop a model for public policy. 

</P>
<P>
	Automakers, UAW Begin Contract Talks  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- National contract talks began today  
between the United Auto Workers and Ford Motor Co., which enjoys 
the best union relations among Detroit's automakers and may set the 
standard for an economic package for the start of a new century. 
Among the key issues for the industry this year is a change in 
manufacturing that could rely more heavily on components made by 
lower-paid workers who are not members of the UAW. Health and 
safety, job security, wages and benefits remain perennial major 
considerations. The triennial negotiations kicked off with 
ceremonial handshakes over the main bargaining table at Ford 
headquarters. Similar ceremonies are set for tomorrow at 
DaimlerChrysler and Wednesday at GM. 

</P>
<P>
	Computer Virus Keeps Spreading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Computer support lines were overwhelmed today  
with calls reporting new outbreaks of a software virus that spreads 
not only by e-mail, but through shared files on a network. The 
development dashed hopes that Worm.Explore.Zip might be contained 
more quickly than the recent Melissa outbreak. Last week, the 
primary means of infection seemed to be through a friendly e-mail 
that tricks the recipient into opening an attached file, uncaging 
Worm.Explore.Zip. But in addition to ruining files stored on an 
individual computer, the virus apparently ``worms'' its way into 
other computers linked to the same network server. 

</P>
<P>
	Qwest Bids Billions for Telecom Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Qwest's bold bid to acquire U S West Inc. and  
Frontier Corp. lost some of its luster today. Investors pummeled 
Qwest's stock, reducing the value of the initial $55 billion deal 
to $43 billion. Qwest's unsolicited proposals aim to break up the 
two companies' agreements to be acquired by Global Crossing Inc., 
and could start a bidding war between Qwest and Global Crossing. 
The two companies are fighting to be the first to build a global 
network of high-speed fiber optic cables that will bring consumers 
and businesses a host of video, audio and Internet services. Qwest 
stock was at 34 1/8, down 10 3/4. U S West was at 58, up 3 1/8. Frontier was 
at 57 3/8, up 1 13/16. Global Crossing was at 50 3/8, down 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Launches MSN Mobile  
</P>
<P>
	REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. today launched MSN Mobile,  
enabling customers to receive wireless information services on 
their interactive pagers and cellular phones. Microsoft and other 
operators of Internet portal sites, including Yahoo! Inc. and 
America Online Inc., are scrambling to offer Internet content on 
wireless devices, handheld computers and television in addition to 
personal computers. Microsoft said its latest service, a version of 
its MSN online service, will allow consumers to control what they 
receive and when they receive it, and to tailor content to fit 
their needs or location. Microsoft stock was at 77 9/16, down 9/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart Is Buying Asda  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Global retailing leader Wal-Mart Stores Inc. today  
announced its arrival in Britain with the $10.7 billion takeover of 
Asda Group PLC, the country's third largest supermarket chain. The 
deal, which more than doubles the Wal-Mart's international sales 
and consolidates its position in Europe, promises to increase 
competition in the British retail sector. ``Retailers over here are 
scared of Wal-Mart,'' said retail analyst Richard Hyman of the 
London firm Verdict. ``It's of a size that's beyond the experience 
of everyone else. Things will never be the same again. Wal-Mart's 
offer trumps a $9.4 billion deal previously agreed upon between 
Asda and Britain's Kingfisher PLC. 

</P>
<P>
	Amtrak Trains Return to Oklahoma  
</P>
<P>
	ARDMORE, Okla. (AP) -- Twenty years after the last passenger  
train left Oklahoma, Amtrak rolled back into the state with daily 
service between Oklahoma City and Fort Worth, Texas. Hundreds of 
people who turned out along the tracks in this town just north of 
the Texas state line to catch a glimpse of the gleaming silver 
train, called the Heartland Flyer. State leaders had lobbied for 
years for the return of train service. The Heartland Flyer will 
allow travelers from Oklahoma City to connect in Fort Worth with 
trains that serve Chicago, San Antonio, Los Angeles, New Orleans 
and Florida. 

</P>
<P>
	Redenbacher Plant To Shut Down  
</P>
<P>
	VALPARAISO, Ind. (AP) -- The Orville Redenbacher factory in the  
city where he invented his brand of popcorn will produce its last 
kernel next year. ConAgra, the Nebraska company that owns the 
plant, said last month it will consolidate the Valparaiso popcorn 
bottling and microwave popcorn packaging operations with those at 
other plants. Valparaiso, about 40 miles southeast of Chicago, will 
lose 230 jobs and a part of its identity. An annual popcorn 
festival has been held in the city since 1979, attracting as many 
as 80,000 people each year. 

</P>
