<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Co. Dynegy Acquires Illinova </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DECATUR, Ill. (AP) -- The chairman of Midwest electric utility  
Illinova Corp. on Monday said Houston-based energy marketer Dynegy 
Inc. $2 billion acquisition of his company is about growth -- not 
cost cutting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our two companies are an excellent strategic fit with each  
other. The merger creates tremendous opportunities for each company 
much faster than we could have achieved alone,'' chairman Charles 
Bayless said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new firm, to be called Dynegy, will be a ``full-service''  
energy company with about $17 billion in annual revenue, the 
companies said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both boards of directors have unanimously approved the  
acquisition, which still must be approved by federal and state 
regulators and shareholders for each company. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company will be based in Houston. Illinois Power, an  
Illinova subsidiary that serves about 650,000 electric and natural 
gas customers in central Illinois, will keep its Decatur 
headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies expect to eventually eliminate about 5 percent of  
their combined work force of 6,500, or about 325 jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Watson, Dynegy's chairman and chief executive officer,  
said he expects the job cuts will mostly be accomplished through 
reduced hiring, attrition and options such as early retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Dynegy shareholders will receive 0.69 share  
in the new company or $16.50 in cash for each Dynegy share. 
Illinova shareholders will exchange their shares on a 
share-for-share basis. Dynegy will also acquire an unspecified 
amount of Illinova debt in the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson will keep his title in the new company. Bayless,  
Illinova's chairman, president and chief executive officer, will be 
a nonexecutive director. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this merger, I think we continue to distinguish ourselves  
as one of the few players in the business with experience in energy 
marketing and energy trading and power generation,'' Watson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dynegy, known as Natural Gas Clearinghouse until a year ago,  
began in 1985 as a wholesale marketer of natural gas. In the past 
few years, it has become a full-scale energy marketer. 
</P>
<P>
	Dynegy's major shareholders -- Chevron Corp.; BG PLC, parent of  
British Gas; and Nova Chemicals -- have agreed to the merger, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron, which currently owns 29 percent interest in Dynegy,  
said it has elected to take all stock and also plans to invest 
between $200 million and $240 million in the new company. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger is expected to close by the end of the first quarter  
in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Illinova rose 31 1/4 cents to $25.62 1/2 on the New York  
Stock Exchange. Shares of Dynegy fell 43 3/4 cents to $18.25, also on 
the NYSE. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
