<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Road Repairs To Slow Summer Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Travelers hitting the road this summer will  
find the going slow. 
</P>
<P>
	Widespread repair work on state and federal highways, combined  
with a record number of drivers expected to take advantage of 
still-low gas prices, threaten to make long-distance treks more 
like rush-hour commuting. 
</P>
<P>
	The red flag from experts: Do not expect to go more than 40  
miles on major roads without encountering the cones and barrels of 
a construction zone, from California's Yosemite National Park to 
Pennsylvania's Amish country. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the work is the first fruit of the $203 billion highway  
bill that President Clinton signed into law a year ago Wednesday. 
The funding is a 40 percent increase over the nation's previous 
highway bill, and unlike past years, all states but Massachusetts 
saw a sizable jump in their share of the pie. 
</P>
<P>
	Government leaders gathered on Capitol Hill last week to  
celebrate the first anniversary of the law, which they said would 
create safer roads, ease urban congestion, alleviate suburban 
sprawl and promote mass transit. 
</P>
<P>
	The joviality was accompanied by a sober warning: The added  
construction has increased the risk of traffic accidents at 
construction sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Each year more than 700 people are killed and 37,000 injured in  
such accidents. One in seven deaths involves a construction worker. 
Many involve motorists who slam into the vehicle in front of them 
when it suddenly slows for a flagman or a police officer directing 
traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	Political leaders asked the public to be vigilant behind the  
wheel during what will be a taxing summer on the roads. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is it possible that with the 43 percent increase in funding  
there will be a 43 percent increase in construction zone 
accidents?'' asked Rep. James Oberstar of Minnesota, the top 
Democrat on the House Transportation Committee. ``It need not 
happen, it must not happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They also appealed for patience.  
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., the committee's chairman, added: ``What  
seems like wasted time in traffic now will mean time and lives 
saved in the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The roadwork itself spreads from sea to shining sea.  
</P>
<P>
	The main entrance into Yosemite is under construction, closing  
it to traffic from 10:30 p.m. to 6:30 a.m. daily. The speed limit 
there has also been reduced from 35 mph to 25 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. 30 near Lancaster, Pa., a main route into the area's  
popular Amish country, has closed lanes, and backups of as much as 
30 minutes are projected. Interstate 75, a north-south route from 
Michigan to Florida, will have a dozen construction zones, and 
there will be three on I-87 around New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	On I-15 in Salt Lake City, 17 miles of road are being doubled  
from four lanes to eight in preparation for the 2002 Winter 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	AAA, the nation's largest automobile club, recommends that  
drivers plan routes around the construction zones and be ready when 
they encounter them. And the group says drivers should check their 
vehicle's cooling system, since it is more important in traffic 
because an engine doesn't get the benefit of fast-moving air. 
</P>
<P>
	Drivers should also check the effectiveness of their air  
conditioning before setting out, since long delays can make a hot 
interior unbearable. 
</P>
<P>
	AAA spokesman Mitch Fuqua had one final piece of advice for this  
summer of snarl: slow down for safety's sake. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you see an orange barrel, that means there's probably  
somebody behind it doing work,'' Fuqua said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
