<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Wants Prison Hitching Posts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Alabama on Monday asked a federal judge  
for permission to resume handcuffing inmates to hitching posts in 
the hot sun when they refuse to work. 
</P>
<P>
	If U.S. District Judge Myron Thompson approves the request by  
Gov. Don Siegelman, Alabama will again become the only state using 
hitching posts to restrain inmates. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson ruled last year that the way the state was using the  
hitching posts -- leaving inmates in the sun for long hours without 
water or restroom breaks -- was unconstitutionally cruel. But he 
allowed the state to try to devise a constitutional method. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Haley, Siegelman's prison commissioner, said he believes  
the new policy proposed by the state Department of Corrections is 
constitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	It includes videotape monitoring of the hitching posts to make  
sure inmates get hourly water and restroom breaks, and it allows an 
inmate to be unhitched and to sit down the moment he agrees to go 
to work. 
</P>
<P>
	But inmate attorney Rhonda Brownstein argued during a court  
hearing Monday that except for the videotaping, the Siegelman 
policy differs little from the one used during Gov. Fob James' 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Restraining people this way is a form of corporal punishment  
and violates the Constitution,'' Brownstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson told the attorneys in the court hearing that he is  
reluctant to stop the Siegelman administration from trying out the 
new policy for a few months. 
</P>
<P>
	``The court doesn't want to be a super commissioner determining  
what's good policy for the future,'' the judge said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson will hear more testimony about the hitching posts  
Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
