<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Accepts Opposition's Attention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- To measure Gov. George W. Bush's  
campaign advantages now that he's off his own front porch and 
``running hard'' for the White House, check his opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Three days into his bid for votes in New Hampshire and Iowa,  
he's drawn a Republican debate challenge, a Democratic Party 
operation to rebut him and a GOP opponent's observation that this 
shouldn't be a coronation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am pleased that the Democrats are paying attention to me,''  
Bush said Monday on his first New Hampshire swing. ``What I like to 
say is I like to talk about me and I am glad that others are 
talking about me. 
</P>
<P>
	``They must be worried.''  
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats have assigned what politicians call a truth squad  
to track his campaign debut, disputing what he's said and done as a 
``compassionate conservative,'' his chosen label. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Steve Forbes challenged Bush to a series of five  
debates beginning next month, saying they should include all the 
GOP candidates. Debate challenges are standard for a candidate 
trying to catch a front-runner. So was Bush's brushoff. ``It is way 
too early for the debate on debates,'' said Karen Hughes, his press 
secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to have a coronation, we're going to have a  
process here,'' Bob Dole, the 1996 GOP nominee, said in Council 
Bluffs, Iowa, on behalf of his candidate-wife. Elizabeth Dole runs 
second in the preseason polling. 
</P>
<P>
	It is very early in the season for all of this; indeed, for any  
of it. But to get going and to keep going -- with Bush commanding 
the polls and absorbing the campaign donations -- everyone else has 
to find a route past the governor of Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, his year-old lead comes with no guarantees. Running first  
and staying there has proven too much for front-running candidates 
before. Indeed, Bush came to New Hampshire in a position unmatched 
in eight campaigns -- since Sen. Edmund S. Muskie arrived as the 
towering Democratic favorite in 1972 and quickly collapsed as a 
candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	In his Iowa and New Hampshire debuts, Bush was at pains to say  
that he knows he's late, and intends to work hard the rest of the 
way. ``I know how important New Hampshire is,'' he told some 900 
people at a sold-out luncheon of the Federation of Republican Women 
on Monday. ``You're first in the nation and I'm the last candidate 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said his late start showed that he keeps campaign  
commitments, as when he promised Texans to do his job with the 
state legislature before he moved to the national stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I'm a late arriver,'' he said. ``I'm taking my front  
porch campaign to every front porch in this state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those will be crowded porches. Bush draws them, and brings them  
with him. Three busloads of reporters and cameras, for example, to 
an overflow turnout at the Bow fire station. Another crowd, an 
advertised 500 supporters and campaign leaders, at a college in 
Goffstown. 
</P>
<P>
	All tightly scheduled, but with time for questions and  
predictable answers from the candidate. He was not out to break new 
ground on the issues -- ample time for detailed programs later, he 
said. Bush said his aim was to present broad themes and big issues 
to tell people what kind of president he would be. He said he'll 
have proposals for income tax cuts and more military spending, that 
he will work for free trade and better schools, that he will 
protect the dignity of the office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think ``I've been pretty darn specific,'' he said on WMUR-TV  
in Manchester. But the itemized 10-point plans can come later. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a long campaign, and there are a lot of hands to be  
shaken, a lot of speeches to be given,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	So he broke little new ground this first trip. He endorsed  
ethanol subsidies in Iowa, where they grow the corn used to 
manufacture the fuel. In New Castle, N.H., he said he would not 
make opposition to abortion a litmus test for Supreme Court 
appointments. Bush is personally opposed to abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he would not allow whatever he did in his  
admittedly reckless youth -- he won't be more specific -- to be used 
as a test of his candidacy. ``There is a game inn Washington, it is 
called gotcha,'' he said. ``It's the game where they float a rumor 
and make the candidate prove a negative, and I'm not playing the 
game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, he's leading in the game he is playing. But so far is  
only a beginning. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
