<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Satan Looks To End Scoring Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Miroslav Satan is a playmaker and  
shot-maker for the Buffalo Sabres, as witness his 40 goals and 66 
points during the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas Stars, however, have limited him to one assist in the  
Stanley Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tried to get him away from a couple of their matchups and  
tried to get him away from a couple of their defensive pairs,'' 
Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said Monday. ``We tried everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres have little time to tinker with their top scoring  
machine. They trail the Stars two games to one in the best-of-7 
series with Game 4 in Buffalo on Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The entire Buffalo offense is sputtering, with 29 points coming  
from defensemen Jason Woolley and Alexei Zhitnik. The Sabres can 
thank the Dallas defense for that. 
</P>
<P>
	Satan's struggle is most disturbing.  
</P>
<P>
	``They don't make the mistakes that would give Satan an  
opportunity,'' Ruff said. ``Every time he steps on the ice he's 
facing three or four of their biggest defensemen. There's no way 
around that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Satan's 40 goals led the Sabres during the regular season. He  
missed nine playoff games with a deep ankle bruise sustained in the 
first round but returned to form during the Eastern Conference 
finals against Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Satan (pronounced SHUH-tan) appeared rejuvenated on a new line  
with veteran Joe Juneau and speedy Geoff Sanderson, but has failed 
to score in three games in the Stanley Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	He has only two shots against the Stars. Both came in 26 minutes  
of ice time in Game 3, which was more playing time than any other 
forward in the game received. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, Satan has improved with additional playing time,  
and Ruff had him killing penalties and working power plays in Game 
3. The coach even tried different line combinations in an effort to 
get his regular-season star to shine again. 
</P>
<P>
	``The added ice time didn't result in a plus for us,'' Ruff  
said. ``If we're going to win the series, we need our big players 
to do something for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Satan feels the heat.  
</P>
<P>
	``I do feel the pressure and I'll try to respond the best way I  
can,'' he said. ``But right now there's not too much room and the 
whole team is having problems creating anything in their zone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres don't blame Satan for a scoring drought that is  
affecting the entire team. ``We're not putting any pressure on him 
to score,'' Sanderson said. ``That's everybody's job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not looking for this guy to somehow score three goals in  
Game 4,'' Juneau said. ``That's not the way it's going to happen. 
Miro, like everybody else, has to concentrate on playing well in 
our zone and being in the right position at the right time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He's just going to have to battle through the checking that  
he's getting,'' Sabres center Brian Holzinger said. ``In Game 3 
there wasn't any open ice for any of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Satan had two goals and an assist in Buffalo's first-round sweep  
of Ottawa before a shot by Zhitnik sidelined him in Game 3 of that 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not play in the Sabres' victory over Boston in the  
conference semifinals, and tallied one goal and three assists in 
the last three games against Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Satan practiced Monday on a line with Curtis Brown and Juneau.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's a guy who's dangerous in open ice, so we're going to have  
to get him the puck when he's in open ice,'' Holzinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not on his shoulders,'' Juneau said. ``It's on  
everybody's shoulders. I don't know why it's a subject of 
conversation. He hasn't scored in the finals, but who cares. 
Everybody has to do the job.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
