<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Version of Nasdaq Planned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- U.S. securities dealers plan to set up a Japanese  
version of the computerized Nasdaq Stock Market as early as next 
year, a Japanese paper reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The new exchange will focus on listing stocks of start-up firms  
based mainly in the United States and Japan, including some 
American companies with shares already listed on the Nasdaq, the 
Nihon Keizai financial daily said. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Securities Dealers will establish a  
joint Japanese subsidiary this summer with Tokyo-based Softbank 
Corp. and other companies, the paper said. It did not identify its 
sources for the report. 
</P>
<P>
	American and Japanese securities houses will be asked to serve  
as brokers, it added. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Zarb, the association's chairman, and other officials were  
expected to arrive in Tokyo on Monday for talks with Japan's 
Ministry of Finance about the exchange, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq is where the shares of many computer and technology  
companies are traded, including Microsoft Corp. and Intel Corp. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
