<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Finals Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- It's OK with Spurs center David Robinson if  
the NBA Finals between New York and San Antonio are billed as a 
showdown between the big city and a small town. 
</P>
<P>
	But good versus evil?  
</P>
<P>
	``Who's good?'' Robinson asked reporters Monday. ``There are  
some great guys on that team. I know Charlie Ward and Allan Houston 
and those guys are great guys. I don't know who you're talking 
about, evil. They're probably better than me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A devout Christian, Robinson said he's simply looking forward to  
what he expects will be a well-played best-of-7 series beginning 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be good, hard basketball,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	His friend and teammate, Avery Johnson, who shares Robinson's  
Christian beliefs, added that he doesn't care for the ``choir 
boys'' tag some are giving the Spurs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the `choir' part because that's associated with church  
and that's a good thing,'' Johnson said. ``But `choir boy' put 
together, I don't really like that because choir boys tend to have 
this soft personality and I don't think we have anybody on our team 
soft.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SUPER MARIO:* As the Spurs met the media Monday after practice,  
one player lingered around after all his teammates left and 
genuinely seemed to be enjoying himself spinning tales about his 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	Elie, 35, a New Yorker who grew up five minutes away from  
Madison Square Garden and played junior varsity ball with Chris 
Mullin, didn't break into the NBA until he was 26. Before that, he 
spent time playing in U.S. minor leagues and overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I'm home by myself, I think about playing in Portugal in  
a small farming town that closed at 8 o'clock. It had one street 
light, and you'd wake up in the morning and women were walking cows 
on the side of the road,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	After stints with the Lakers, 76ers, Warriors and Trail Blazers,  
Elie won championships with the Houston Rockets in 1994 and 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got a lot of guys who call me and say `Yo, you're in your  
third finals, I'm trying to get into one.' And I say I don't 
believe how it's been done. I'm amazed. I've played nine years in 
the league and I've got a chance to win three rings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just pinch myself sometimes and think I'm one of the  
luckiest guys that have played this game.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BLACK SOCKS BEGONE:* The Spurs saw what happened to the Indiana  
Pacers against the Knicks, and San Antonio doesn't plan to follow 
the Pacers' playoff practice of wearing black socks to show 
solidarity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think some of those guys look terrible in black socks and  
black sneakers,'' said Spurs forward Malik Rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs have no superstitions about clothing anyway, he added.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're just going to stay with what's gotten us here, and  
that's tremendous defense and great execution down the stretch -- 
and white socks,'' Rose said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FACTS AND FIGURES:* The Knicks are the first eighth-seeded team  
to make it to the finals. The 1980-81 and 1994-95 Houston Rockets 
made it as sixth seeds, and the 1968-69 Boston Celtics and 1977-78 
Seattle SuperSonics advanced as fourth seeds. ... With a 27-23 
(.540) regular-season record, the Knicks could become the team with 
the second-worst record ever to win a championship. The 1977-78 
Washington Bullets at 44-37 (.537) had the worst record of any team 
to win a title. ... Since the NBA went to a 2-3-2 format 15 years 
ago, no team has ever swept Games 3, 4 and 5. ... Since the 1990 
finals, the home team is 26-25. The home team won three of the six 
games in last year's finals between Utah and Chicago. ... Head 
coaches Gregg Popovich of San Antonio and Jeff Van Gundy of New 
York never played in the NBA. That makes this the first finals 
since 1981 in which at least one of the coaches did not have NBA 
playing experience. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BABIES, BABIES EVERYWHERE:* Allan Houston of the Knicks had an  
eventful weekend. Not only did New York win the Eastern Conference 
finals on Friday, but his wife gave birth to a girl Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston was not at the Knicks' practice Sunday because of his  
daughter's birth. 
</P>
<P>
	Jaren Jackson of the Spurs and his wife, Terri, are expecting  
their first child in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the couple isn't likely to have to worry about a delivery  
during the finals, they are paying close attention to Terri's 
health and travel abilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``My wife is just trying her best to figure out what games she's  
going to make,'' Jackson said. ``She's been going to her doctor's 
appointments and stuff like that. Plus, she's from New Jersey. So 
she's planning on being in New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *AND THEN THEY BECOME KIDS:* Sean Elliott, David Robinson and  
Avery Johnson say having children has helped them keep perspective 
during their journey to the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's anything that's happened in my life  
that's been better for me,'' said Elliott, whose daughter, Jordyn 
May Elliott, turned a year old last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``My little girl is just awesome,'' Elliott said. ``She runs up  
to me and she's smiling or laughing, you can forget about anything 
else that happened during the day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After advancing to the NBA Finals by sweeping Portland and  
getting several days off, Johnson kept himself occupied by watching 
his son and daughter play tennis. 
</P>
<P>
	``They keep my attention,'' he said. ``I was at tennis camp,  
watching them play like Venus Williams and Andre Agassi. So I had a 
good time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson may have been a Spurs' star for a decade, but two of  
three his sons are fans of other players. His oldest son likes 
Charles Barkley. His second-oldest son is a big fan of Tim Duncan. 
</P>
<P>
	``But my 2-year-old says, `Daddy, me love you. You're my boy.'  
So I got one of them. That's two out of three,'' Robinson said with 
a laugh. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
