<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors See More Diabetes in Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Type 2 diabetes, long thought to be a  
disease that only affected adults, is being diagnosed in 
startlingly high numbers of children, doctors say. 
</P>
<P>
	Diabetes is the leading cause of blindness, kidney failure and  
amputations in the United States and kills 180,000 a year. It also 
can lead to heart problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Tallahassee Memorial Hospital's Diabetes Center, which draws  
patients from Florida, Georgia and Alabama, has seen the number of 
type 2 cases among children triple in the last three years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It dawned on us this spring that ... four out of five new  
cases were type 2,'' said Larry Deeb, a pediatric endocrinologist 
at the center. ``And we said, `My Lord.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The University of Miami's Diabetes Research Institute is seeing  
the same thing and, along with medical schools at the University of 
Florida and the University of South Florida, is compiling data to 
determine the extent of the problem in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Type 2 diabetes can go undiagnosed for years -- sometimes until  
severe complications, like blindness, show up. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine out of 10 of the nation's 16 million diabetes cases are  
type 2. A much less common form of diabetes, type 1, generally 
strikes children. 
</P>
<P>
	But so ingrained is the perception that type 2 is primarily a  
disease for overweight, middle-aged people, it is frequently called 
adult-onset diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
	Type 1 diabetes is easier to diagnose, because children who get  
it usually get sick quickly. But with type 2, as many as a third of 
cases go undiagnosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Obesity is an indicator parents should watch for, doctors say.  
</P>
<P>
	``The rise in the incidence of obesity is making its ugly face  
known,'' said Ronald B. Goldberg, a diabetes specialist at the 
University of Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``Children are so much less active than they used to be,''  
Goldberg said, ``and exposed to our western type diets, they're 
putting on weight at alarming rates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to federal government statistics the percentage of  
children who are obese has increased from less than 8 percent in 
1976 to 14 percent in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Minority children are particularly at risk, experts say. Parents  
of black, Hispanic or American Indian children who are overweight 
should particularly be on the lookout for diabetes symptoms, such 
as excessive thirst, Deeb said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
