<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Klagenfurt Bids for 2006 Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KLAGENFURT, Austria (AP) -- First there was the mountain, then  
the national borders of three countries, and maybe, if Klagenfurt 
wins the bid for the 2006 Winter Olympics, there will be a very 
special ski race. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's alpine events would start in Italy, pass through  
Slovenia and finish in Austria. The mountain is located near 
Arnoldstein, a town near the Austrian-Italian border, which is at 
the heart of this Olympic bid ``without borders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the start near the mountain peak, where the borders of the  
three countries meet, the women's downhill event could become the 
symbolic core of the Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reality is that it (the Olympics) all takes place around  
one mountain,'' said Piergiorgio Baldassini, the general secretary 
of the Italian bid committee, pointing to the peak where the three 
countries meet. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohne Grenzen, Senza Confini, Brez Meja -- ``without borders'' in  
German, Italian and Slovenian. In this part of the world, where 
ripping borders apart has been tragically more common, it seems 
like a nice idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Klagenfurt's bid manager, Dieter Kalt, is good at bluffing, but  
he does get twitchy when he hears the names of the favorites -- 
Sion, Switzerland, and Turin, Italy. The Klagenfurt committee 
people know they are the outsiders in a six-way competition for the 
2006 Winter Olympics to be decided in Seoul on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure if the IOC members will go with the open-borders  
bid,'' Kalt admitted. ``But in reality, it's all the same whether 
we get the Olympics or not. When we can remind the world that we 
can sit at one table and discuss, we already have the moral 
victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This moral victory is important. As Kalt was quick to point out,  
the fathers of the bid organizers fought each other in World War 
II. 
</P>
<P>
	If successful, Klagenfurt may be a unique combination of  
altruism and unbridled luxury. More than 3,000 athletes and 
officials would be accommodated in existing 4-star hotels on the 
lakeside at Velden. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers say that 12 of 16 facilities already exist. From the  
transport center in Villach, the average distance to the six 
outdoor venues is 20 miles, while the average distance to the five 
indoor venues in Klagenfurt is 17 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Only two venues are located more than an hour from the Olympic  
Village -- the ice hockey arena in Ljubljana, Slovenia's capital, 
and the bobsled-luge run in Cortina d'Ampezzo, site of the 1956 
Winter Olympics in Italy. Modern highways and a rail network 
already link the sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Sports have been divided according to local traditions.  
</P>
<P>
	``Ski jumping is our national sport,'' said Vojteh Budinek, the  
general secretary of the Slovenian committee. ``We host the finals 
of the World Cup Ski Jumping here and it attracts between 50,000 
and 70,000 fans. We are even discussing making it an annual 
holiday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Alpine events would be held at four ski resorts taking in  
all three countries. Kranjska Gora, Slovenia, would play host to 
the men's giant slalom, slalom and combined slalom, while those 
events for women would be held in Tarvisio, Italy. The men' 
downhill, super-giant slalom and combined downhill would be at 
Hermagor-Nassfeld in Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	More than $1 million is being invested in the downhill course,  
due for completion in 2000. The women's speed events, including the 
downhill, the symbolic heart of the games, would pivot around the 
Arnoldstein Mountain. 
</P>
<P>
	Men's ice hockey would be held in Ljubljana. The women's  
competition and the curling events would be staged at the 
Klagenfurt Trade Fair. 
</P>
<P>
	A $79.6 million ice center is being built in Klagenfurt for  
figure skating, short track and speedskating. 
</P>
<P>
	Snowboarding would be held at the Austrian resort of Bad  
Kleinkirchheim and freestyle skiing at Tarvisio. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we are the best,'' Olympic downhill hero Franz Klammer  
said. ``Not just because of the sports facilities, but because we 
have a message about a United Europe. All this should be part of 
the Olympic ideal.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
