<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 05:30:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Silicon Valley Execs Getting Richer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Silicon Valley's top executives keep  
getting richer, widening the pay gap between corporate chiefs and 
the people who work for them. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest paid executive, Intel Corp. chief executive officer  
Craig Barrett, pulled down a staggering $116.8 million in 1998 -- 
the biggest one-year gain in wealth of any top Silicon Valley 
executive in the 14 years that the San Jose Mercury News has been 
tracking executive wealth. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper on Sunday described the fiscal dynamics of the  
Silicon Valley, where companies seeking a competitive edge offer 
huge enticements -- stock, relocation expenses, even home loans -- to 
lure executives. 
</P>
<P>
	The top 100 executives collected $1.4 billion in compensation.  
Only one woman made that list -- Carolyn Ticknor, the president of 
Hewlett-Packard's laserjet and imaging systems unit. She was 83rd 
with $3.17 million in pay and stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the ranks of highly paid executives, women take home  
far less than men: The most highly compensated woman received less 
than 3 percent of the sum taken home by the best-compensated man. 
</P>
<P>
	The corporate pay reflects direct salaries, but those often are  
dwarfed by the paper profits from parlaying stock options. Indeed, 
most of the $442 million in compensation collected by Silicon 
Valley's top 10 executives came from stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure is up a dramatic 65 percent from 1997, and up  
fourfold from the $108 million of 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The compensation information was based on 1998's proxy  
statements for 772 bosses at 147 of the largest public companies in 
Silicon Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Some familiar figures are not on the top list.  
</P>
<P>
	For example, many top executives of Hewlett-Packard aren't there  
because they forfeited millions of dollars in shares for failing to 
meet performance goals. Nor is Netscape Communications Corp. boss 
Jim Barksdale, who accepted only $1 in cash but owns almost 5 
percent of the company sold to America Online for $10 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	One columnist covering the executives' compensation was struck  
by the disparity of pay and the value placed on work. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took my daughter to her speech therapy class. We sat with a  
wonderful career teacher (about $61,000 a year), a woman who has my 
4-year-old daughter pronouncing 'K' sounds at the beginning and in 
the middle of words like 'cookie.' This teacher would need to put 
in 1,915 years to make what Barrett made last year,'' wrote 
columnist Mike Cassidy. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Barrett was worth $116.8 million last year, surely she was  
worth $232 million. Instead, we brought her roses from our yard,'' 
he wrote. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
