<DOCNO> APW19990614.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 14:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Hope To Find Scorers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres' scorers should be well  
rested for Game 4 of the Stanley Cup finals against the Dallas 
Stars on Tuesday night. After all, they've been on vacation for a 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Since they sneaked into Dallas and won 3-2 in Game 1, the Sabres  
have three goals in two games -- and, as a result, two losses. Their 
offense has been like Randy Johnson's fastball: It's there, but you 
can't see it. 
</P>
<P>
	Memo to Miroslav Satan, Curtis Brown, Michael Peca, Stu Barnes  
and crew: You might want to try scoring a goal or two on Tuesday. 
If not, that trip to Dallas on Thursday for Game 5 might be the 
last of a very, very long season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know what they're saying, that if we don't go out and win  
tomorrow, it's probably over,'' Brown said Monday as the Sabres 
plotted ways to combat a Stars defense as oppressive as Dallas' 
heat and just as stifling. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars allowed an NHL-low 168 goals during the season. But  
they've elevated the intensity and tenacity of their neutral-zone 
trap, backchecking and shot-blocking to a new level of distracting 
effectiveness in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy is simple. As Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said,  
``When there's a lot of pressure, your hands become like stone and 
it's hard to make plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres' frustration clearly grew as they got off only 12  
shots in their 2-1 loss in Game 3. So much so that coach Lindy Ruff 
is aware how the performance deflated a city still discouraged by 
the ego-deflating disappointment of four Super Bowl losses in four 
seasons by the Bills. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a big downer,'' Ruff said. ``The whole city was pumped  
up, and it was a bit of a letdown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Game 3, Dallas actually blocked more shots (19) than Buffalo  
put on Ed Belfour, who might have enjoyed the quietest night of any 
goaltender in recent Stanley Cup history despite facing eight 
Buffalo power plays. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to be more aggressive. We know that,'' said Sabres  
goaltender Dominik Hasek, who has yielded only five goals in 
Dallas' two victories. ``It is very difficult to win when you get 
only 12 shots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Juneau said of the Sabres' postgame feelings of frustration,  
``It's hard. You're mad. But it's still the first team to win four 
games, and we have to correct what has to be corrected. If we win 
Game 4, everybody will change their minds again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to rekindle his offense, Ruff gave extra shifts in  
Game 3 to Satan, his slumping 40-goal scorer. Satan managed his 
first two shots of the series but still didn't score, and Ruff 
admits to a growing impatience with his big gun. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Ruff probably will move Juneau onto the  
Satan-Curtis Brown line to add speed and a goal-scoring touch. He 
also plans to make faster line changes so the Stars' effective No. 
2 line, led by Joe Nieuwendyk, who had both Dallas goals in Game 3, 
faces different defenders on the same shift. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're stressing a lot shorter shifts, so maybe for 15 seconds  
they'll see Curtis Brown, maybe for 30 seconds they'll see Michael 
Peca,'' Ruff said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres probably won't see Dallas sharpshooter Brett Hull,  
who had two goals in the first two games before reinjuring his 
groin early in Game 3. Hull says there is a chance he can play, but 
Hitchcock lists him as doubtful. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's any doubt in anybody's mind that he's  
not a player for tomorrow night,'' Hitchcock said. ``I don't think 
there is enough soreness out of the area yet. You might do a lot 
more further damage if you do put him in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There also is no doubt in the Sabres' minds they must attack  
Game 4 with a much different approach than they did Game 4 of the 
Eastern Conference finals a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	They trailed Washington 2-1, yet responded with one of their  
poorest efforts of the season and lost 2-0, and went on to lose the 
series in six games. 
</P>
<P>
	``The group inside our room is still very confident,'' Ruff said  
``I don't see anything to resemble last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, the Stars also were up 2-1 to Colorado in the Western  
Conference finals several weeks ago, only to lose 3-2. Hitchcock 
hopes they have short memories. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we made enough physical and mental sacrifices to  
win that game,'' Hitchcock said. ``I think we know the sacrifices 
we have to make if we want to win Game 4.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
