<DOCNO> APW19990614.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Art Museum Agrees To Return Matisse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle Art Museum has agreed to return a  
Henri Matisse painting to the heirs of a French art dealer whose 
collection disappeared into Nazi vaults when he and his family fled 
to New York during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The heirs of Paul Rosenberg, a top Paris art dealer of 19th- and  
20th-century art between World War I and World War II, filed a 
lawsuit in U.S. District Court last year seeking the return of 
``Odalisque'' after learning it was part of the museum's 
collection. 
</P>
<P>
	Museum officials said an investigation confirmed the Rosenbergs'  
claims. 
</P>
<P>
	``By our action today, the Seattle Art Museum is drawing a clear  
ethical line. Since day one, SAM has been committed to doing the 
right thing,'' museum director Mimi Gardner Gates said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum received the painting in 1991 in a bequest from  
Seattle-area residents Prentice and Virginia Bloedel, who bought 
the painting in 1954 from the Knoedler &AMP; Co. gallery in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The gallery has said the Rosenbergs have no right to the  
painting, but failed to present evidence that the family claim was 
invalid, Gates said. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum has filed a lawsuit accusing Knoedler of fraud,  
breach of warranty of title and ``negligent misrepresentation'' 
when it sold the painting to Bloedel. The museum wants Knoedler to 
pay the market value of ``Odalisque.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No one will say what the 1928 oil painting is worth, though  
Matisses of similar size and quality have in recent years sold for 
around $2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The research was done by the Holocaust Art Restitution Project,  
a Washington, D.C.-based independent research organization that 
provides Holocaust victims with information on the origins and 
ownership of valuable artwork that disappeared or changed hands 
during the war. 
</P>
<P>
	It indicated that ``Odalisque'' was stolen in 1941 from the  
vault where Rosenberg had stored 162 paintings and then was stored 
at the Jeu de Paume Museum in Paris. The next year, a German art 
dealer based in Paris apparently acquired Odalisque in exchange for 
a French Renaissance painting. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no further proof of its whereabouts until July 1954  
when Knoedler &AMP; Co. acquired it from Paris' Galerie Drouant-David, 
the report said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Automakers, UAW Begin Contract Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. and the United Auto  
Workers kicked off the auto industry's triennial contract talks 
with a warning from the UAW's top leader that automakers are 
subjecting workers to too much overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	UAW President Stephen P. Yokich acknowledged that many UAW  
members have become used to working the kind of overtime that can 
boost their wages well above $70,000 a year. Working overtime 
traditionally was considered prudent in the industry's good times 
to sock away cash for the inevitable layoffs of lean years. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry likes overtime because it is cheaper than hiring  
additional workers and paying them the UAW's generous lifetime 
benefits. Last year the average Ford hourly worker put in 9.4 hours 
of overtime a week. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the industry in an unprecedented era of stability and  
expecting to post record domestic sales this year, Yokich said 
Monday that it's time to reconsider the cost of too much work. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's got to be a balance of some overtime and spending time  
with your families,'' Yokich said. ``There's other families that 
need good jobs as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His comments reflected the union's chosen theme for this year's  
talks: ``Bargaining for Families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford and union negotiators met to formally open the 1996 talks  
with handshake ceremonies at Ford headquarters. The ritual was to 
be repeated today at DaimlerChrysler AG's U.S. headquarters and at 
General Motors Corp. on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the key issues for the industry this year are changes in  
manufacturing that would allow lower-paid supplier workers to do 
more subassembly work. Health and safety, job security, wages and 
benefits remain perennial big issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford President Jac Nasser noted the significance of this year's  
talks, which will produce a new contract that will carry the 
industry into the 21st century. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not only is it a new contract for a new century, but it's a  
contract that a lot of people in the U.S. and in the world will be 
watching -- not only what we accomplish, but how we do it,'' Nasser 
told the bargaining teams. ``The how is almost as important as 
where we come out in the end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike strike-prone rival GM, Ford has enjoyed peaceful labor  
relations with the UAW for two decades. Ford has not endured a 
nationwide UAW strike in 23 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Come Labor Day, the UAW will choose the lead company with which  
it will work out an economic package that the other automakers will 
be expected to adopt. Ford set the pace for the contracts as lead 
company in 1993 and 1996 and is hoping to do so again. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford chief negotiator Robert H. Marcin said the reason was  
simple: It allows the company to negotiate what's best for Ford 
rather than being stuck with what may be best for its domestic 
competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasser told negotiators that changes in ``manufacturing  
processes'' were key to Ford's growth plans. All three companies 
have long sought and in some cases gained more flexibility in the 
way they can use UAW workers on the assembly lines. 
</P>
<P>
	But GM executives' public talk of drastically changing the way  
the No. 1 automaker manufactures small cars by adopting ``modular'' 
assembly techniques has angered the UAW. Modular assembly would 
rely more on suppliers to build a car's major parts assemblies, or 
``modules,'' and less on higher-cost UAW workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford executives have been careful in recent weeks to avoid the  
``M word,'' and Nasser was no exception. But he said the issue of 
manufacturing processes ``really drives how good we are and what 
our customers think about us and our products and the value that we 
can put into the market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The remarks by Nasser and Chairman William C. Ford Jr. were made  
behind closed doors, but they were inadvertently broadcast into the 
Ford pressroom where reporters were awaiting the handshake 
ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	At a later news conference, Yokich maintained his stance against  
modular assembly. ``If it's not good for GM, why would I say it's 
good for Ford?'' he asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Health and safety issues will be one of the first issues tackled  
at Ford in the wake of the February explosion at its Rouge plant 
near Detroit, which killed six workers. An executive who spoke on 
condition of anonymity said the company was eager to negotiate any 
contract provisions that could prevent another such disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	Yokich said he discussed the Rouge explosion with negotiators  
Monday and that it would be an issue throughout the talks. He said 
there have been 42 work-related deaths in the domestic auto 
industry during the current three-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's 42 too many as far as we're concerned,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ford negotiators also will be tackling the future of the 23,500  
UAW workers at the company's Visteon parts unit. Ford is expected 
to spin off Visteon in the next year or two, though it says no 
final decision has been made. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiations cover between 101,000 and 110,000 Ford workers,  
depending on who's counting. The company issued the smaller number 
Monday; the union used the larger one. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 08:52:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mbeki Chosen As S.African President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- South Africa's parliament  
selected Thabo Mbeki as the country's second freely elected 
president today in a ceremony that marked the nation's farewell to 
the era of Nelson Mandela. 
</P>
<P>
	With Mandela looking on, Mbeki was nominated without opposition  
and then proclaimed president by Constitutional Court chief Arthur 
Chaskalson. Mandela and the legislators broke into thunderous 
applause and chanted ``Mbeki, Mbeki!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Chaskalson swore in the 400 legislators. Dressed in  
saris, colorful headwraps, embroidered tunics, blankets, beadwork 
and business suits, they took the oath in groups of 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Mbeki and Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, Mandela's former wife, were  
in the first group. 
</P>
<P>
	The ANC won 266 seats in the June 2 election, only the second  
national vote in which all races were allowed to cast ballots since 
the fall of apartheid in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The ANC's margin in the assembly is so great that many members  
laughed when Chaskalson asked if there were any other nominations 
for the presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	In an emotional moment, President Mandela walked into the  
chamber at the opening of the afternoon session. The legislators 
stood, clapped rhythmically and broke into a song of praise. 
</P>
<P>
	Mbeki will be inaugurated in Pretoria on Wednesday, and name his  
Cabinet on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech, Mbeki paid tribute to the masses who propelled  
the ANC to a second overwhelming mandate. The 1994 election ended 
white minority rule. 
</P>
<P>
	``If all of us stand tall today, as all of us surely do, it is  
only because we are borne aloft by the firm hands of the ordinary 
people of our country,'' he said, his voice hoarse from the flu. 
</P>
<P>
	He referred to the deep poverty and a racial divide that  
continues to plague South Africa even after apartheid's fall five 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Mbeki, who turns 57 on Friday, has been effectively running the  
country for the past several years as deputy president after a long 
career in the ANC as an organizer, administrator and negotiator 
with the white government. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 08:52:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
