<DOCNO> APW19990614.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 21:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Slams NRA, House on Guns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Pressing for help in a fight for stricter gun  
laws, Vice President Al Gore told the nation's mayors on Monday 
that he had underestimated the ability of the National Rifle 
Association to ``call the shots in Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Will we let the NRA call the shots in Washington or will we  
cross party lines to make our children safer?'' Gore said to more 
than 300 city leaders at the annual meeting of the U.S. Conference 
of Mayors. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore cast the deciding vote three weeks ago when the Senate  
passed a proposal to require background checks for gun buyers at 
gun shows. He said he thought the measure and others in the Senate 
bill ``would just pick up momentum'' and move toward House passage. 
</P>
<P>
	However, an intense lobbying effort by the NRA has helped to  
derail any easy passage of gun safety legislation in the House, for 
now. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some in the House are pushing a bill that gives the NRA the  
loopholes it wants instead of giving the country the protection it 
needs,'' Gore said to cheers from the mayors. ``It's time to side 
with our children instead of the gun lobby.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican-controlled House is expected to debate gun  
control proposals this week, with Democrats generally pressing for 
adoption of provisions the Senate approved last month, and the NRA 
fighting to water them down or eliminate them. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the background checks for all purchases at gun  
shows, the Senate-passed provisions include a requirement that 
safety devices be sold with guns and a ban on importing 
high-capacity ammunition clips. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush, campaigning in New Hampshire for the  
Republican presidential nomination, said he favored the Senate 
legislation, but with a GOP-backed amendment on gun-show background 
checks that failed. Asked about Gore's push for new controls, he 
replied, ``We need to enforce the laws already on the books.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's only Democratic opponent, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New  
Jersey, has called for an aggressive gun control campaign, 
including ``handgun cards'' -- photo identity cards required of 
anybody carrying a handgun. He also has been considering whether to 
propose a ban on handgun sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore released a report by the Justice and Treasury departments  
that found 24 percent of all gun homicides are committed by 18- to 
20-year-olds, a group that is just 4 percent of the population. The 
same age group also led all other age categories in using guns in 
murders and other crimes, including rape, assault and robberies, 
according to the report. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also said 18-year-olds commit 35 percent more gun  
murders than 21-year-olds, double the gun murders by 24-year olds 
and four times the number of gun murders committed by 30-year-olds. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore laid out a broad outline for job creation, an increase in  
educational standards and urban development. His pledge to improve 
schools by providing ``high-quality preschool education'' for all 
American children drew a standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	``A strong economy, safer communities and better schools are  
just some of the challenges we need to tackle as we move to the 
21st century,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, Gore was host at a $1,000 per-person  
fund-raiser in a Bourbon Street jazz bar. Gore staffers said the 
event raised more than $250,000, more than twice the amount tallied 
at a similar event for President Clinton four years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he's often painted as a robotic speaker, Gore broke with  
tradition by strutting into the Storyville Jazz Bar in the city's 
French Quarter district with a musical procession known as a Second 
Line and took a few dance steps to the music. 
</P>
<P>
	The speeches were Gore's last major addresses before he  
officially announces his presidential candidacy Wednesday in his 
hometown of Carthage, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheering their man as a strong advocate for urban America, more  
than 100 mayors announced their support of Gore at the convention 
Sunday. So far, a total of 167 mayors have pledged him their 
support for the 2000 presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton-Gore team has enjoyed great popularity with the  
mayors' group for giving more attention to the nation's urban 
policy agenda than its Republican predecessors did in the 1980s. 
That support was in evidence after the speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see him as a champion for the cities,'' said Larry Delgado,  
mayor of Santa Fe, N.M. ``He's been fighting for the funding we 
need.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
