<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 20:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rice Hopes To Continue Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- It's elimination time in Omaha, and Rice is  
hoping its season doesn't come to an end just days after its first 
College World Series victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The eighth-seeded Owls (59-14) meet second-seeded Alabama  
(52-15) in Tuesday's early game. In the nightcap, second-seeded 
Florida State (54-13) will meet third-seeded Cal State-Fullerton, 
which eliminated Texas A&AMP;M on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite being ranked No. 1 nationally in some polls this season,  
the Owls said their lack of high draft picks and recognizable 
standouts in 1999 made them a team that gets no respect. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we hadn't won last night, people would have limited their  
perception of our program,'' coach Wayne Graham said Monday. ``We 
don't have a lot of high draft picks, but we've got an awful lot of 
good players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graham said he will start either Marc Gwyn (7-1, 2.99 ERA) or  
Jeff Nichols (15-3, 4.95) against Alabama's potent offense. Graham 
won't decide until Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Crimson Tide also face elimination after failing to find  
their offense in an 8-1 loss to Miami on Sunday. The defeat ended 
Alabama's 16-game winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was surprised when we weren't hitting the ball,'' said  
Alabama freshman pitcher Scott Murphy (7-0, 5.61), who gets the 
call against Rice. ``But when you win 16 or 17 games in a row, 
you're probably going to have a flat day eventually.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graham said Alabama wins with effective hitting.  
</P>
<P>
	``I love their hitting concept,'' he said. ``They use the whole  
field. They take good swings. They can foul off pitches with two 
strikes. They don't just pay lip service to the proper way to 
hit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Murphy said he knows almost nothing about the Owls, who went 0-2  
in their only previous CWS appearance in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our coaches are still working on getting a scouting report,''  
he said. ``But you just have to go out there with the mindset that 
they're all superstars and try to get them out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rice catcher Zane Curry, 0-for-15 in the postseason before  
hitting a double Sunday night, said his performance typifies his 
team. He said any player can step up with big hits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's a guy they (opponents) can get a fix  
on,'' Curry said. ``We're just a team of working-class guys that 
have worked really hard to get here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
