<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 15:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Murray Hired as L.A. Kings Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Andy Murray, a success at the high school and  
international levels of hockey, added the NHL to his head coaching 
resume Monday when he was hired by the Los Angeles Kings. 
</P>
<P>
	Murray, 48, replaces Larry Robinson, whose contract wasn't  
renewed in April after the team finished 32-45-5 and failed to 
reach the playoffs for the third time in four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that the team underachieved last season, this is a  
great time to come to Los Angeles,'' Murray said at a news 
conference near the downtown Staples Center, the new arena where 
the Kings will play next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Murray agreed to a three-year contract. Financial terms weren't  
disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Andy Murray has a wealth of hockey knowledge. He's coached at  
just about every level you can imagine. He's a very bright 
individual, very intense,'' Kings general manager Dave Taylor said. 
``He'll demand the utmost of our players, certainly earn their 
respect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Murray won the job over the other finalist, John Van Boxmeer,  
coach and general manager of the IHL's Long Beach Ice Dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	Murray's only other stints in the NHL were as an assistant with  
the Philadelphia Flyers from 1988-90; the Minnesota North Stars in 
1990-91, when they reached the Stanley Cup final; and the Winnipeg 
Jets from 1992-94. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that I have worked with players as a head coach at  
the international level will help me in this situation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He coached Canada's national team to a 77-29-14 record and the  
gold medal in the 1997 world championships. Among his players was 
defenseman Rob Blake, the Kings' captain. 
</P>
<P>
	Blake cited Murray's intensity, discipline and work ethic as  
reasons the coach could succeed without any prior NHL head coaching 
experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``He understands the players,'' Blake said. ``He touched on a  
big thing about respect, demanding a lot out of each player -- as 
much as they can give -- but also having that respect for them. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll get the most out of this team.''  
</P>
<P>
	Murray's most recent job was coaching at Shattuck-St. Mary's in  
Faribault, Minn., a prep school south of Minneapolis. The team went 
70-9-2 and won the Midget Triple A USA Hockey national title. 
</P>
<P>
	He also served as an assistant for Canada at the 1996 World Cup  
of Hockey and the world championships, where the team won silver 
medals. He was an assistant for Canada at the 1998 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Left wing Luc Robitaille wasn't concerned the Kings didn't hire  
a high-profile coach. Taylor also interviewed former Buffalo Sabres 
coach Ted Nolan, Montreal assistant Dave King and Detroit assistant 
Dave Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	``This guy deserves a chance,'' Robitaille said. ``Everywhere  
he's been going, he's won.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings made the playoffs just once in four years under  
Robinson, who had a 122-161-45 record. Last season, the Kings lost 
25 games by one goal, had one of the league's worst power plays and 
lost 335 man-games to injuries or illness. 
</P>
<P>
	``We lacked intensity and the will to pay the price to win any  
game, especially down the stretch,'' Robitaille said. ``That's what 
a guy like that with his intensity will bring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Murray said he plans to emphasize improved defense, with clearly  
defined roles for each player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want our players when they don't have the puck to know  
exactly what their responsibilities are. There won't be leeway. 
Everybody will have to follow the same guidelines,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When they have the puck, I want players to bring their  
individual creativity on the ice because that's what the fans come 
to see.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 18:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
