<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 08:10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Won't Halt Md. College Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling  
that lawyers for a Maryland college say will result in ``an 
intrusive investigation of religious speech and practice on its 
campus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The justices, over one dissenting vote, refused to scuttle an  
investigation aimed at determining whether Columbia Union College, 
a Takoma Park, Md., school affiliated with the Seventh-day 
Adventist Church, is ``pervasively sectarian'' and therefore 
ineligible for any direct monetary aid from the state. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court ordered such fact-finding last October,  
and today's Supreme Court order rejected the college's ensuing 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1971, Maryland has provided financial aid to private  
colleges in the state, based on the number of each school's 
full-time students. The fund, called the Sellinger Program, 
distributed money to 15 colleges in 1997 -- 12 with no religious 
affiliation and three linked to the Roman Catholic Church. 
</P>
<P>
	The religiously affiliated schools are not allowed to use the  
money they receive for any religious purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1976 Supreme Court decision upheld the Catholic colleges'  
participation in the program, ruling that the schools were not 
``pervasively sectarian'' and could use money provided by the state 
for purposes having nothing to do with religion. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Union, a school of about 1,200 students, sought  
Sellinger Program funding in 1990 but the Maryland Commission of 
Higher Education denied the application. The commission concluded 
that the school was pervasively religious and that any grant would 
be used for religious purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission noted that Catholic schools received money but  
said Columbia Union was ``more religious'' -- and that giving it 
public money would be unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	After unsuccessfully seeking reconsideration of its application,  
Columbia Union sued the commission's members in 1996, and at the 
same time submitted a new application seeking $806,000 in state 
money for use in various academic programs. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal trial judge threw out the lawsuit, ruling that the  
college is too pervasively religious to receive any state money -- 
even funds earmarked for specific academic programs such as 
mathematics and computer science. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals set aside the trial  
judge's ruling, reinstated the school's lawsuit and ordered further 
study. 
</P>
<P>
	``No court could or should decide whether Columbia Union is  
pervasively sectarian based solely on the evidence in this record, 
which is comprised almost exclusively on the college's written 
literature and policies,'' the appeals court said. 
</P>
<P>
	It ordered the judge to take into account the school's practices  
``to determine whether religious indoctrination pervades the 
institution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the college urged the  
justices to call of any such inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where a funding program is neutral toward religion ... (and)  
contains safeguards to ensure that program funds are used for 
secular program purposes, the 'pervasively sectarian' inquiry 
pursued below is simply unnecessary,'' the appeal said. 
</P>
<P>
	It suggested that the 1976 Supreme Court decision relied on by  
the appeals court has been overtaken by more recent church-state 
rulings by the justices. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland Attorney General Joseph Curran urged the court to  
reject the school's appeal, calling it premature. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Clarence Thomas dissented from today's denial of review.  
``Although the court declines ... (review) today -- perhaps because 
this case comes to us in an interlocutory posture -- the growing 
confusion among the lower courts illustrates that we cannot long 
avoid addressing the important issue that it presents,'' he said in 
a dissenting opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Columbia Union College vs. Clark, 98-1509.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 16:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charges Vs. Cycling Chiefs Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LILLE, France (AP) -- A judge on Monday threw out charges against  
the presidents of the French Cycling Federation and the 
Professional Cycling League, who had been among more than a dozen 
people suspected of a role in the Festina cycling scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Baal, who heads the French Cycling Federation, later said  
that the problem of drug use in the sport was the fault of everyone 
-- even the state. 
</P>
<P>
	The failure ``is that of the entire sporting world,'' he told a  
news conference, ``of national and international federations ... It 
is the failure of all states, including the French state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baal and Roger Legeay, suspected of not taking sufficient  
preventive measures against doping by cyclists, had been placed 
under investigation for ``complicity in facilitating, inciting the 
use and administration of illegal substances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Investigating Magistrate Patrick Keil threw out the  
charges for both men. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven other people, including Italian cyclist Rodolfo Massi of  
the Casino team and French cyclist Richard Virenque, formerly with 
Festina, remain under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Disclosures that Festina riders had used banned substances  
surfaced three days before last year's Tour de France, and news of 
drug use followed the entire race. Festina was forced to pull out. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 03:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Is Jackson Ready To Be Reeled In? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Phil Jackson spent the weekend fishing in a remote corner of  
Alaska. In a nice twist of fate, he was the one who returned to 
civilization still wearing the hook. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other end of the line is Lakers owner Jerry Buss. The  
bait, according to published reports, was a contract for four or 
five years at close to $6 million per year. And if the deal is as 
good as agent Todd Musburger and Los Angeles general manager Jerry 
West swear it is, all that's left for Jackson to decide is whether 
he's ready to be reeled in. 
</P>
<P>
	Whichever it is, Jackson owes it to some people to answer soon.  
</P>
<P>
	That way, incumbent LA coach Kurt Rambis would know whether he's  
still in line for a prime parking space when the team moves into 
the new Staples Center. 
</P>
<P>
	That way, incumbent Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy could lose the  
nervous tic that makes him look over his shoulder every few 
minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	And that way, the Nets can decide whether Don Casey, a good and  
decent career NBA assistant, gets the shot at a head coaching job 
he deserves. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides, Jackson's options are narrowing all the time. By the  
time he left the Lower 48 to go fishing, his name had been 
mentioned for every job opening except the White House (and a 
friend of his is up for that). It won't continue forever. 
</P>
<P>
	New York may already be moot, since the Knicks' win over the  
Pacers triggered a clause in Van Gundy's contract guaranteeing him 
a one-year extension at $3.5 million. And while the Nets job is 
still Jackson's for the asking, the owners never put a firm offer 
on the table and are already preparing to move on without him. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, as befits a man associated so closely with the triangle  
offense, Jackson has a third option -- campaigning for former Knick 
teammate and current Democratic presidential contender Bill 
Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	Long blessed with touch, Bradley has added tact to his  
repertoire. Asked last Friday at the Knicks game where he'd like to 
see Jackson wind up, he replied, ``Wherever is best for Phil.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But right now, even Phil is not sure where that is.  
</P>
<P>
	By sitting out last season, Jackson benefitted from the sporting  
world equivalent of the ``dead-artist syndrome''; that is, his work 
rose in value because there might not be any more to go around. 
</P>
<P>
	Like so many other tricks of the trade, the sabbatical was a  
move perfected by Pat Riley. He went from the bench to the 
broadcast booth -- where every dig at a former colleague drove up 
his own asking price -- and once the right situation materialized, 
back to the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Say this much for Jackson: He did not take time off to advance  
his career. He turned up in Chicago to collect his sixth 
championship ring during a ceremony clumsily shoehorned between 
halves of a regular-season game. But that was pretty much it. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of Jackson's sabbatical has been spent in less public  
pursuits -- enjoying family, reading and traveling. Outside of 
speaking engagements, the only time he turns up on the news is 
standing next to Bradley. But that's where the timing gets sticky. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bradley campaign is scheduled to arrive midweek in LA and  
Jackson is supposed to speak at a fund-raising dinner Thursday in 
Beverly Hills. ``I'm sure he'll be doing that as the Laker coach,'' 
a source told the Los Angeles Times. 
</P>
<P>
	It's easy to see the lure of LA. Jackson inherits Shaquille  
O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, with a chance to add Scottie Pippen (for 
Glen Rice) and resurrect Dennis Rodman's career again. It's the 
perfect place to prove he contributed more to the Bulls 
championships than the command: ``Get the ball to Michael.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the Lakers can only get better. They haven't won a  
championship since 1988, haven't reached the finals since 1991, and 
they've been swept out of the playoffs the last two years. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, it's hard to see Buss and Jackson connecting.  
The Lakers owner thinks culture is checking out the art at the 
Bellagio in Las Vegas. And he won't be patient for long; Buss 
balked at paying $6 million a year for Jackson until someone 
explained that credibility might mean fewer empty seats in a new 
arena. And remember: the last time Jackson worked for two guys 
named Jerry (Krause and Reinsdorf), things ended badly. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nets, meanwhile, offer greater stability, just as much money  
and only a little less talent. And the owners, longtime supporters 
of former Sen. Bradley, are more in line with Jackson 
philosophically. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, if that's really important to Jackson, he might just  
as well stick to politics, which another former Democratic 
presidential hopeful once likened to coaching. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to be smart enough to know the game,'' former Sen.  
Eugene McCarthy said, ``and stupid enough to think it's 
important.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 03:10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hull's Out for Dallas Stars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- It's taken 10 years for Ken Hitchcock to  
finally square things with Darryl Sydor. And what a time to do it -- 
in the Stanley Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	When Hitchcock was coaching Sydor in Kamloops in the Canadian  
juniors, he turned him from a forward into a defenseman. It looks 
like he will be reversing that now as the Dallas Stars prepare for 
Game 4 of the finals against the Buffalo Sabres on Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that Darryl gives us so much energy that we can play  
him in the middle 20s (in minutes) up and back and he doesn't miss 
a beat,'' Hitchcock said. 
</P>
<P>
	The position switch was made possible by the loss of Brett Hull,  
who suffered a groin injury in Dallas' 2-1 victory in Game 3 
Saturday night that gave the Stars a two games to one lead in the 
best-of-7 series. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock on Sunday said Hull ``is probably doubtful for Game 4.  
He was pretty sore last night. ... I don't think he will be ready. 
I think he is looking at probably Game 5 or Game 6 right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Sydor will be looking at a possible opportunity to  
play on the Stars' top line with Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it will change my game that much,'' said Sydor,  
an offensive-minded defenseman who is sixth on the Dallas scoring 
charts with 11 points. Modano and Lehtinen are the offensive 
players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock and Sydor go way back. While coaching at Kamloops in  
the Western Hockey League, Hitchcock had been scouting Sydor when 
the player was 13 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came to us as a forward, and he played his first game as a  
16-year-old as a forward,'' Hitchcock recalled. ``I put him on 
defense as a junior player because I felt that he wasn't going to 
be the impact player that some people thought he was as a junior.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sydor has already been used as a forward sparingly in the  
finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``You saw the two shifts he took out there, he was trying to  
kill everybody,'' Hitchcock said. ``He likes playing (forward) now 
because he feels he can get even with everybody that has taken runs 
at him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another possibility to replace Hull is Tony Hrkac, who has been  
thrown into action of late after being used sparingly in the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were really impressed with the way Tony played,'' Hitchcock  
said. ``So we have got some good options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hull is the second big-name player for Dallas who has suffered  
an injury in the playoffs. Modano had his left wrist injured in 
Game 2 in Dallas, but felt good enough to play Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock said his top all-around player was feeling even better  
on Sunday, particularly with the addition of Sydor on his line. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think if we put a defensive player there, then we are aiming  
to turn (Modano) and Lehtinen loose, and (Modano) is pretty excited 
about that,'' Hitchcock said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Modano has been enjoying himself in the playoffs this year  
with five goals and 13 assists in 20 games, the same can't be said 
of the Sabres' Miroslav Satan. 
</P>
<P>
	A 40-goal scorer during the season, Satan has only managed three  
goals in nine postseason games -- none in the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I do feel the pressure,'' Satan said in response to a  
reporter's question. ``I tried to respond the best way I can, but 
right now they are backchecking hard. There is not too much room; 
not only me, but the whole team has problems to create anything in 
their zone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that is the key why we had only 12 shots last night  
and why we are not creating a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sabres coach Lindy Ruff has no answer for Satan's slump.  
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, we need him. We tried to get him away from a couple  
of matchups; tried to get him away from a couple of their defensive 
pairs. We tried everything, but didn't get a lot out of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Satan isn't the only one having problems scoring for the Sabres.  
The defense-first Stars have restricted Buffalo to just six goals 
in the first three games while scoring only eight themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team is still very positive,'' Sabres captain Mike Peca  
said. ``It is a race to four games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was disappointing to lose (Saturday) night. We could have  
put ourselves in a good spot. We didn't have our greatest game. 
Obviously at this point of the season this is the greatest 
adversity we have faced, but this team seems to thrive on that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
