<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Awards $76M for Birth Injuries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A jury ordered the city's hospital agency to pay  
$76 million to a child who allegedly was choked by her umbilical 
cord during birth and suffered severe brain injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The verdict came Friday in a case brought on behalf of  
12-year-old Gaelle Prindilus, who has cerebral palsy. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl requires 24-hour care, needs a wheelchair and is unable  
to read or write because of her botched delivery by unsupervised, 
overworked and inexperienced residents at Harlem Hospital, said her 
lawyer, Thomas Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	Her father works two jobs to pay for her care -- as a kitchen  
worker and a janitor. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaelle was born in 1987. During delivery, Moore said, the  
umbilical cord was wrapped tightly around her neck, decreasing her 
oxygen intake. 
</P>
<P>
	When the girl's mother, a Haitian immigrant with limited  
English, arrived at the hospital, a resident failed to do a 
sonogram that would have shown the cord around the baby's neck, 
Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman delivered the baby alone in her room, ``no doctor, no  
nurse, no one,'' Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Luke Pittoni, a lawyer for the agency that oversees the city's  
hospitals, said it will appeal. Gaelle's condition existed in the 
womb and showed up in a CAT scan before delivery, Pittoni said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
