<HEADLINE> Angels Rookie Tears Thumb Ligament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Anaheim Angels outfielder Mike Colangelo  
will be sidelined at least three weeks after tearing a ligament in 
his left thumb during a collision in his major league debut. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo's hand was placed in a cast Monday, a day after the  
left fielder ran into center fielder Reggie Williams in a game 
against Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo was examined by team physician Lewis Yocum and hand  
specialist Norman Zemel. The rookie's injury will be evaluated 
again in three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels will make a move to replace Colangelo on the roster  
prior to Tuesday night's game at Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo was running full speed in the seventh inning when when  
Williams, who made the catch, barreled over him in a violent 
collision. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo was down for about 15 minutes before being placed on a  
immobilizing board and taken off the field on a medical cart. He 
was taken to UC Irvine for a series of tests because he had pain in 
his upper back, but the tests showed that his spine was undamaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams was unhurt and remained in the game, a 3-1, 13-inning  
loss to the Diamondbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The 22-year-old Colangelo had just been called up from Anaheim's  
Triple-A Edmonton farm team and singled in his first big league 
at-bat. 
</P>
<P>
	He was hitting .362, with 13 runs scored and nine RBIs in 26  
games at Edmonton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
