<DOCNO> APW19990614.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 18:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- The Venezuelan economy declined nearly  
10 percent during the first quarter of 1999, according to news 
reports Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	A Central Bank official, who was not identified in the reports,  
said the institution would not deny the report. Official 
confirmation of the 9.8 percent figure was expected on Tuesday, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The contraction was due mostly to a precipitous drop in the  
price of oil, Venezuela's main export product. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of a barrel of Venezuelan oil has recovered in the  
past two months -- from a low of $7 last year to about $14 now -- 
improving economic prospects for the rest of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the current recession is considered the worst in a  
decade, with hundreds of companies declaring bankruptcy. 
Unemployment is estimated at between 15 percent and 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	According to respected economist Pedro Palma, the chances of a  
recovery this year are small because of an overvalued currency that 
makes it difficult for exporters to compete and the drafting of a 
new constitution that could contribute to investor uncertainty. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazilian airplane manufacturer Embraer  
saw its shares skyrocket Monday after it announced several billion 
dollars worth of new contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Embraer's stock jumped as high as 55 percent to $1.67 before  
closing at $1.35 on news that the company had secured some $4.9 
billion in contacts to sell 200 airplanes to Switzerland's 
Crossair. 
</P>
<P>
	Formerly owned by the government, Embraer was sold in 1994 and  
earned $102 million in 1998, the first profit in its 30-year 
history. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
