<DOCNO> APW19990614.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 12:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Candidates' Stances on Justices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Positions of George W. Bush's Republican rivals on requiring  
anti-abortion stances from potential Supreme Court nominees: 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Smith:  
</P>
<P>
	Smith has pledged ``only to nominate pro-life justices for the  
Supreme Court,'' said spokeswoman Karen Hickey. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes:  
</P>
<P>
	``I believe you should appoint justices on matter of principle.  
One of those principles is belief in the sanctity of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan:  
</P>
<P>
	``He's a 'yes' on an anti-abortion litmus test,'' said spokesman  
Bob Adams. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Quayle:  
</P>
<P>
	In February: ``I continue to support an amendment to overturn  
Roe vs. Wade today. ... Those I select for the most critical 
positions in government, including my running mate or nominees to 
the Supreme Court, will share it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John McCain:  
</P>
<P>
	``McCain has said that he will nominate justices based on their  
experience, and those who share his values,'' said spokesman Howard 
Opinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole:  
</P>
<P>
	``Mrs. Dole appoints people who think like she does, who she  
likes and who will not legislate from the bench,'' said spokesman 
Ari Fleischer. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamar Alexander:  
</P>
<P>
	``He would appoint judges who share his philosophy'' and would  
``interpret the constitution the way it was written,'' said 
political director Brian Kennedy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
