<DOCNO> APW19990614.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 15:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Don King Wants Holyfield-Lewis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Don King says if the Evander Holyfield-Lennox  
Lewis rematch happens, he will be the promoter. 
</P>
<P>
	Seth Abraham, head of Time Warner Sports, has said the  
pay-per-view fight, which is set for Nov. 13, is in jeopardy if 
King does not give Time Warner the right to order the promoter to 
step aside if he is indicted in connection with the first 
Holyfield-Lewis fight. That bout ended in a controversial draw. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not giving up my rights, I'm not giving up the presumption  
of innocence,'' King said Monday at a news conference for the Oscar 
De La Hoya-Felix Trinidad welterweight tile bout Sept. 18 at Las 
Vegas. That fight will be co-promoted by King and Bob Arum and 
carried on pay-per-view by TVKO. 
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner Sports operates HBO and its pay-per-view arm, TVKO.  
</P>
<P>
	``An indictment is only an allegation,'' King said. ``If they  
have trouble being associated with me, then they can buy me out or 
I will buy them out,'' King said. 
</P>
<P>
	A buyout, either way, won't happen.  
</P>
<P>
	Abraham said that if King should grant Time Warner the right it  
seeks, it does not necessarily mean it would be exercised. 
</P>
<P>
	Most observers thought Lewis clearly won the March 13 fight in  
Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	``When an unpopular decision came, not a corrupt decision but an  
unpopular decision, I was abandoned like the bubonic plague,'' King 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	There is a chance that King could be indicted in connection with  
an investigation that the IBF fixed rankings for a payoff. Abraham 
said Time Warner would not be concerned about such an indictment in 
connection with an Holyfield-Lewis rematch. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, FBI agents raided King's offices at Deerfield Beach,  
Fla., reportedly seeking records involving the IBF. The FBI would 
not confirm that was the reason. 
</P>
<P>
	King was not present.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was in Seth Abraham's office (in New York),'' King said,  
laughing. ``My office was under siege. No woman could go to the 
bathroom without an agent. No man could go to the bathroom without 
an agent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Abraham said that should the Holyfield-Lewis rematch not take  
place, Lewis, promoted by Panos Eliades of Britain and Main Events, 
could fight the winner of the Michael Grant-Lou Savarese fight, 
possible in Madison Square Garden on Nov. 13. Lewis is scheduled to 
fly to New York Thursday and attend a match Saturday night in The 
Theater at the Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fight is made,'' King, Holyfield's promoter, said of the  
rematch. ``I got a $10 million site fee (for the match at Mandalay 
Bay in Las Vegas). Both fighters have signed. Holyfield wants the 
fight. I want the fight. The only one holding it up is HBO. If it 
falls through, we'll go on about our business.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 22:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smaller Crop May Mean Bigger Fruit / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENNEWICK, Wash. (AP) -- The unseasonably cool spring means fewer  
cherries and a later season, but growers say that might not be such 
a bad thing. It may mean a bigger, firmer fruit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most cherry growers are pretty optimistic at this point that  
we have a winning season ahead of us,'' said Jim Kelley, a 
Kennewick orchardist and horticulturist for 34 Chief Wenatchee 
growers from Prosser to Basin City. 
</P>
<P>
	The delayed crop means losing part of big Independence Day  
sales, but it also means growers don't have to compete with 
California's own later-than-usual crop for workers and market 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvest projections for Washington and Oregon are for about  
70,000 tons of fresh-market cherries, down more than 15,000 tons 
from the earliest estimates because of a cool spring and 
pollination problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of this year's crop was damaged by wind or last summer's  
heat, which can cause growing abnormalities in the subsequent 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a big hit, but we still have plenty of cherries to  
sell,'' said B.J. Thurlby, promotion director for Northwest Cherry 
Growers. 
</P>
<P>
	Pasco grower Denny Hayden said less fruit means bigger, firmer  
cherries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going have quite a bit better size,'' said Hayden, who  
just returned from California where he checked on harvest that was 
just starting to peak. 
</P>
<P>
	He saw plenty of good fruit, and he likes the timing of the two  
harvests this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just adds to smooth marketing to allow (Californians) to  
move their crop prior to us really getting rolling,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It also gives growers a chance to find workers, many of whom  
travel to Washington as the California season wanes. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Washington and Oregon cherry growers picked more than  
85,000 tons -- a record crop and well above the eight-year average 
of 58,000 tons. 
</P>
<P>
	Bigger harvests are the product of more land in cherries,  
surpassing 20,000 acres in Washington. Cherries were Washington's 
ninth-most valuable crop in 1997, bringing in more than $128 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	They also are one of the few reliable money makers in a  
generally poor farm economy and are worth more per acre than any 
other state crop, according to the most recent reports from the 
Washington Agricultural Statistics Service. 
</P>
<P>
	But the late harvest -- probably starting in the third week of  
June -- isn't all good news. It might not allow shipment of 
Northwest cherries across the nation by July 4, the biggest buying 
time for cherries, Thurlby said. About 60 percent of the crop is 
typically sold in the two weeks leading up to the holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	But local cherry lovers won't have to skimp. ``West Coast  
consumers will see plenty of fruit,'' Thurlby said, noting the 
marketing commission has shifted toward late July promotions to 
make sure consumers are looking for cherries later than usual. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, the whole intricate picking and marketing machine  
depends on the weather. A week of temperatures in the low 80s is 
what growers want to ripen the hard balls of yellow fruit. And 
orchardists won't even talk about rain, which splits cherries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 18:17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Off DL, Ripken Ripping the Ball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cal Ripken woke up Monday morning wondering  
whether the finest performance of his outstanding baseball career 
was merely a figment of his imagination. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken set a Baltimore Orioles record by getting six hits in a  
game Sunday night, hitting two homers and a double in a 6-for-6 
effort against the Atlanta Braves. He then boarded a chartered 
flight and arrived home around 3 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	After a few hours sleep, Ripken opened his eyes and immediately  
had a horrid thought. 
</P>
<P>
	``You wake up and wonder if it actually did happen or you just  
dreamed it happened. It's nice to know it did happen,'' Ripken said 
Monday afternoon. ``It's a pretty darn good feeling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The record-breaking night was the consummation of a remarkable  
stretch in which he has added 149 points to his batting average 
while moving significantly closer to reaching 400 homers and 3,000 
hits over his 19-year career. He had 391 homers and 2,923 hits 
before the Orioles played Kansas City on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, best known for playing in 2,632 consecutive games, was  
batting .179 on April 20 before being placed on the disabled list 
for the first time in his career with a strained lower back. At the 
time he was also wrestling with feelings related to the death of 
his father, Cal Sr., who succumbed to lung cancer on March 25. 
</P>
<P>
	``In hindsight, there was a lot of benefit of being on the  
disabled list. It was a good break for me mentally and a necessary 
break physically,'' Ripken said. ``So when I came back, I was armed 
with a little bit better focus, a clearer head. And physically, I 
felt great. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you learn the most from some of your not-so-nice  
experiences,'' he said. ``The obstacles that were in the way, I've 
been able to step over them and step around them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since returning from the disabled list on May 13, Ripken hit  
safely in 22 of 26 games, batting .367 over that span to raise his 
batting average from .179 to .328. 
</P>
<P>
	The difference goes far beyond the new stance he broke out last  
month. Ripken valiantly attempted to play with pain in his lower 
back and anguish in his heart, but it was a futile effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fire just wasn't there,'' Orioles manager Ray Miller said.  
``Now he's having fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Batting coach Terry Crowley, who played under Ripken Sr. and has  
known the younger Ripken for years, realized early in spring 
training that Cal just didn't have his usual zest for the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know his actions, his personality and I know right away when  
Cal is feeling good. When he's feeling good, he's got a lot of 
energy and is fun to be around,'' Crowley said. ``When he's a 
little quiet, you know something's bothering him. I saw spurts of 
energy from him, but it wasn't a normal spring for Cal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, admittedly, Sunday wasn't a normal night for Ripken. His 13  
total bases tied his career high, the five runs scored set a team 
mark and it was the first time he had as many as five hits in a 
game since May 5, 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like the ball was looking bigger than normal and coming  
in a little slower, even though the speed gun said differently,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	His recent surge might turn out to be worth millions to him.  
Ripken's contract states that the Orioles must decide by the 
All-Star break whether to exercise his $6.3 million option for next 
season, or pay him $2.5 million with a chance to re-sign him at a 
lesser salary. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, Ripken looks like a steal at $6.3 million a year,  
even if he does turn 39 in August. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he did last night was sort of a culmination,'' Orioles  
first baseman Will Clark said. ``By no means was it a fluke. He's 
been swinging the bat well for weeks.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 18:17:09 </DATE_TIME>
