<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 10:30:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Session on Israel Settlements Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Israeli peace activists and delegates to a  
U.N. conference urged Israel on Monday to halt construction of 
Jewish settlements in Palestinian areas and adhere to peace 
agreements. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaker after speaker at the opening session of a U.N. meeting  
on Palestinian rights criticized Israeli settlement policies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Building of new settlements and the expansion of the existing  
ones have destructive effects on the peace process,'' said Seyed 
el-Misry, Egypt's deputy foreign minister. 
</P>
<P>
	The Israeli government, which always has ignored such  
discussions, did not send a delegate to Monday's meeting. ``We 
believe that is politicization of an issue which is basically 
humanitarian,'' said Ayellet Yehiav, a spokeswomen for the Israeli 
Embassy in Cairo. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials and delegates from member countries also started  
preparations for a meeting next month that could start a process 
for dealing with Jewish settlements under international law. 
</P>
<P>
	That meeting, called by the U.N. General Assembly, is to urge  
Switzerland to enforce a ban on settlement activity in 
Israeli-occupied territories as a violation of the Fourth Geneva 
Convention. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians maintain construction of Jewish settlements in  
traditionally Arab east Jerusalem, the West Bank and Gaza Strip 
violate the convention, which deals mainly with wartime actions. 
</P>
<P>
	The convention bans usurpation of land by an occupying power.  
But Israel, a signatory to it, maintains the territory it captured 
in the 1967 Middle East War is Jewish land. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinian Planning Minister Nabil Shaath, addressing delegates  
Tuesday, said the June 15 conference in Geneva is of ``utmost 
importance'' to the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
<P>
	``A remedy should be found to stop Israel's mutilation and  
colonization of the Palestinian territories,'' Shaath said. ``Peace 
cannot be made while confiscation of the land continues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Israel and the Palestinians have failed to hold substantive  
peace talks since Israeli settlement activity stalled discussions a 
year ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Bans Sales of Coca Cola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The government on Monday banned the  
sale of all beverages of the Coca-Cola Co. following more 
hospitalizations of children who got sick after drinking Coke. 
</P>
<P>
	Health Minister Luc Vandenbossche urged Belgians not to drink  
Coca-Cola and such Coca-Cola brands as Fanta, Sprite, Aquarius and 
Bonaqua. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, 40 students were hospitalized in Lochristi in west  
Belgium. Last week, 31 school children became nauseous in the town 
of Bornem after drinking Coca-Cola and were taken to the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Vandenbossche said doctors across Belgium have reported cases of  
illness after people drank Coca-Cola products. The nature and cause 
were under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been working and continue to work around the clock to  
identify the reasons behind the product complaints,'' said 
Coca-Cola spokesman Robert Baskin. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the incident appears to be isolated to Belgium, where  
those who became ill reported a foul odor on the outside of the 
cans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what we have are symptoms of nausea likely induced by  
the off odor. There is not evidence that the cans or the product in 
the cans have caused any ill effects,'' Baskin said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said tests run by Coca-Cola and an independent lab found  
nothing wrong with other beverages in the same vending machines. 
Additional test results were pending. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale ban for Coca-Cola came as Belgium was still reeling  
from revelations that cancer-causing dioxin had entered the food 
chain through animal feed in recent months. That led the government 
to ban sales of chicken, pork, beef, eggs and meat products. 
</P>
<P>
	Vandenbossche said on the Belgian VRT radio network that the  
Coca-Cola ban will ``remain in effect until it becomes clear what 
the origin and nature of the contamination are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week the Belgian branch of Coca-Cola announced a recall of  
2.5 million bottles of Coca-Cola after the 31 schoolchildren became 
ill after drinking from Coca-Cola bottles. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said some bottles had a quality defect, which can  
lead to symptoms such as headaches, nausea and stomach cramps. 
</P>
<P>
	The soft-drink company sent researchers to the school at Bornem  
where students fell ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola has been active in Belgium for 70 years. It has large  
bottling operations in Antwerp and Ghent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 07:00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Troops Find Atrocities  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Thousands of NATO forces in Kosovo  
began to uncover evidence of Serb atrocities against ethnic 
Albanians. In the southern town of Kacanik, British soldiers 
counted 81 graves believed to hold bodies of massacre victims. Area 
residents said the graves were recently dug for bodies that 
initially had been dumped in a mass grave. They indicated a large 
pit behind a gasoline station, which was covered with boards. 
British officials said war crimes investigators would be called in 
to examine the site, 30 miles south of Pristina. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Troops Flood Into Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- More than 14,000 NATO troops are now  
in Kosovo as part of the alliance's peacekeeping convoy. More than 
1,200 U.S. Marines are part of the deployment. The Marines took up 
positions in what eventually will be the U.S.-controlled zone of 
the province. The United States will contribute about 7,000 troops 
to NATO's 50,000-strong force. A NATO official says the deployment 
is going ``very smoothly'' and slightly ahead of schedule. 

</P>
<P>
	Unwanted e-Mail Proliferating  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- A survey of 13,000 e-mail users found  
that 90 percent of those polled received junk e-mail at least once 
a week, and 50 percent said they got ``spam'' six or more times per 
week. The Gartner Group survey also found that the longer a user 
stays with a particular Internet service provider, the more spam he 
or she is likely to receive. Examples of ``spam'' include 
get-rich-quick schemes, links to pornography, software offers, 
health promotions and investment information. America Online and 
several other leading Internet service providers have become 
leaders in the fight against spam. 

</P>
<P>
	Drunk Driving Penalties Tougher  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans behind bars or on  
probation for drunken driving nearly doubled between 1986 and 1997, 
the government reports. While the severity of punishment increased, 
arrests for drunken driving dropped during the same period -- from 
1.8 million in 1986 to 1.5 million in 1997 -- said a Justice 
Department study released yesterday. The department's Bureau of 
Justice Statistics attributed the decline in arrests in part to the 
aging of motorists, since younger drivers are more prone to drink 
and drive. In 1997, 54 percent of licensed drivers were age 40 or 
older, up from 46 percent in 1986. 

</P>
<P>
	16 Die in Chinese Factory Blaze  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- As fire engulfed an electronics factory in  
south China, managers ordered workers to save property instead of 
rescuing endangered colleagues, and 16 people were killed, a 
Chinese media report said. The fire broke out late Saturday on the 
first floor at the Zhimao Electronics Plant in Shenzhen, an 
industrial city bordering Hong Kong. Twelve women and four men were 
suffocated by the heavy smoke, and eight other people were 
seriously injured, the agency said. 

</P>
<P>
	N.D. Man Wins 'Think-Off' Contest  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK MILLS, Minn. (AP) -- A 26-year-old high school social  
studies teacher from Valley City, N.D., won the Great American 
Think-Off on Saturday with a convincing spiel that science is more 
dangerous than religion. The seventh annual event featured debate 
between four finalists selected from about 500 argumentative essays 
submitted from around the world. The Think-Off audience then 
selected a winner, who receives $500 and a contract from an 
educational book publisher. Mark Friestad cited the early 1900s 
eugenics movement, which hypothesized the human gene pool could be 
improved if weak links were removed. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 46  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The markets will likely trade cautiously today  
before hearing from Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan. Just before 10 
a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were up 46.22 to 10,536.73. Advancing 
issues on the New York Stock Exchange led decliners 1,060-593. The 
Nasdaq was down 1.05 to 2,446.83. 

</P>
<P>
	NBA Mulls Age Limits for Rookies  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NBA commissioner David Stern said he'd like to  
see an age limit for young players coming into the league. Stern 
told The Washington Post in today's editions that with more and 
more young players leaving college early, or skipping it 
altogether, to turn pro, he'd like to work with the players' union 
to impose a minimum age limit. According to the Post, the NBA would 
try to follow the lead of the NFL, which has a rule that requires 
players to have been out of high school for three years before they 
are eligible for the draft. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
