<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Troops Find Atrocities  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- British forces in Kosovo may have  
found evidence of mass killings. The troops, part of NATO's 
peacekeeping convoy in the Yugoslav province, counted 81 graves in 
one city, and say they can smell decomposing flesh. The graves are 
marked with numbers, but no names. Area residents said the graves 
were recently dug for bodies that initially had been dumped in a 
mass grave. They indicated a large pit behind a gasoline station, 
which was covered with boards. Norway is sending eight forensic 
experts to join a 60-member international team gathering evidence 
for the U.N. War Crimes Tribunal in the Hague, the National Bureau 
of Crime Investigation said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Rejects Ban on Casino Ads  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court unanimously struck down  
today the federal government's effort to protect compulsive 
gamblers from the lure of some casinos, ruling that a ban on 
television and radio advertising violates free-speech rights. 
Several justices wondered aloud about the legitimacy and 
effectiveness of the government's plan when some 240 casinos owned 
by Indian tribes in 31 states, 38 state-run lotteries and other 
gambling operations are free to advertise at will. The government 
argued that compulsive gamblers cause ``devastating social costs.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Court To Decide on Religious Schools  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide  
whether computers and other instructional materials paid for with 
taxpayer money can be used by religious schools. The decision, 
expected sometime next year, could affect the constitutional debate 
over school vouchers -- financial help from the government for 
families whose children attend religious and other private schools. 
A New Orleans-based federal appeals court struck down a federal 
program last year by ruling that providing educational materials 
other than textbooks for religiously affiliated elementary and 
secondary schools violates the constitutionally required separation 
of government and religion. 

</P>
<P>
	Mr. Whipple Returns To Sell Charmin  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Procter &AMP; Gamble is calling Mr. Whipple out of  
retirement to push sales of its Charmin bathroom tissue. Dick 
Wilson, who debuted in his first Charmin ad as Mr. Whipple in 1964, 
will return for the new campaign. Wilson, 82, made the slogan, 
``Please don't squeeze the Charmin'' a household phrase in more 
than 500 commercials over 20 years. Wilson became so familiar to 
television viewers that he was named the third best-known American 
behind former President Richard Nixon and the Rev. Billy Graham in 
a 1978 poll. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan Cautious on Productivity  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said  
today that recent increases in productivity have been a principal 
factor holding down inflation, but he cautioned that the ``growth 
of productivity cannot increase indefinitely'' and said 
``experience advises caution.'' Productivity is considered the 
crucial element in raising living standards because it allows 
employers to pay their workers more without triggering inflationary 
pressures by having to raise the cost of products. 

</P>
<P>
	Standard Planned for E-Commerce  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Some of the nation's largest computer companies,  
credit card companies and retailers are expected to announce today 
they have agreed on an Internet commerce standard that will make 
online shopping easier and quicker. It will involve the use of an 
``electronic wallet'' that allows consumers to input their names, 
addresses and credit card numbers once, instead of re-entering the 
information for every transaction. Microsoft, America Online and 
IBM will endorse a new technical format called electronic-commerce 
modeling language, or ECML, The New York Times and The Wall Street 
Journal reported today. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 84  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 84.22 to 10,574.74. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,350-1,332. The Nasdaq was down 11.42 to 
2,436.46. 

</P>
<P>
	Coles Forced To Resign From Sydney Committee  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Australian Olympic Committee member  
Phil Coles escaped expulsion from the IOC but was stripped of many 
official duties and forced to resign from the Sydney 2000 
organizing committee. Olympic leaders reprimanded the Australian 
for ``serious negligence'' in compiling secret memos on his 
colleagues but ruled today that the offense did not warrant 
expulsion. Coles was already censured in March for his role in the 
Salt Lake City bribery scandal. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

  	   	
</P>
