<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marinovich Reports to Training Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHILLIWACK, British Columbia (AP) -- A day late, quarterback Todd  
Marinovich finally embarked on his pro football comeback with the 
CFL's British Columbia Lions on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to take some time. The coaches are great. They're  
not rushing me through it,'' said Marinovich, given club permission 
to miss the Lions' first day of training camp so he could attend to 
personal matters in southern California. ``That's what's great 
about it, there's not a whole lot of pressure on me to perform 
right away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing a No. 19 jersey, Marinovich took snaps and attempted  
passes in what was his first competitive workout in five years. 
Signing a one-year deal with an option with the Lions last week, 
Marinovich is vying for the club's backup quarterback spot behind 
Damon Allen. 
</P>
<P>
	He admitted his biggest challenge is becoming familiar with the  
CFL game and its 12 players aside. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first it is a little overwhelming, but the way training  
camp's set up you go over a few things so there won't be any 
problems,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Marinovich, who turned 30 last month, first gained national  
attention when he led the Southern Cal to the 1990 Rose Bowl title. 
A first-round selection in the 1991 NFL draft, the 6-foot-4, 
220-pound Marinovich played two years with the then-Los Angeles 
Raiders before he was cut in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	He hasn't dressed for a game since 1992 and has been out of  
football since 1994 when he sustained a knee injury in the first 
week of training camp with the CFL's Winnipeg Blue Bombers. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, he was sentenced to six months in jail after pleading  
guilty to a felony charge of cultivating marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	Last April, the NFL cleared Marinovich to pursue a comeback. He  
worked out with Chicago, Seattle, New Orleans and Washington, but 
never signed an NFL contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm over it now,'' said Marinovich about not landing a spot on  
an NFL club. ``I was a little baffled looking around the league and 
seeing the talent, but at least now I've got a chance to play 
somewhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marinovich is one of four quarterbacks in camp after Justin  
Vedder, from the University of California product, was suspended 
for leaving the team before camp opened. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 10:31:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colombians Flee Rebel Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LA PISTA, Colombia (AP) -- It had been rebel territory for as  
long as most could remember. Guerrillas of the Revolutionary Armed 
Forces of Colombia levied taxes, built roads, ran child care 
centers and meted out gun-barrel justice to those accused of 
collaborating with the government. 
</P>
<P>
	But the murderous debut of right-wing death squads in the vast  
jungle known as Catatumbo transformed the political landscape in 
this corner of northeastern Colombia and sent hundreds of terrified 
residents fleeing into neighboring Venezuela. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 29, according to human rights workers and villagers,  
about 150 armed men in camouflage fatigues mounted a roadblock on a 
rural highway and forced dozens of vehicles to stop. 
</P>
<P>
	Lists in hand, they ordered motorists and bus passengers to show  
identification. Anyone whose name appeared on a list was ordered to 
lie face down on the ground and was shot in the head, the accounts 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had no compassion with anyone. They murdered in cold  
blood,'' said a 54-year-old man who identified himself only as 
Luis. He said he witnessed the killing of eight people that day and 
escaped by running into the jungle. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebels, landowner-backed paramilitary groups and the army are  
still fighting for control of the Catatumbo River valley, where 
guerrillas have been the de facto government and where the economy 
depends on the cultivation of coca, the raw material for cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	A week ago, Venezuela repatriated more than 2,000 Colombians who  
had fled the violence. Most of the refugees were trying to get to 
the Colombian city of Cucuta, but couldn't because the paramilitary 
squads blocked the roads. 
</P>
<P>
	Fearing for their lives, Catatumbo residents are still streaming  
into Venezuela by foot and canoe, braving swamps, rugged terrain, 
heat and armed irregulars. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, 600 people, most of them from La Pista, petitioned  
Venezuela for refuge. They were sent back to Colombia over the 
weekend, despite protests from human rights workers worried about 
their safety. Venezuelan officials said the refugees were 
repatriated after reaching a deal with Colombia providing them with 
protection, and that they went back voluntarily. 
</P>
<P>
	The exodus underscores how the effects of Colombia's worsening  
35-year-old civil war have begun to spill into neighboring 
countries, despite renewed efforts to start peace talks. 
</P>
<P>
	It also shows how paramilitary squads, created nearly two  
decades ago to fight leftist rebels, are gaining ground in 
Colombia, inflaming the armed conflict in one of the world's most 
violent countries. 
</P>
<P>
	No one knows for sure how many have died in the past two weeks,  
but Venezuelan Foreign Minister Jose Vicente Rangel put the number 
of dead civilians at 80. Peasants say there are several mass 
graves. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez called the situation  
in Catatumbo ``a mini Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ruben Zamora, regional commander of the Revolutionary Armed  
Forces, told The Associated Press that his group would ``fight to 
the very end'' so life in Catatumbo can ``return to normal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Normal'' in these parts means rebel rule.  
</P>
<P>
	The guerrillas charge taxes on each pound of harvested coca leaf  
and settle property disputes. When the rebels stage one of their 
periodic bombings of Colombia's main oil pipeline -- sometimes 
spilling thousands of barrels of crude into the Catatumbo River -- 
rebel commanders tell oil company supervisors whom to hire for the 
cleanup. 
</P>
<P>
	Ever since last month's paramilitary offensive, schools in the  
Catatumbo village of La Pista have been closed. Food is scarce, and 
most people have chosen to flee to safer ground. 
</P>
<P>
	In La Gabarra, the village hit hardest by paramilitary violence,  
hooded men wearing the death squads' trademark armband were seen 
roaming the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	A message spray-painted on a wall and signed by a paramilitary  
group said, ``We have arrived to stay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The displacement of people will continue because the  
paramilitaries are advancing with the support of the armed 
forces,'' charged Zamora, the rebel commander, who granted an 
interview at a jungle location he requested not be disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	As he and five other rebels spoke, a peasant in a canoe carried  
coca leaf down a river and in the distance, entire families trudged 
through the jungle in their quest to reach Venezuela. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people are terrorized,'' Zamora said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
