<DOCNO> APW19990614.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 08:20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers' Sanctions Appeals Limited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawyers sanctioned by a federal judge for  
misconduct cannot appeal the penalty until the case is over, even 
if they no longer are involved in the dispute, the Supreme Court 
ruled today. 
</P>
<P>
	The unanimous decision said a Kentucky lawyer acted too soon in  
appealing a penalty she was ordered to pay for violating a judge's 
orders during a wrongful-death case. 
</P>
<P>
	An appeal can be filed only after the underlying case is over,  
the justices said. 
</P>
<P>
	``To permit an immediate appeal from such a sanctions order  
would undermine the very purposes'' of a federal trial rule, 
Justice Clarence Thomas wrote for the court. That rule ``was 
designed to protect courts and opposing parties from delaying or 
harassing tactics'' during pretrial fact-finding. 
</P>
<P>
	Generally, appeals cannot be filed while a case still is  
pending, although there are some exceptions. For example, someone 
who claims legal immunity from a lawsuit is allowed to file a 
pretrial appeal when a judge has denied immunity and ordered the 
case to trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Appeals courts had split over whether lawyers could appeal  
sanctions against them while the underlying case was continuing. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's decision upholds a federal appeals court decision that  
dismissed attorney Teresa L. Cunningham's appeal of a $1,494 
penalty she had been ordered to pay. 
</P>
<P>
	Cunningham, of Florence, Ky., filed a wrongful-death lawsuit in  
September 1995 on behalf of Darwin Lee Starcher after his son, 
Casey, committed suicide while in the Hamilton County Jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Disputes arose during pretrial fact-finding when Cunningham had  
difficulty responding to requests for information by the county's 
lawyers. The county asked the judge to sanction her for failing to 
comply with the judge's orders. 
</P>
<P>
	The county also sought to have Cunningham disqualified from the  
case on grounds she was a potential witness. She had spoken to jail 
officials about Casey Starcher's psychiatric condition a few days 
before his suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal magistrate judge ruled that Cunningham had violated  
his order on the fact-finding schedule and directed her to pay 
$1,494 in attorneys' fees to the county. The magistrate also 
ordered her removed from the case because she might be a witness. 
</P>
<P>
	Cunningham appealed the sanction, but the 6th U.S. Circuit Court  
of Appeals ruled she could not appeal until the wrongful-death case 
was resolved. The issues in Cunningham's appeal of the sanctions 
were too closely related to the underlying case, the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Cunningham's appeal was pending, the wrongful-death case  
went forward with another lawyer. A lower court granted judgment to 
the county, and Starcher's family appealed that ruling to the 6th 
Circuit court. However, Cunningham did not file a new appeal of her 
sanctions based on the judge's ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the Supreme Court ruled that Cunningham filed her appeal  
too early. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas noted that a sanctions order is different from a ruling  
that someone is in contempt of court, which is intended to force 
someone to comply with a court order. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Cunningham vs. Hamilton County, 98-727.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
