<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Popovich in Control in San Antonio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- This was supposed to be a good day for the  
San Antonio Spurs. It was December 1996 and David Robinson was 
returning from an injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Leave it to Gregg Popovich to kill the mood.  
</P>
<P>
	Popovich, the general manager, fired coach Bob Hill before that  
night's game in Phoenix. He appointed himself coach, and it was 
hardly a popular decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was made with a lot of thought and a lot of counsel and a  
lot of heartache,'' Popovich explained at the time, admitting the 
scenario looked ``quite self-serving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Popovich was never one to let on that he worried what others  
thought of him. The same holds true today. 
</P>
<P>
	As San Antonio heads into the NBA Finals on Wednesday against  
the New York Knicks, Popovich is doing his job in typical 
no-nonsense fashion. Sometimes brash, always disciplined, he is 
leading the Spurs further in the playoffs than they've ever gone 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pop has stayed on us,'' guard Mario Elie said. ``Pop just  
wants us to get better every day, and he's been doing a good job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The way the Spurs marched into the championship series -- losing  
only one game to Minnesota in the first round then sweeping the Los 
Angeles Lakers and Portland Trail Blazers -- demonstrated Popovich's 
workmanlike approach. 
</P>
<P>
	Popovich got his early basketball experience in the military,  
playing at the Air Force Academy. Appropriately, he was team 
captain. While serving a five-year military commitment afterward he 
toured Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union as part of the U.S. 
Armed Forces team. 
</P>
<P>
	Popovich later was an assistant coach at Air Force before  
becoming head coach at Pomona-Pitzer in Claremont, Calif. He worked 
as an assistant in the NBA under Larry Brown at San Antonio and Don 
Nelson at Golden State. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Nelson, now coach and general manager of the Dallas  
Mavericks, Popovich still holds both jobs with the Spurs. He says 
it's a big help to have a strong staff on both the coaching and 
management sides. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to be able to delegate and trust people and let them  
do their jobs. My staff allow me to do that,'' Popovich said. 
``It's run pretty smoothly for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Popovich hints he might not always want both titles.  
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe over time it's something you wouldn't want to do anymore  
just because no matter what, it does take up a lot of your 
concentration,'' he said. ``So I think in time I might want to get 
rid of that responsibility and enjoy life a little bit more, 
maybe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spurs chairman Peter Holt has been negotiating an extension on  
Popovich's three-year contract, which ends after next season. 
Popovich is paid $1.1 million this season and $1.2 million next 
season, the San Antonio Express-News reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Popovich struggled through a public relations nightmare after  
firing Hill, then led the Spurs to the franchise's worst record 
that season (20-62). He redeemed himself in the summer of 1997 when 
the Spurs won the NBA Draft lottery. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Duncan was the top prize. With the 7-footer from Wake Forest  
on board and Robinson recuperating, the Spurs were on the mend and 
on the way toward winning again. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1997-98 season, the Spurs went 56-26 and set the league  
record for best turnaround in a season. San Antonio advanced to the 
Western Conference semifinals before getting ousted by Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, Popovich added playoff-tested veterans Elie, Steve  
Kerr and Jerome Kersey to the mix. After a 6-8 start and 
speculation that Popovich might be fired, the Spurs went on a tear 
in March and finished the rest of the regular season 31-5. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even the superstars, Pop gets on both of them, Tim and Dave.  
... We accept it and just move on and try to do better,'' Elie 
said. ``Nobody talks back to Pop. He's in charge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Popovich has nothing but praise for his players.  
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of people who could take this group to the  
finals,'' he said. ``It's a hell of a group of guys.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
