<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Chief Warns on Hasty Regulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- IBM Chairman Louis Gerstner Jr. warned  
Congress on Monday against hastily enacting legislation to govern 
the fast-changing technology industry, saying that policies rushed 
into place today could become obsolete quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerstner, speaking at the Joint Economic Committee's High Tech  
Summit, said the rise of networks that connect people around the 
world already has begun to transform education, business and 
government. But he estimated that this process is only about 
one-sixth of the way complete, and that more information is needed 
to develop a model for public policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a grave error to think the Internet and e-business will  
develop under the kind of regulation we applied to the phone system 
back in the days when coal and steel were determinants of a 
nation's greatness,'' Gerstner said. ``This means we have to be 
patient and thoughtful before rushing to enact new legislation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Government does have a role to play, even taking the lead on  
such issues as tax policy, the IBM chief said. In other areas, such 
as electronic commerce, government and industry should work 
together to come up with an approach that balances the interests of 
business and society. 
</P>
<P>
	``Building this kind of market-based environment implies that we  
will allow our respect for free market economies to work wherever 
possible,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other technology leaders expressed their support for ways the  
government could assist the industry, particularly on the issue of 
liability for Y2K computer problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig Barrett, Intel's chief executive officer, backed a Senate  
bill that would give companies 90 days to fix Y2K glitches before 
lawsuits can be filed. The legislation would also encourage 
mediation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our main issue is that we not clog up the courts and tie down  
the industry with frivolous litigation,'' Barrett told the 
committee via a video hookup. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., with the help  
of Democratic Sens. Ron Wyden of Oregon and Christopher Dodd of 
Connecticut, would limit class action lawsuits and ensure that most 
companies are liable only for the proportion of the damage they 
cause. It would also set punitive damage caps for companies with 50 
or fewer employees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
