<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 15:10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Wet weather moved into parts of the Northeast and the Plains,  
while the West enjoyed mostly fair and dry conditions Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain and thunderstorms pushed into the Northeast, eastern Ohio  
Valley and Tennessee Valley. Coastal areas of the Northeast were 
cloudy and had scattered rain because of a low pressure system 
spinning off the New Jersey shore. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers also dampened the lower Mississippi Valley and Texas.  
Heavier thunderstorms were expected in western Texas, where some 
flooding was possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong to severe thunderstorms were expected in the eastern  
parts of Wyoming and Colorado, into South Dakota and Nebraska. 
Damaging winds, large hail and heavy rainfall were likely. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than the showers over the northern Rockies, fair and dry  
weather dominated in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest mid-afternoon high in the Lower 48 was recorded in  
Gila Bend, Ariz., where it was 101. The low was 36, in Stanley, 
Idaho, and Grand Forks, N.D. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
