<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Short-Term T-Bill Interest Rates Up / T-Bills  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury  
securities rose in Monday's auction to the highest level in roughly 
10 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department sold $7.50 billion in three-month bills  
at a discount rate of 4.620 percent, up from 4.510 percent last 
week. An additional $7.51 billion was sold in six-month bills at a 
rate of 4.855 percent, up from 4.760 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-month rate was the highest since Sept. 21, 1998, when  
the bills sold for 4.635 percent. The six-month rate was the 
highest since Aug. 24, 1998, when the rate was 4.940. 
</P>
<P>
	The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors  
-- 4.753 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling 
for $9,883.20 and 5.059 percent for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,754.60. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the  
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index 
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 5.12 
percent last week from 5.08 percent the previous week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
