<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 07:00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> California Birthday Party May Be a Bust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PLACERVILLE, Calif. (AP) -- It's raining on California's  
sesquicentennial party. 
</P>
<P>
	At a barbecue to celebrate the state's upcoming 150th birthday,  
water beads on purple tablecloths, a misty wind stirs the pine 
trees and no one seems surprised. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very fitting,'' said a soggy Bryan Barr, a member of the  
state sesquicentennial commission. ``All these events and most of 
our efforts have gotten rained on in some way or another. We can 
only hope it eventually stops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It hasn't yet. Despite the state's appropriation of $2.9 million  
in taxpayer money and pledges of at least $2 million from corporate 
sponsors, California's efforts to celebrate its big birthday have 
been drowned by bad management, politics and apathy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Legislature's budget committee voted June 1 to shut down the  
commission and give its $963,000 budget to local celebrations, a 
powerful suggestion that state government no longer wants to put on 
the party. 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't the case in 1994, when Gov. Pete Wilson envisioned a  
2 1/2-year-long celebration of California's Sept. 9, 1850, statehood 
day. He created the sesquicentennial commission to manage it. 
</P>
<P>
	The party started in January 1998 with a festival celebrating  
the 1848 discovery of gold. But it fizzled this year after the main 
event, a race of tall ships from San Francisco to San Diego, was 
axed and efforts to commemorate the '49ers gold rush yielded only a 
handful of small events. 
</P>
<P>
	Fund raising has been a problem from the beginning. Last year,  
the commission was restructured after a legislative task force 
accused it of wasting state funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislature committee finally eliminated the commission from  
the budget after cancellation of the $4.8 million regatta. The full 
Legislature may vote on the budget this week. 
</P>
<P>
	At the barbecue in the Sierra Nevada foothills, news of the  
latest decision was received with nods and smiles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Heck with 'em,'' said Ray Nutting, 39, an El Dorado County  
board member and fourth-generation Californian. ``The state needs 
to get out of the way and let people be who they are. The only way 
they are going to be successful is to let local people carry the 
sesquicentennial ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, at a time when organizers have donned pins asking  
``Sesqui-what?'', some wonder if communities will rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Passion for the past is typical of northern Californians  
surrounded by the lore of the gold rush, but less common hundreds 
of miles to the south where fellow Californians are steeped in the 
history of the Spanish and Mexican missions of the 1700s, said Ken 
Owens, a history professor at California State University in 
Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are also hundreds of thousands of people who are too new  
to this state to even care,'' Owens said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Californians would simply rather not look back, said Jorgi  
Boom, a public relations consultant for the Rumsey band of Wintune 
Indians, the Jackson band of Mi-Wuk and eight other tribes. 
</P>
<P>
	California's American Indian population was decimated by the  
gold rush, Boom said. Tens of thousands died of settler-borne 
diseases such as smallpox or were slaughtered or forced into 
slavery. 
</P>
<P>
	The reluctance of California officials to trumpet the state  
compounds the apathy problem, said David Glassberg, a history 
professor at the University of Massachusetts, Amherst, who is 
studying Californians' attitude toward their history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some leaders fear that promoting California may bring a  
backlash of criticism over controversial issues like the rundown 
highways, overcrowded universities, racial issues and the 
environment,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Or the sesquicentennial itself. Some observers wonder if anyone  
is willing to take responsibility for such a troubled event. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Assembly Democrats accused the sesquicentennial  
commission's head, Republican Secretary of State Bill Jones, of 
mismanagement. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones canceled the tall ships race in February and squandered  
money on a Rose Parade float and performance art, their report 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, a possible candidate for governor in 2002, called the  
report ``a political hit piece.'' Democratic Gov. Gray Davis 
ignored his pleas for support at a critical time in fund raising, 
he said. Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante said the committee's 
performance under Jones was ``embarrassing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis is now looking at the sesquicentennial to see whether  
``lemonade can be made from lemons,'' Bustamante said. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, tall ships that arrange trips a year in advance  
could not cancel as quickly as California officials, organizers 
said, and six ships from as far away as Indonesia are expected next 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Clemente-based Nautical Heritage Society is spending  
$75,000 to make sure some sort of event greets them. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
