<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Prices Rise on Strong Dollar / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose Monday, recovering from a  
plunge Friday with some help from a rise in the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 3/4 point,  
or $7.50 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, fell to 6.09 percent from 6.16 percent late 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds recovered from much of their losses Friday after the Bank  
of Japan intervened in foreign exchange markets to stem the rise of 
the yen, which helped the dollar rise. A strong dollar often helps 
lift the value of Treasury bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were up between 3/32 point and 1/8 point, and intermediate maturities 
were up 7/32 point to 15/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a 
financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.73 percent as the  
discount rose 0.01 percentage point to 4.61 percent. Six-month 
yields were 5.04 percent, as the discount fell 0.03 percentage 
point to 4.85 percent. One-year yields were 5.09 percent as the 
discount fell by 0.03 percentage point from late Friday to 4.84 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, was unchanged at 4.75 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds was unchanged at 119 1/16. The average yield 
to maturity was also unchanged at 5.54 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
