<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Up 72.82 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed mixed Monday as a bond market  
rally pushed blue chips higher, but poor-performing Internet shares 
carried the Nasdaq composite index lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 72.82 to 10,563.33 after  
dropping 309 points last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 0.36 to 1,294.00, while the  
technology-dominated Nasdaq fell 49.57 to 2,398.31. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow's rise was its first in five sessions, and came as  
investors, perhaps less worried about interest rates than they were 
last week, picked up economically-sensitive stocks such as General 
Electric, which rose 2 13/32 to 103 3/4, and DuPont, up 2 7/8 to 70 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock investors were heartened by the first rally in the bond  
market in two weeks. Bonds rose after the Bank of Japan intervened 
in the global currency markets by buying dollars to slow the 
advance of the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The stronger dollar in turn made U.S. Treasury bonds more  
attractive to overseas investors and triggered buying that reduced 
the yield in the benchmark 30-year bond from Friday's 6.16 percent 
to 6.09 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, comments by Fed Vice Chairwoman Alice Rivlin helped  
ease concerns that the Fed will increase interest rates at its June 
29-30 meeting of its Open Market Committee. Rivlin said inflation 
worries in the United States are exaggerated. 
</P>
<P>
	Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan was silent about the Fed's interest  
rate policy during an appearance before Congress. His remarks had 
no effect on trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial markets have been focused on interest rates since  
the Fed warned May 18 it was leaning toward an increase to prevent 
the strong economy from driving up inflation. The stock market was 
rattled by the prospect of higher borrowing costs eroding corporate 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	But Monday's bond market rally gave a lift to some technology  
and financial services shares, which, sensitive to interest-rate 
fluctuations, had taken a pounding on Friday. IBM rose 1 3/16 to 
115 1/2 and J.P. Morgan rose 5/16 to 126 9/16. Both are Dow 
components. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're seeing is simply a low volume bounce off an  
oversold market, with a strong dollar and a good bond market,'' 
said Charles Pradilla, chief investment strategist at SG Cowen 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	But Internet shares were down sharply, led by America Online,  
down 9 3/8 to 90 1/8, and Amazon.com, off 13 13/16 to 92. Online auction 
company eBay skidded 29 7/8 to 136 after last week's shutdown of the 
service because of computer problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks are hurting because of their high valuations,  
which makes them more vulnerable should the Fed increase interest 
rates, Pradilla said. Further, eBay's technical problems and 
concerns about AOL's subscriber growth have a domino effect on the 
entire sector. 
</P>
<P>
	``Internet stocks are getting pummeled,'' said Larry Rice, chief  
investment officer at Josephthal &AMP; Co. ``There's just too much 
supply and the quality of internet offerings has been declining.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest Communications, the No. 4 U.S. long-distance phone  
company, fell 10 3/4 to 34 1/8 after making a bid to buy U S West Inc. 
and Frontier Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West rose 3 1/8 to 58 and Frontier rose 1 15/16 to 57 3/8.  
</P>
<P>
	If the Qwest bid were to succeed, it would block a competing  
offer from Global Crossing, which closed down 3/8 to 50 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other Dow stocks, Minnesota Mining &AMP; Manufacturing was up  
3 5/16 to 89 1/4 and Union Carbide rose 2 5/16 to 53 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a margin of about 4 to  
3 on the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,314 up, 1,706 down and 541 
unchanged. Composite volume totaled 813.16 million shares, down 
from 838.59 million on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 0.10 to 619.60, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.13 to 762.69. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.48 at 431.53  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.06 percent.  
Germany's DAX index was up 0.32 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was 
down 0.8 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.39 percent. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
