<DOCNO> APW19990614.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 05:30:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Compaq Offers New Storage Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Compaq Computer Corp. today unveiled a high-speed  
backup process for network systems, which officials say will reduce 
the time it takes some companies to protect data from hours to 
seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	The virtual replicator takes a ``snapshot'' of a company's data  
on a Windows NT system, then allows the network to continue 
operating normally while it backs itself up. 
</P>
<P>
	While such processes have been available for large mainframe  
systems, Howard Elias, general manager of the company's storage 
products division, said Compaq has developed the technology for 
systems of all sizes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody offers this at a low cost,'' Elias said.  
</P>
<P>
	Dave Hill, an analyst at the Aberdeen Group, applauded Compaq's  
ongoing effort to advance its storage division. 
</P>
<P>
	``Virtual disks, storage pools, and snapshots are key  
ingredients that allow customers to move closer to realizing the 
full potential of storage area networks,'' Hill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues associated with Windows NT storage are expected to grow  
from $6.2 billion in 1998 to $25.7 billion in 2003, according to an 
analysis by Dataquest Inc. Compaq currently holds about half of 
that market. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq's $3.1 billion in NT storage revenues last year accounted  
for about 10 percent of revenues for the entire company, best known 
for being the world's largest personal computer maker. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashok Kumar, an analyst for Piper Jaffrey Inc., said it's  
important for Compaq to maintain its huge presence in the storage 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look in aggregate for every dollar in hardware  
spending, there's $2 or $3 spent on storage,'' Kumar said, adding 
that continued advancement in storage is vital because ``they've 
got Dell nipping at their heels and can't afford to look back.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tattooed Barbie Leads to Complaints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- Despite a handful of complaints,  
tattooed Barbie will not be grounded. But her friends will be free 
of body art. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel said it received about a dozen complaints over tattooed  
Butterfly Art Barbie, a doll introduced last year with a small 
butterfly tattoo on her stomach. The package includes stick-on 
tattoos for young girls. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel, the nation's largest toymaker, has not halted production  
on Butterfly Art Barbie, which is selling well, Mattel Inc. 
spokeswoman Lisa McKendall said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	But she said the complaints prompted Mattell to abandon plans to  
include tattoos and nose piercing on this spring's Generation Girl 
dolls, a line of dolls for older girls that includes Generation 
Girl Barbie and her friend Chelsie. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
