<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bermuda Issues Tropical Storm Watch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The first storm of the Atlantic hurricane season  
headed northwest Monday across the north Atlantic, prompting a 
tropical storm watch for Bermuda. 
</P>
<P>
	Tropical Storm Arlene had winds of 45 mph, down from 50 mph  
earlier in the day and 60 mph Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm is expected to miss the United States by curving away  
into the open ocean before reaching the coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the East Coast is in the future of this storm,''  
hurricane specialist Miles Lawrence said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the storm was on track toward Bermuda, which could feel  
high winds by Tuesday night if the storm does not change course. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 p.m. EDT, Arlene's center was about 255 miles southeast of  
Bermuda. It was moving northwest and was expected to continue in 
that direction at 5 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms in this part of the Atlantic often turn toward the  
northeast and die at sea as they enter cooler waters, which 
discourage development. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Cohen, Albright To Meet Russians  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Clinton administration officials said today  
that the relatively small Russian contingent at the Pristina 
airport won't affect NATO's overall peacekeeping plans in Kosovo. 
Secretary of State Madeline Albright said the Russians understood 
and accepted NATO's insistence on a unified command structure in 
Kosovo. Albright and Defense Secretary William Cohen made plans 
today to meet Russian officials to thrash out Moscow's disputed 
peacekeeping role in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Peackeepers Spread in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Thousands of NATO peacekeepers  
spread out today across Kosovo on a mission to secure the province. 
Evidence of atrocities committed by the Serbs was uncovered as the 
peacekeepers moved about Kosovo. Serb forces complying with the 
pullout ordered by NATO to end the 78-day air war mixed in with 
civilians fleeing in columns up to 500 vehicles long. Some ethnic 
Albanian homes were set ablaze by Serb troops leaving Kosovo. 
Officials said about 15,000 allied troops had entered Kosovo at 
this time. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush: No Litmus Test on Abortion  
</P>
<P>
	NEW CASTLE, N.H. (AP) -- Supreme Court nominees will not have to  
pass any anti-abortion litmus test if he is elected president, 
George W. Bush said today. He also pledged to uphold the dignity of 
the presidency. Bush visited New Hampshire on a campaign swing for 
the GOP nomination. He said he was determined not to raise 
corporate and income taxes and eager to work with the 
Republican-led Congress. The Republican front-runner also said he 
was opposed to racial quotas and preferences and concerned about 
the Kosovo peace implementation plan. 

</P>
<P>
	Steel, Oil, Gas Bailout in Senate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A proposal to provide more than $1 billion  
worth of taxpayer-backed loans for domestic steel, oil and gas 
companies faces a fight in the Senate this week. Senate Majority 
Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla., is heading an effort to prevent the 
Senate from even debating the legislation. A showdown vote is 
scheduled for tomorrow, in which supporters of proposed loans will 
have to muster 60 votes for the measure to survive. 

</P>
<P>
	Banks To End Sales to Telemarketers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Big banks are coming under pressure to give up  
a lucrative part of their business, selling customers' personal 
data to telemarketers, as state officials and House lawmakers take 
tough actions aimed at protecting financial privacy. Federal law 
doesn't prohibit banks from selling customers' personal data, but 
prohibits the sharing of information obtained from a third party, 
such as a credit bureau. Banks often provide the data -- such as 
addresses, phone numbers, birth dates, Social Security numbers, and 
checking and credit card account information -- to telemarketing 
firms and other companies in exchange for commissions on sales to 
consumers. 

</P>
<P>
	Doctors See More Diabetes in Kids  
</P>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Type 2 diabetes, long thought to be a  
disease that only affected adults, is being diagnosed in 
startlingly high numbers of children, doctors say. Diabetes is the 
leading cause of blindness, kidney failure and amputations in the 
United States and kills 180,000 a year. It also can lead to heart 
problems. Obesity is an indicator parents should watch for, doctors 
say. ``Children are so much less active than they used to be,'' 
said Ronald B. Goldberg, a diabetes specialist at the University of 
Miami. ``And exposed to our western type diets, they're putting on 
weight at alarming rates.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Up 72.82  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, as a bond market rally  
pushed blue chips higher and the Dow industrials closed up 72.82 to 
end at 10,563.33. Declining issues on the New York Stock Exchange 
led advancers 1,683-1,306. The Nasdaq was down 49.58 to 2,398.30. 

</P>
<P>
	Tattooed Barbie Leads to Complaints  
</P>
<P>
	EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- The tattooed Barbie won't be forced to  
cover up her body art, but any ink for her friends in the Mattel 
doll line is now strictly prohibited. Mattel said it received about 
a dozen complaints over tattooed Butterfly Art Barbie, a doll 
introduced last year with a small butterfly tattoo on her stomach. 
The complaints prompted Mattel to abandon plans to include tattoos 
and nose piercing on this spring's Generation Girl dolls, a line of 
dolls for older girls that includes Generation Girl Barbie and her 
friend Chelsie. 

</P>
<P>
	Valentine To Talk With NL President  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- New York Mets manager Bobby Valentine expects  
to talk to NL president Len Coleman tomorrow about his two-game 
suspension for returning to the dugout in disguise after being 
ejected. Valentine was ejected by plate umpire Randy Marsh in the 
12th inning of a game last Wednesday for arguing a catcher's 
interference call on Mike Piazza. Valentine's suspension is on hold 
during his appeal. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
