<DOCNO> APW19990614.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 08:10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Opens Campaign Account </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton has set up a bank  
account and has begun depositing checks sent in by supporters for a 
New York Senate campaign, her top adviser said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Harold Ickes, a former White House deputy chief of staff  
advising the first lady on her possible Senate race, said he was 
not certain how much money had already come in. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really dribs and drabs, an inconsequential little amount  
of money,'' Ickes said, adding that checks didn't begin arriving 
until last week. ``She hasn't done anything in terms of making 
fund-raising calls yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ickes said he expected Mrs. Clinton to begin making such calls  
in early July, shortly after she formally creates her Senate 
exploratory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of money to raise,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Estimates of the bankroll needed to be competitive in the race  
for the Senate seat being vacated next year by Democrat Daniel 
Patrick Moynihan have ranged from $15 million to $20 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The race is being eyed on the Republican side by New York City  
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, among others. Mrs. Clinton is expected to 
have no real competition for the Democratic nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Ickes said he wasn't aware of the technical aspects of creating  
the campaign bank account, but said ``legally you can do that prior 
to actually filing the exploratory committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Creation of an exploratory committee allows a prospective  
candidate to raise and spend money for campaign-like purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	Ickes said that heading up Mrs. Clinton's fund-raising operation  
would be Terence McAuliffe, President Clinton's chief fund-raiser 
in 1996, and Laura Hartigan, who was McAuliffe's chief deputy then. 
</P>
<P>
	Gabrielle Fialkoff, a New York City-based operative who was in  
charge of raising money for New York City Council Speaker Peter 
Vallone's unsuccessful run for governor, has been hired by Mrs. 
Clinton's camp to concentrate on New York fund raising, Ickes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street tycoon Roger Altman, who was deputy treasury  
secretary during President Clinton's first term, also will be 
heavily involved in fund-raising work for the first lady, Ickes 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
