<DOCNO> APW19990614.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 15:00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online shopping Made Less Tedious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shopaholics just got another reason to succumb  
to the lure of the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of credit-card and technology companies said Monday they  
have agreed on a technical standard designed to make online 
shopping far easier by eliminating the tedious process of typing in 
personal data for every Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``electronic commerce modeling language'' is intended to  
allow shoppers to enter their name, billing address, credit-card 
number and other information just once. 
</P>
<P>
	If the standard is adopted by enough online retailers, it could  
remove a major barrier to online shopping. A study by the Web 
research firm Jupiter Communications last February found that 27 
percent of potential buyers gave up rather than entering 
information to make a purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies have tried without much success so far to lure  
shoppers to so-called electronic wallet systems that enable 
consumers to enter personal information they can automatically take 
with them to multiple Web sites. A main reason is that the 
thousands of online merchants use widely varying codes to complete 
online purchases, instead of a common system that all wallet 
systems can read. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the electronic standard could succeed in part  
because the companies promoting it include a number high-tech and 
financial heavyweights. 
</P>
<P>
	Included in the group are the Internet provider America Online,  
computer makers IBM, Compaq and Sun Microsystems, software maker 
Microsoft Corp. and the charge card companies American Express, 
MasterCard, and Visa. 
</P>
<P>
	Online retailers are expected to widely adopt the new standard  
at their Web sites, but that will take at least two years, analysts 
said. Banks and retailers haven't yet figured out a system for 
signing up customers to the service. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the convenience provided by the new standard, some  
consumers may be hesitant to use electronic ``wallets'' because of 
concerns their private information could be gathered for unwanted 
marketing pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, some large online stores, such as Amazon.com, may  
be slow to adopt the standard because it gives competitors the same 
easy way to sell goods and services, said Lucas Graves, an industry 
analyst with Jupiter. 
</P>
<P>
	Many large retailers already let customers enter purchase  
information just once, but their systems work only for that 
retailer's products and services. 
</P>
<P>
	``The announcement today is very significant, but only as a  
first step in the long-term evolution of the universal wallet 
standard,'' Graves said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
