<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Recalls NBA Rookie Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- He had a storied career with the New  
York Knicks, served three terms in the U.S. Senate and now he's 
running for president. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bill Bradley vividly recalls the humiliation of being a  
rookie NBA guard so inept that fans spit on him and regularly 
insulted him on the street. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, campaigning here for the Democratic presidential  
nomination, held an audience of young people in rapt attention 
Monday with the story of his pathetic rookie year with the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	It was 1967, and the New York news media had built him up into a  
savior, he told about a dozen listeners. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was going to be the guy who came in and saved the team,'' he  
recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bradley discovered he was too slow and ``failing  
miserably.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It got so bad that the audiences would not only boo me --  
18,000 people booing -- but as I left the court, they would throw 
coins at me, and occasionally they would spit on me,'' he said. 
``And when I walked through the streets of New York, I found that 
they accosted me constantly, they told me that I was no good. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very tough time,'' he told more than a dozen young  
mentors in an anti-violence program. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley dug deep to pull out of the slump, recalling the  
inspiration of teachers who instilled a work ethic and a coach who 
had warned him when he was 14: ``Remember, if you're not 
practicing, somebody, somewhere, is practicing. And if you two 
meet, given roughly the same ability, he's going to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I kept working, working, working,'' he said. Bradley went on  
to win two NBA championships with the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, facing an uphill fight against Vice President Al Gore  
for the Democratic presidential nomination, laced his speeches with 
basketball metaphors Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	He rejected suggestions that a bruising primary campaign could  
damage the Democratic Party's chances for winning the White House 
in 2000, just as it did for the GOP in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always believed, whether it was in basketball or  
politics, that competition was good -- that you're a better team in 
the finals because you've had competition,'' the former New Jersey 
senator said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about his chances against Gore, who enjoys considerable  
support in California, Bradley pointed to the Knicks' semifinal 
victory over the bigger Indiana Pacers team last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Speed and quickness are more important than bulk,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	On his first high-profile visit to California's capital since  
announcing his presidential exploratory committee, Bradley held 
question-and-answer sessions with two groups: first, disabled 
people and their caretakers, and second, a racially mixed group of 
young mentors and troubled youths. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley delivered about 15 minutes of remarks to each group and  
invoked personal experiences to establish credibility with them. 
</P>
<P>
	He told the group of home health care workers that when he was  
growing up his family had such an assistant to care for his father, 
who had calcified arthritis of the lower spine. 
</P>
<P>
	After each speech, delivered sitting in a chair with listeners  
gathered around him, Bradley played moderator, probing at the 
failings of the home health care industry and the dangers of youth 
violence. He asked questions, but mostly listened. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got to make a change now, or the future's gonna be  
chaotic,'' one young man told Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley didn't make any policy pronouncements, instead  
encouraging each group to continue its work. 
</P>
<P>
	On the third day of his 10-day California swing, Bradley took  
pains to connect with every individual in every room he entered, 
even shaking hands in a roomful of journalists before his news 
conference. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
