<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Up 51.29 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today,  
responding to a rally in long-term bonds as investors' anxiety over 
interest rates lessened. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 51.29 at 10.541.80 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was up 5.42 at 1,299.06, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
down 1.29 at 2,446.59. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were closely watching a speech by Federal Reserve  
Chairman Alan Greenspan today for clues about whether Fed policy 
makers will vote to raise interest rates when they meet June 29 and 
30. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow lost 309 points last week as 30-year Treasury bonds  
suffered their biggest weekly decline more than three months. 
</P>
<P>
	But bonds rose today for the first time in nine sessions, after  
Fed Vice Chairwoman Alice Rivlen said inflation worries in the 
United States are exaggerated. The benchmark 30-year bond rose 1/2 
point as yields fell to 6.11 percent from 6.16 percent on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest gainers in Dow stocks were Eastman Kodak, up 1 to 71  
11/16 and DuPont, up 1 5/8 at 68 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest Communications, the No. 4 U.S. long-distance phone  
company, was down 9 3/4 to 35, after making a bid to buy U S West Inc. 
and Frontier Corp. for $66.4 billion. U S West was up 2 15/16 to 57 
13/16, while Frontier rose 2 7/8 to 58 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Qwest bid were to succeed, it would block a competing  
offer from Global Crossing, which fell 1/4 to 50 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 75.93 million shares. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 1.92 to 621.42, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 3.05 to 768.87. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.06 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.32 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.3 percent, and France's CAC-40 was 
down 0.39 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
