<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Names In The Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Wayne Gretzky cleared another hurdle in making  
the Hockey Hall of Fame ahead of schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the Hall's board of directors supported an earlier  
decision by the selection committee to waive the standard 
three-year waiting process for potential inductees in Gretzky's 
situation. 
</P>
<P>
	The inductees will be announced June 23, with the ceremony  
scheduled for Nov. 22. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, the selection committee unanimously voted to make  
Gretzky the 10th player to bypass the process. Former Pittsburgh 
Penguins center Mario Lemieux was the last to do that, in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Gretzky retired at age 38 in April after his New York Rangers  
failed to make the playoffs. He left the game holding 61 league 
records. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- Grady Lewis, who invented the low-cut  
canvas basketball sneaker, and Fred Zollner, who helped lead the 
pro game into the modern age, have been nominated to the Basketball 
Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis played with the pre-NBA Basketball Association of America  
champions, the Baltimore Bullets, in 1948. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1950s, as a salesman for Converse, he experimented by  
cutting the tops off high-cut sneakers for the Harlem 
Globetrotters. The result was his low-cut canvas sneaker in the 
oxford style. 
</P>
<P>
	Zollner owned the Fort Wayne Pistons when they captured National  
Basketball League championships in 1944 and 1945. In 1952, he was 
one of the first to buy an airplane to transport his teams to away 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	He helped found and nurture the early NBA. The league's Western  
Conference trophy is named after Zollner, who died in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hall of Fame named Lewis and Zollner as veteran nominees  
Monday. Other nominees announced earlier are Kevin McHale, Dennis 
Johnson, Jo Jo White, Wayne Embry, Bob McAdoo, John Thompson, 
Maurice Cheeks, Gus Johnson, Sidney Moncrief, Chet Walker, Jim 
Phelan, Tex Winter and Morgan Wootten. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's Hall of Famers will be announced June 21.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LATROBE, Pa. (AP) -- Civic cheerleaders want to restore Latrobe's  
claim as the birthplace of pro football. 
</P>
<P>
	Latrobe is about 35 miles east of Pittsburgh, which is regarded  
as the place where players first were paid to play football. 
</P>
<P>
	Latrobe boosters said that's a mistake, citing new historical  
evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to prove this area was damaged by the NFL removing the  
claim from Latrobe,'' Latrobe resident Tony Novak said. ``We plan 
to file suit in U.S. District Court in Pittsburgh to prove it. 
</P>
<P>
	``That birthplace stuff is all over the town's letterhead,  
street signs and everything. And the NFL just took it away based on 
handwritten notes which mysteriously appeared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until 1992, football historians believe the first pro game was  
played Sept. 3, 1895, between the Latrobe YMCA and a team from the 
town of Jeanette. Records indicate that John Brallier, then an 
18-year-old quarterback who became a dentist, was paid $10 and food 
that was said to be cakes. Latrobe won 6-0. 
</P>
<P>
	Then a ledger surfaced that listed expenses of the Allegheny  
Athletic Association from a game in Pittsburgh on Nov. 12, 1892, 
including $500 plus $25 in expenses paid to William ``Pudge'' 
Heffelfinger. The Allegheny Club beat the Pittsburgh Athletic Club 
4-0 on a touchdown by Heffelfinger at a time before touchdowns 
counted for six points. 
</P>
<P>
	The old ledgers are considered to be the ``birth certificate of  
professional football,'' said Pete Fierle, a spokesman for the Pro 
Football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Allegheny club paid four people in addition to  
Heffelfinger for games in 1892 and 1893, and the Greensburg 
Athletic Association paid Lawson Fiscus to play a game in 1894. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
