<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	US To Negotiate Russia's Kosovo Role  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and Russian President Boris  
Yeltsin discussed by telephone today the standoff between Russian 
and NATO troops in Kosovo. They agreed that Secretary of State 
Madeleine Albright and Defense Secretary William Cohen would meet 
their Russian counterparts in Finland to try to work out an 
arrangement for Russian troops to serve in a NATO-commanded 
peacekeeping operation. A main worry for NATO is that independent 
Russian troops could lead to a split in Kosovo, drawing the 
minority Serb population to a Russian-controlled zone and excluding 
the ethnic Albanians. 

</P>
<P>
	Serbs Withdraw With Fury  
</P>
<P>
	PEC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- After a final spree of burning, shooting  
and alleged rapes, Yugoslav forces withdrew from Kosovo's border 
region with Albania today, whooping and giving parting mock salutes 
to a citizenry devastated by war. Some citizens in the hard-hit 
city of Djakovica say Serb paramilitary troops went on a rampage 
there Saturday, after the peace deal and two days before their 
withdrawal. Masked fighters burned buildings and raped several 
women, said Binakaj Azgon, who said his daughter was among the 
women taken away. A tally of Djakovica's dead has yet to be 
compiled; a cemetery worker said he buried as many as 200 people 
slain in mass killings of up to 70 at a time. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Chief Warns of Tech Regulation  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- IBM Chairman Louis Gerstner Jr. warned  
Congress today against enacting legislation to govern the 
fast-changing technology industry, saying that policies rushed into 
place today could become obsolete tomorrow. Gerstner said the rise 
of global networks already has begun to transform education, 
business and government. But he estimated that this process is only 
about one-sixth complete, adding that more information is needed to 
develop a model for public policy. In areas such as electronic 
commerce, Gerstner said, government and industry should work 
together to come up with an approach that balances the interests of 
business and society. 

</P>
<P>
	Road Repairs To Slow Summer Travel  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Widespread repair work on state and federal  
highways, combined with a record number of drivers expected to take 
advantage of still-low gas prices, threaten to make long-distance 
driving trips this summer more like rush-hour commuting. Experts 
warn that drivers shouldn't expect to go more than 40 miles on 
major roads without encountering a construction zone. 
Transportation officials also said the added construction increases 
the risk of traffic accidents. 

</P>
<P>
	India PM Wants Rebels Out of Kashmir  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- India's prime minister today ruled out more  
talks with Pakistan until Islamic rebels withdraw from a disputed 
mountain region of Kashmir. Atal Bihari Vajpayee's tough stance was 
a rebuff to his Pakistani counterpart, Nawaz Sharif, and came the 
same day as India said it had seized more ground in an attempt to 
secure its key northern highway. The road has been under constant 
bombardment from artillery units inside of Pakistan. India blames 
the month-old hostilities on Pakistan, accusing Islamabad of 
sending hundreds of soldiers and mercenaries over the cease-fire 
line that divides the Himalayan territory between the two nations. 

</P>
<P>
	'Jerusalem Syndrome' Hits Pilgrims  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Jerusalem Syndrome strikes with little warning:  
After a few days in the holy city, seemingly normal pilgrims 
imagine they are biblical figures, sing psalms at the top of their 
lungs, preach to passers-by or dress up in hotel bedsheets. 
Jerusalem clergymen and officials came together today to discuss 
ways to spot and deal with the mental illness, which one 
psychiatrist says may strike as many as one in 100 pilgrims and 
disrupt Jesus' 2000th birthday celebrations. About 4 million 
Christian pilgrims are expected to visit Israel and the Palestinian 
areas in 2000. The Jerusalem mental health commissioner, Dr. Yair 
Barel, who first diagnosed Jerusalem Syndrome, predicted about 
40,000 millennium pilgrims might suffer from religious delusions. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 72.50  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before the close, the Dow industrials were  
up 72.50 to 10,563.01. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,626-1,338. The Nasdaq was down 46.32 to 
2,401.56. 

</P>
<P>
	L.A. Kings Hire Andy Murray As Coach  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former NHL assistant Andy Murray, who spent  
last year coaching a high school team, was hired today as coach of 
the Los Angeles Kings. Murray, 48, was introduced at a news 
conference near the Staples Center, the new arena the Kings will 
begin playing in next season. Murray got a three-year contract, but 
financial terms were not disclosed. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
