<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC To Open Its General Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- For the first time, reporters will be  
allowed to see the International Olympic Committee at work. But 
they still won't be allowed inside. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of a commitment to openness in the wake of its worst  
scandal, the IOC announced Monday that its four-day session in 
Seoul would be carried live to reporters via closed-circuit 
television. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive board said it decided to open the meetings on the  
recommendation of its new IOC 2000 reform commission, which was 
created following the Salt Lake City vote-buying case. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC director general Francois Carrard said the committee was  
satisfied with open meetings of the world anti-doping conference in 
February and of the reform panel earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The meetings of the ruling executive board will remain behind  
closed doors, however. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrard said the deliberations of many national parliaments are  
open to the public, while those of government cabinets are normally 
closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Some IOC members have opposed the idea of opening the sessions  
on grounds that it would inhibit debate. 
</P>
<P>
	The 109th IOC session opens Thursday and members will hear  
reports from organizing committees of the 2000 Sydney Games and 
2002 Salt Lake City Winter Games. On Saturday, the IOC will select 
the host city for the 2006 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a new system, the assembly will elect a 16-member panel  
that will choose two finalists from the field of six European 
cities. Then the full membership will choose the winner by secret 
ballot. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 16:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gannett Issues Ethical Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Public distrust of the media and reader  
concerns about fair play and accuracy prompted The Gannett Co. Inc. 
on Monday to announce ethical guidelines for all 73 of its daily 
newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	Unveiled at a management conference for its publishers and  
editors, the news gathering ethics state that newspapers should 
seek and report the truth in a truthful way, serve the public 
interest, exercise fair play, maintain independence and act with 
integrity. 
</P>
<P>
	The five ethics are accompanied by guidelines that ``forbid  
lying to get a story, misstatements of identity or intent, 
fabrications, plagiarism, misleading alterations of photographs and 
slanting of the news,'' a statement released by Gannett said. 
</P>
<P>
	The principles were first outlined in March at a conference  
attended by 30 Gannett editors, reporters, corporate officials and 
outside experts. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to write them was prompted in part by a rising  
number of lawsuits challenging news gathering methods, a desire to 
encourage honest investigative reporting and news gathering 
problems last year at several newspapers, including the Cincinnati 
Enquirer, which is owned by Gannett. 
</P>
<P>
	A reporter for the Enquirer relied on voice mail messages for  
stories published last May accusing Chiquita Brands International 
Inc. of improper dealings in Central America. The newspaper later 
renounced the articles, fired the reporter and paid Chiquita more 
than $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Problems at the Enquirer were a factor in Gannett's decision to  
develop the ethics, but the problem of newspaper credibility is 
widespread and print reporters generally have received low 
performance marks on recent public opinion surveys, said Phil 
Currie, senior vice president of news. 
</P>
<P>
	The guidelines urge editors to be skeptical, provide specific  
ways to correct errors and make cautious use of unnamed sources and 
only on important news stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannett said its newspapers should strive to expose wrongdoing,  
be watchdogs of government and institutions that affect the public, 
treat people with dignity, respect and compassion and maintain an 
arm's length relationship with anyone seeking to influence the 
news. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 17:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Playoff's TV Ratings Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Thanks to the New York Knicks' surprising run to  
the NBA Finals, playoff ratings have slipped just 8 percent on NBC. 
</P>
<P>
	This season's postseason average on the network was a 6.5 rating  
and a 16 share for 25 telecasts, compared to a 7.1/19 in 21 games a 
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Many predicted even lower ratings after Michael Jordan's  
retirement and the NBA lockout, but the network was aided by the 
interest of the New York market in the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest rating of the playoffs, a 10.2/19, came during the  
Knicks' victory over Indiana in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference 
finals. The game got a 18.6/31 in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner finished with a 2.9 rating in 36 playoff games, down 9  
percent from 1998. One reason was because it only had one 
third-round game in 1999, Game 1 of the Knicks-Pacers series, which 
grabbed a 6.1. Last year, it showed three third-round contests. 
</P>
<P>
	The rating is the percentage of TV households in the nation  
tuned to a program, and each network point represents 994,000 
homes. The share is the percentage tuned to a program among those 
televisions on at the time. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 08:52:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indian Troops Battle Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- India pressed ahead today with hand-to-hand  
combat against Islamic guerrilla forces in the disputed mountain 
region of Kashmir with no political resolution to the conflict in 
sight. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif spoke with his Indian  
counterpart, Atal Bihari Vajpayee, by telephone Sunday to prevent 
South Asia from ``descending into chaos and conflagration'' over 
the Kashmir fighting, the Pakistani Foreign Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was no indication the call moved the two sides closer  
to easing the escalating conflict after talks failed this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	India blames the hostilities on Pakistan, accusing it of sending  
hundreds of soldiers and mercenaries over the cease-fire line that 
divides the Himalayan territory between the two nuclear powers. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan denies the charge, saying the guerrillas who seized  
mountain positions inside India's territory in early May are 
indigenous ``freedom fighters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Indian ground forces troops captured the summit of  
Tololing Peak, the first of the three peaks looming high over the 
abandoned town of Dras and its important military base. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldiers found the bodies of 14 infiltrators on Tololing Peak,  
said an officer who returned from the mountain after the fighting. 
He said that the victims were all Pakistani soldiers and that they 
had enough ammunition to last a year. In New Delhi, the army 
spokesman said 17 Indian soldiers were killed in the two days of 
fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	After another night of massive bombardments and close-quarters  
fighting with flame-throwers, Indian troops today closed in on the 
peak of a second mountain overlooking India's northern highway, 
field commanders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian commandos also were dropped onto the strategic Marpola  
Heights west of Dras looking over the guerrillas' supply route, 
front-line officers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kashmir is claimed by India and Pakistan, and has been the cause  
of two wars between the rival neighbors since they gained 
independence from Britain in 1947. India controls two-thirds of the 
territory, and Pakistan has the remaining third. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian Foreign Minister Jaswant Singh was in Beijing to discuss  
the fighting with his Chinese counterpart, Tang Jiaxuan. Pakistan's 
foreign minister, Sartaj Aziz, briefed Chinese authorities 
Saturday. Beijing, a close ally of Pakistan, asked Islamabad to 
solve the Kashmir dispute through talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks in New Delhi on Saturday between Singh and Aziz left both  
sides trading accusations about who was to blame for the latest 
fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan, meanwhile, accused India today of using chemical  
weapons, saying it was testing the contents of Indian shells that 
slammed into its Kashmir territory during the weekend. India has 
denied using chemical weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistani police said Sunday that Indian troops rained mortar  
shells on border villages in the Samani sector of 
Pakistani-controlled Kashmir over the weekend, killing three people 
and wounding one. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side, India said one villager was killed by  
Pakistani shelling in Kasba. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 08:52:53 </DATE_TIME>
