<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 03:10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks Flying to San Antonio Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- Shooting in a dome is different from  
shooting in an arena, which is why the New York Knicks are wasting 
no time getting to the Alamodome. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, shooting in a dome is different. The shooting  
background in domes is different, and that gives them, to me, a 
huge homecourt advantage,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	New York planned to practice at its suburban facility one more  
time today before boarding a charter flight to San Antonio that 
should arrive in the late afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Game 1 of the finals is Wednesday night.  
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs and Knicks did not play each other during the regular  
season because of the lockout-shortened schedule, so there will be 
a greater degree of unfamiliarity in this series than there ever 
has been in an NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Familiarity in the Miami series and the Indiana series,  
coaching staff-wise, was easy,'' Van Gundy said. ``This is just 
different. You don't really know a team until you compete against 
them regularly, and particularly until you compete against them in 
the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both teams think they know, but they're not really going to  
know until a couple games into the series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By then, the Knicks should also know how much of a contribution  
Larry Johnson will be able to make. 
</P>
<P>
	The co-captain's sprained right knee was causing him a lot of  
pain Sunday, although he said he'll play in the series -- even if 
it's not in Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I hate more than sitting out is being on the floor and  
not being 100 percent. Because you know you can make this move or 
guard this guy better, but there's something hampering you,'' 
Johnson said. ``Another thing is I don't want to be out there with 
a big, bulky brace on and not be able to do the things I want to 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Johnson can't play in Game 1, the Knicks would be expected to  
use a starting lineup of Chris Dudley at center, Kurt Thomas and 
Latrell Sprewell at forward and Allan Houston and Charlie Ward in 
the backcourt. 
</P>
<P>
	That would leave Marcus Camby and 41-year-old Herb Williams as  
the only big men coming off the bench since the Knicks are also 
missing 7-foot center Patrick Ewing, who was lost for the season 
with a torn Achilles tendon. 
</P>
<P>
	That size predicament had Van Gundy and his staff wondering  
whether to double-team Duncan and Robinson when they have the ball, 
as most teams do, or take their chances with single coverage on the 
Twin Towers and tight defense on the other three players. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what's going to be great to watch,'' Van Gundy said.  
``It's going to be a great, great decision for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs, meanwhile, are hoping rest doesn't lead to rust after  
their long layoff. They had a day off from practice Sunday as the 
players further enjoyed the downtime they earned by disposing of 
the Portland Trail Blazers in a four-game sweep. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio, which also swept the Los Angeles Lakers in the  
second round, hasn't lost since the second game of the first round 
against Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teams that are inconsistent, or not as good, you can exploit  
because they have weaknesses,'' Van Gundy said of the Spurs. ``But 
this team really has no weaknesses, which is why they've won 10 
playoff games in a row, which is unheard of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The archive on ``How To Beat The Spurs'' is not a voluminous  
one, which is what Van Gundy learned when he started researching 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I asked our video coordinator: `Pull up all their losses. I  
want to see the teams that beat them in the last three months.' And 
he gives me this little stack of tapes,'' Van Gundy said. ``Baaaad 
sign. 
</P>
<P>
	``They lost to Phoenix, Dallas, Sacramento in overtime and  
Minnesota. That's it since April 1,'' Van Gundy said. ``That's the 
stack. Four of 'em.'' 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio swept the two-game season series in 1997-98, but  
those Knicks were nothing like the current squad -- an uptempo, 
athletic mix who were at their best playing at a greyhound pace 
against the Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be tougher in transition against San Antonio  
because those guys run real well,'' said Camby, who provided the 
Knicks with a huge lift off the bench in the Indiana series. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Dudley: ``It definitely will be more difficult without  
Larry. He's been a huge part of our success and he's integral to 
our team, but we'll move forward if he can't play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At practice, Van Gundy showed the players a tape of the final  
seven minutes of Game 6 against Indiana and asked them to savor it 
for the rest of their lives -- but only after they forget about it 
for the next two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a special time, that's going to be a special memory,  
but hopefully there are more special memories to come,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 08:26:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Campaigns in New Hampshire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW CASTLE, N.H. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate George  
W. Bush said today he would not impose an abortion litmus test on 
his Supreme Court nominees and promised to uphold the dignity of 
the office if elected. 
</P>
<P>
	In a wide ranging news conference on his maiden trip to this key  
primary state, the GOP front-runner raised his right hand to a 
crowd of 150 reporters and said he swore an oath as Texas' governor 
to uphold the constitution and respect the dignity of the 
governorship. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a pledge I have upheld, so help me God,'' Bush said, his  
right hand still raised. 
</P>
<P>
	The twice-elected governor has said he was ``young and  
irresponsible'' when he was a young man. Now 52, Bush refused to 
say more about the topic today. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a game in Washington,'' he told a New Hampshire  
reporter who posed the question. ``It's called ``Gotcha.' It's a 
game where you float a rumor and make the candidate'' respond. 
``I'm not playing that game,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	On abortion, Bush has said he would nominate judges who strictly  
interpret the U.S. Constitution. He was asked whether he interprets 
the Constitution to allow for abortions and whether he would 
require his judicial nominees to view it the same way. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be no litmus tests, except for whether or not the  
judges will strictly interpret the Constitution,'' he said. ``I am 
not a lawyer. My job is to pick judges who are qualified to serve 
on the bench and that will be my criteria.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said later that Bush feels it is unethical to require a  
nominee to cement his or her views on any potential case before 
being nominated. But they said he would appoint conservative judges 
who hold the same general values as he. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has said he is opposed to abortion and would even support a  
constitutional amendment making the procedure illegal except in 
cases of rape, incest or to protect the woman. But he also says 
Americans don't support the measure so there is no sense in 
pursuing it. 
</P>
<P>
	On other topics, Bush:  
</P>
<P>
	--Said he opposes quotas and racial preferences, but said the  
private and public sector should be encourage to reach out to 
minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	--Promised not to raise corporate or income taxes, but did not  
extend the pledge to other taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Expressed concern about the implementation of a peace plan in  
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	--Pledged to provide more details about his agenda as the  
campaign progressed, saying he will move ``at my own timetable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor also planned to visit an elementary school  
and speak at a women's forum later today. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the Republican presidential front-runner drew more than  
300 people to an early morning address on the banks of the Atlantic 
Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic National Committee Chairman Joe Andrew crashed Bush's  
speech, pigeonholing reporters to accuse the Texas governor of 
refusing to detail his position on national issues. ``The governor 
from the Alamo state won't take a stand,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew dubbed Bush ``Curious George'' because he said the  
governor's positions are so vague. ``Nobody wants Curious George 
with his finger on the button,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew also shadowed Bush's trip to Iowa on Saturday,  
underscoring how seriously the Democratic Party is taking his 
candidacy. No other GOP candidate is getting such attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has the support of the state's leading GOP politician, Sen.  
Judd Gregg. He was announcing the names of more than 180 local 
organizers today, along with the appointment of state public safety 
director Richard Flynn to be chairman of his coordinating 
committee. Flynn is the longest-serving state department head, long 
considered a behind-the-scenes powerbroker. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush apologized to New Hampshire voters for waiting so long for  
his first trip,, saying he promised Texans he would complete the 
state's legislative session before campaigning for president. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope you understand that I'm a man of my word,'' Bush said.  
</P>
<P>
	Bush took more than 20 minutes getting to the stage, slowly  
making his way through a crowd of supporters eager to grab his 
hand. Spotting a redheaded baby in the crowd, he shouted, ``I've 
always been a sucker for baby pictures,'' then took the child from 
his mother. 
</P>
<P>
	He kissed the baby in front of a group of photographers, then  
turned on request to pose for more cameras. ``Another kiss 
governor!'' one photographer yelled. Bush eagerly consented, and 
planted another kiss on the baby's cheek. 
</P>
<P>
	Irma Pierce of Portsmouth, N.H., pulled Bush aside briefly and  
asked him to do something about the rising costs of long-term care. 
`I will,'' he replied. 
</P>
<P>
	She wasn't satisfied with his answer.  
</P>
<P>
	``But at least it's hopeful,'' she said. ``He needs to be  
formulating some plans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush announced Saturday in Iowa that there was ``no turning  
back'' from his bid for the GOP presidential nomination, in which 
he leads in the polls. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 23:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Leave for Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, leaving tonight for Europe,  
is joining with allies to launch a costly rebuilding plan for 
war-torn Kosovo and other trouble-plagued nations of southeast 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``The coming months will be a period of return and  
reconstruction,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said 
Monday. ``Our goal is a democratic Kosovo, at peace with itself and 
secure from external threats.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This won't happen overnight,'' Albright said at a White House  
briefing. ``But as President Clinton consults with his colleagues 
this week, he will do all he can to ensure that the effort is well 
launched.'' 
</P>
<P>
	European nations will bear the largest share of the financial  
burden of rebuilding, Albright said, because the United States 
absorbed the heaviest cost of the 78-day bombing campaign against 
Yugoslavia. She said that as of Monday, 13,000 to 15,000 Serb 
forces have pulled out of Kosovo and 14,000 peacekeeping troops 
have begun to deploy. 
</P>
<P>
	While the allies are digging into their pockets to rebuild the  
Balkans, Clinton has ruled out giving any help to Belgrade as long 
as Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic remains in power. 
</P>
<P>
	Departing tonight, Clinton flies overnight to Geneva to address  
the International Labor Organization on Wednesday, speaking in 
support of a convention to eradicate the worst forms of child 
labor. The measure is expected to be adopted by all 174 ILO members 
later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, the president will stop overnight in Paris for talks  
with French President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel 
Jospin. 
</P>
<P>
	From Paris, Clinton will travel to Cologne, Germany, for the  
annual summit of the world's seven wealthiest nations -- the United 
States, Germany, England, France, Italy, Canada and Japan -- and 
Russia. They will meet Friday through Sunday, discussing 
reconstruction of the Balkans, debt relief for the poorest nations 
and new global finance structures. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first two days of the summit, Russia will be represented  
by Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin. President Boris Yeltsin will 
come for the final day of talks Sunday and a private meeting with 
Clinton. National security adviser Sandy Berger said he was not 
sure why Yeltsin would not attend the first two days. ``It could be 
a question of physical stamina,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright and Berger played down U.S. unhappiness about the  
surprise deployment of Russian troops to Kosovo, ahead of NATO 
troops. She said she was confident the issue would be resolved, and 
said, ``There has not been long-term damage from this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen and Albright were to go to  
Helsinki in a few days to talk with Russian officials about 
Russia's role in peacekeeping. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said it was critical to bring the Balkans into the  
mainstream of Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``We and our Europeans allies have recognized, after our  
experience in Kosovo and earlier this decade in Bosnia, that 
isolated programs to assist individual countries in this region 
have been insufficient,'' Albright said. ``And we need to 
coordinate our resources and encourage real integration within the 
Balkans, throughout Europe and across the Atlantic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Next Monday, Clinton will attend a summit with leaders of the  
European Union in Bonn, where the Balkan discussions will continue. 
He will then fly to Slovenia for an overnight stay. Slovenia, 
Bosnia and Croatia broke away from Yugoslavia after the fall of 
communism. Slovenia now is a leading candidate to join NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's schedule calls for him to return home from Slovenia,  
but White House aides are exploring a possible stop in Macedonia to 
visit refugees or in Aviano, Italy, to salute American forces who 
took part in bombing raids and humanitarian missions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990614.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-14 05:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Look at Math, Science Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Math and science software tends to aim at the elementary school  
set. But by the time a student is wrestling with calculus or 
physics on a high school or college level, cutesy animations don't 
quite cover the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	MathSoft Inc. of Cambridge, Mass., has some decidedly un-cutesy  
software in StudyWorks Mathematics and StudyWorks Science, and both 
are worth a look as reinforcement tools. 
</P>
<P>
	The approach is three-step: 1. Understand the concepts. 2. Learn  
to use the concepts to solve problems. 3. Reinforce the concepts 
with more problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Although there is a multimedia component and an on-line  
``Collaboratory'' (a virtual study group), the emphasis is on 
education, not entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	Let's face it, it may be possible to make trigonometry, calculus  
and statistics entertaining, but it's not likely. In addition to 
those subjects, the math software offers algebra I, algebra II, 
geometry and pre-calculus and updated SAT II math preparation 
sections from Princeton Review. 
</P>
<P>
	For someone whose math skills peaked at long division and who  
hailed the arrival of pocket calculators as a godsend, the content 
was pretty tough sledding, but well presented and organized. The 
story problems were interesting and current. 
</P>
<P>
	The science product covers biology, chemistry, physics, earth  
science and statistics and also includes SAT II science preparation 
from Princeton Review. Information on each subject is presented in 
a straightforward manner with hypertext links as appropriate. Both 
packages include puzzles and games featuring the subject matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Students are unlikely to come to either package for fun, and  
those with a gift for the subjects at hand would probably become 
bored. But for most, they will provide help in a strange land that 
must be crossed to earn a baccalaureate. 
</P>
<P>
	System requirements are very modest: at least a 66-megahertz 486  
machine running Windows 3.1 or higher, eight megabytes of memory, 
doublespeed CED-ROM drive, Windows-compatible sound card and 
speakers. Use of the Internet will of course require access. I 
reviewed it on one of IBM's snazzy new Thinkpad portables, about 
which more later. Installation was competent and professional and 
the user interface was easy to understand. 
</P>
<P>
	The software carries a price of $29.95 that is modest for the  
value. It is available at software retailers or directly from 
MathSoft at http://www.mathsoft.com. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Questions and comments are welcome. E-mail via the Internet to  
lblasko(at)ap.org, or send regular mail to Larry Blasko, AP, 50 
Rockefeller Plaza, New York, NY 10020. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
