<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA To Retreat on Smog Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON AP) -- Stung by adverse court decisions, the  
Environmental Protection Agency shifted strategy today and 
announced a scaled-back plan to cut smog-causing pollution from 
electric power plants, especially coal burning plants in the Ohio 
Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	EPA Administrator Carol Browner said she remained optimistic  
about the appeal of two recent court decisions that threatened the 
agency's new air quality standards for smog and fine soot and put a 
freeze on regulations to curtail cross-state pollution. 
</P>
<P>
	But Browner told a news conference that another approach was  
needed as ``insurance'' to guarantee that drifting pollution from 
Midwest power plants into the Northeast is curtailed as planned. 
</P>
<P>
	Browner said she would pursue actions against power plants in 12  
states based on petitions that had been filed by four Northeast 
states, claiming they were being environmentally harmed by the 
drifting pollution. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the petition process, the EPA will enforce pollution  
controls with the current ozone and soot standards that are not 
under court challenge. The process also would be separate from the 
broader cross-state pollution rules that are currently in 
litigation, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Browner said she remained optimistic that the court  
rulings will be overcome, she said she believed the agency needed 
to take another approach to protect Northeast states from 
smog-causing chemicals drifting in from the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the agency will act on petitions filed by New York,  
Connecticut, Pennsylvania and Massachusetts to demand that power 
plants in the 12 states reduce emissions of smog-causing nitrogen 
oxide. 
</P>
<P>
	The petitions claimed that coal-burning power plants in Indiana,  
Kentucky, Ohio, Michigan, Pennsylvania, West Virginia, and Virginia 
were responsible for pollution drifting into the Northeast, making 
it impossible to meet federal air quality standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency action, responding to the petitions, also will  
require pollution reduction by some plants in Delaware, Maryland, 
New Jersey, New York and North Carolina because of complaints about 
drifting pollution from other states. 
</P>
<P>
	Browner said use of the petition process would curtail emissions  
less than the broader 22-state ozone transport regulation because 
it will cover only 12 states and be based on the less stringent 
ozone and soot rules, and not the tougher ones under court 
challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	While ``we are not providing as much public health protection,''  
said Browner, the action will ``ensure us we will be able to move 
forward'' in curtailing cross-state pollution into the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	She estimated the scaled-back action would reduce smokestack  
releases of smog-causing chemicals by about 700,000 tons a year, 
compared to 1.1 million tons under the broader 22-state ozone 
transport rule being challenged in court. Plants would have to meet 
the new requirements by 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not our preferred path,'' Browner said. But she said  
she had no choice but to pursue the limited petition approach 
because the courts had ``robbed us of the (other) option.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A three-judge panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the  
District of District of Columbia last month threw out the EPA's 
controversial regulation requiring tougher health standards for 
smog-causing ozone and for microscopic soot. The agency immediately 
said it would appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	A few days later, the same appeals court -- including two of the  
same judges -- ordered the EPA to halt implementation of its 
regulation to require 22 states to take action to reduce 
cross-state air pollution. That action was aimed primarily at 
curtailing emissions from the coal burning power plants in the Ohio 
Valley, whose pollution drifts into the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	While both of those regulatory actions remain in limbo, agency  
action based on the specific state petitions under a separate part 
of the Clean Air Act are not affected by the two appeals court 
rulings, EPA officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
